<TEXT>
THE Herald leader comes down strongly on the side of devolution (December 1).
In a way this is surprising. Like some other institutions in Scotland, The
Herald craves independence for itself yet denies it to the nation it serves.
In recent letters correspondents have deplored the use of the word England in
place of Britain or Scotland and, in part, have put this down to English
arrogance. In this they may be mistaken.
More likely it is simply recognition by outsiders (not just the English) of the
subsidiary position Scotland occupies inside the Union. Just as we get the
Government we deserve, so we are accorded the title that is our due.
To take another example, no-one makes the mistake of calling Ireland England.
The events that took place on St Andrew's Day are unlikely to raise Scotland's
standing in the eyes of the world. A parliament without sovereignty is not
worthy of the name.
On a day when there should be rejoicing, there is indifference; when there
should be optimism and sparkle, there is foreboding; when an inspired people
should be on the march, there is only sheltering in the rain.
D MacCallum,
33 Northfield Avenue, Ayr.
</TEXT>
