<HEADLINE>Medical council finds doctor guilty of rape and assault</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011843</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DOCTOR was yesterday found guilty by the General Medical Council of
assaulting and raping a secretary in his hotel bedroom after a disco.
The council's professional conduct committee found father of four Dr Michael
Bowles, 43, guilty of committing the offences against 35-year-old ``Miss A'' in
Quebec in June 1990.
The committee heard Dr Bowles, of Wykeham Road, Kenton, Harrow, Middlesex,
lured the woman into a lift to the 14th floor of the Concorde Hotel after
dancing with her and buying her a drink in a basement disco.
French Canadian Miss A, who was flown in from Canada to give evidence, said Dr
Bowles dragged her into his room and tried to force her to have oral sex before
raping her. Two friends of Miss A claimed to have seen her ``crying, bruised,
and upset'' after her ordeal.
Dr Bowles told the three-day hearing that Miss A had been only one of a party
of five or six people who had accepted his invitation to have a post-disco
drink in his room. All the party then left the hotel together and he went to
bed alone.
He said he had tried unsuccessfully to contact these potential witnesses -
particularly a man called Pierre - to back his version of events.
Miss A's two friends had claimed to have seen several injuries on her body and
head but the doctor's counsel, Mr Keiran Coonan QC, cited ``inconsistencies''
which he said indicated the three women's ``script'' had been unravelling.
The committee is now considering the question of serious professional
misconduct.
The committee also found Dr Bowles guilty of professional misconduct and
ordered his name to be erased from the register with immediate effect. He has
28 days to appeal.
Council barrister Rosalind Foster disclosed that Dr Bowles had jumped bail and
returned to this country after being charged with ``sexual assault'' - the
Canadian legal term for rape - on Miss A.
He was re-arrested by Scotland Yard officers in November 1993 and consented to
being extradited to Canada, where he was sentenced to 30 months detention, from
which he was released on March 18 this year.
``Dr Bowles had shown himself as unworthy to be a member of a profession which
requires total propriety in public and private life,'' she said.
</TEXT>
