<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000004</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000004</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Theatre   The Heart in Hiding, Battersea Arts Centre, London</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Carole Woddis</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975011845</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROCK idolatry is a mixture of fantasy, self-deception, escapism and parasitical
devotion. The Heart in Hiding - by two up-and-coming stars, writer/poet Glyn
Maxwell and director Andrea Brooks - is an extraordinary piece that doesn't
just pose awkward questions about the nature of the relationship between idol,
fan, and the public but gets right inside its fevered, narcissistic,
self-destructive head.
Moray Treadwell (he can be seen at Perth in very different guise in the New
Year in the old thriller, Night Must Fall) is a charismatic, crack-voiced, rock
star, Aidan, who one night disappears in the middle of a concert.
Like some twentieth-century ape man, Aidan's music is the kind calculated to
make every adolescent young female feel he's talking just at her. But is he
really? And does he want that anyway?
Pursued into oblivion by three women and a hard-nosed hack out for the story of
the century, Brooks's flashy production with its pounding score by rock
composer Charlie Round-Turner and movement by the great Lynn Seymour, sometimes
comes close to being swamped in its own emotional and musical intensity. Eva
Marie Bryer's febrile speed freak, Sash, for example, appears on the point of
combustion at any moment.
But the play grows in power as Sash, confronted with the physical reality of
her idol finds it too hot to handle and the quartet's battle for Aidan explodes
into open warfare.
Fascinating as an exploration of possession, the motor of money and identity,
Maxwell's free verse, fiery epitaph - like the work of Irving Welsh - captures
a culture and whole way of being with an authenticity that is electric.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000005</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000005</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tug-of-war debate on beef No evidence of risk but more tests ne eded</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011846</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NATION which invented the battered and deep-fried Mars Bar should have little
to say on any aspect of the food/health debate, yet we are worried about beef
and the transmission of the cattle disease BSE into the human population.
Anxiety on matters of this sort is increasingly prevalent and it is a
concomitant of knowledge or, to be more precise, a little knowledge. This does
not mean that it is a dangerous thing; rather that it is insufficient. We all
have a right to as much knowledge on matters which affect us as we can
comfortably absorb. The problem with the information available on BSE and the
human version, CJD, is that it is impenetrable to anyone other than experts,
and even they cannot agree. The general public, therefore, if it wishes to take
any sort of intelligent interest, is obliged to listen to the experts and, on
utterly inadequate information and understanding, to decide whether its
children should eat beefburgers in a fast-food chain, sausages at school, or
even a slice of roast beef for Sunday lunch. This is an intolerable imposition
and it is imposed, moreover, on those who are concerned enough about the diet
of their family to seek a sensible balance of risks and benefits.
Where are we, then, in this tug-of-war debate on one of our staple foods? There
have been worries about BSE passing through the food chain to humankind for
several years and a range of measures to prevent this happening were put in
place, and tightened up recently. These were designed primarily to prevent
certain parts of the animal arriving in the cheaper meat products, such as
beefburgers, pies, and sausages, but there are two significant problems with
the existing regulations. To begin with, they can hardly be adequately targeted
when the cause of BSE/CJD is not known. Some scientists believe that it is a
virus, although if it is, the method of transfer is not known. A major
investigation into the possibility that it is passed from mothers to offspring
is under way but it will not report until some time next year. Another group of
scientists believes that it may be a protein of a new and hitherto unsuspected
type. Here we are in the realms of the unknown and little sensible comment can
be made until a good deal more thinking has been done. The second problem with
the regulations is that they are easily and sometimes frequently flouted.
Careless handling of animal carcasses is nothing new and it persists in
abattoirs up and down the country, increasing the risk of suspect meat products
passing into the national diet.
If it is clear that legislation on the way meat is slaughtered and handled
should be tightened further, it is just as evident that the authorities must
make a more serious effort to reach the truth. A former Government health
adviser, Sir Bernard Tomlinson, backed by a number of highly reputable
scientists, says he will not eat beef pies, beefburgers, or beef liver. Others
call for an inquiry into the animal feedstuffs industry, believed to be
responsible for the initial problem when cows ate infected sheep offal. On the
other side the Health Secretary, Mr Stephen Dorrell, is happy to tell people
who eat beef that they run no known risk of contracting CJD. Both parties to
the argument are correct in the position they take. The scientists are right to
point to discrepancies and to call for further investigation and Mr Dorrell is
correct when he points to the lack of firm evidence of any connection. The
really disturbing people are those like the spokesman of a large meat market
who blamed everything on a plot by vegetarians and a supporter of the meat
industry who said that everyone should be quiet lest an important industry be
damaged. On balance, then, there is no clear evidence of risk but an urgent
need for more investigation. This will not help ordinary people with decisions
to make on their diet, save to say that beef is still a lot better for you than
a battered and deep-fried Mars Bar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
