<HEADLINE>Bedside blonde</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975011847</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOST of us have been the anxious relatives of post-surgery patients and have
listened to the professional advice of medical and nursing staff about the
timing of our first visits to our loved ones post-operatively.
Is the advice different in the large London hospital where a complete stranger
- even if a princess - can wander into a ward in the early hours of the morning
to ``work'', as she claims?
Would it not be kinder to send her car for the relatives to take them in to see
their patient next day when it is medically sensible?
I would rather see my husband through an anaesthetic haze than a strange blonde.
Isobel Marshall,
22 Bonaly Brae,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
