<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000007</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000007</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Blair's turn to blush Labour Euro-MPs back French strikers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011848</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE situation in France continues to deteriorate with no sign of an end to the
wave of strikes and protests over the Government's plans to cut welfare
benefits. If anything, the objections of a widening sector of French life
appear to have hardened in the wake of the Prime Minister's insistence that the
welfare reforms will be pushed through. Mr Juppe is in a difficult position
entirely of his own making. As a responsible Prime Minister he was undoubtedly
bound to do something about the French deficit which owes so much to a
traditionally generous welfare system, and particularly if France wishes to
meet the convergence targets for European monetary union. Yet it is odd that a
seasoned politician should have so misjudged the temper of his own people, many
of whom have a warm appreciation of the benefits of the welfare system and an
antipathy to reducing it which may have been fuelled by a glance across the
Channel.
There is a more potent reason why the French Government is in such a difficult
situation. It owes almost everything to the battle within the right-wing of
French politics for the post of President. The splits within the centre-right
led the candidates to make ever more belligerent promises about what they would
do when in office. Mr Chirac allowed his tongue to run away more than most,
particularly on his tough stance on the economy and also on his plans to cut
unemployment swiftly. The unemployment pledge was patently silly, but the
reform of the welfare system could and should have been introduced with more
consultation and in a graduated manner. Instead an attempt was made to bulldoze
it through, with the entirely predictable results which are visible on the
streets of France this morning. Ironically Mr Chirac has absented himself from
the current row, leaving its conduct to his Prime Minister.
In these circumstances the actions of Labour's Euro-MPs in unanimously backing
the French strikers will not be warmly applauded by Mr Tony Blair. No doubt he
will have his own views on the need to maintain a decent welfare system, but he
will be appalled at his Euro-MPs' decision to back widespread strikes which
stand a fair chance of dislodging Mr Juppe's Government. There is, of course, a
history of disagreement between Mr Blair and the Labour Euro-MPs, compounded by
their majority support for the retention of Clause 4. The prime mover in that
debacle was Mr Alex Falconer, the Euro-MP for Mid-Scotland and Fife, and from
the reports of yesterday's action it appears that Mr Falconer is once more the
instigator. It is good to have independent-minded MPs, particularly those who
put principle above mere party advantage. Mr Falconer is undoubtedly one of
those doughty battlers, but in embarrassing his party leader so sorely, is Mr
Falconer saying that Mr Blair's principles are not good enough? We doubt that
this is the case, but there is a distinct possibility that Labour's Euro-MPs
are somewhat out of step with the party in Britain. If so, this should be
remedied.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000008</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000008</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Borderline's artistic future</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975011849</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNTIL last Thursday night I had been on the board of directors of Borderline
Theatre Company for some 14 months.
Although I have a family and a more than full-time job as a freelance writer, I
had devoted a great deal of unpaid time to the company, attending meetings and
performances and supporting it through a major Arts Council review.
It was a hugely enjoyable and rewarding experience. This was almost wholly due
to the efforts of an artistic director who was not only committed to high
quality popular drama but also to involving the local community in the theatre
so that old and young people from all walks of life would come to see it as a
resource for them and not for some narrow elite.
John Murtagh's enthusiasm for his profession was infectious. He is a talented
director and actor but, more importantly, he is generous in imparting those
skills to amateur and professional actors alike.
It was with a sense of shock turning to disbelief that I attended the meeting
last Thursday to be presented with three ``options'', the recommendation of the
finance committee being option 2 - ie, John's redundancy (and that of the
theatre manager) with immediate effect.
It quickly became apparent that of the board members present at that meeting
only I, as vice-chair, and Mrs Winnie Goodwin, had no prior knowledge of this
recommendation.
In spite of all our objections, the proposal was overwhelmingly carried. I had
no alternative but to resign immediately, as did Mrs Goodwin.
The revised personnel infrastructure, in the administration's own words, will
consist of a chief executive, an administrator, and  a secretary as well as a
marketing co-ordinator, and an integration co-ordinator.
The only full-time theatre professional now to be employed by a company
receiving substantial public subsidy from the Scottish Arts Council is a
hard-pressed and underpaid drama worker who admirably handles schools, youth,
and special needs work.
In the documents put before the meeting it was stated - chillingly enough -
that the artistic director was ``surplus to requirements''. And this in spite
of the fact that the Arts Council review team found that ``there is a . . .
need to broaden the creative base of the company, thereby releasing more time
for the artistic director to plan and shape the artistic programme''.
Instead, Borderline now proposes to use so-called artistic associates, invited
on an ad hoc basis with no ongoing commitment to the company.
It seems clear to me as an arts practitioner that the one person a funded
theatre cannot do without is a committed and skilful artistic director.
You might question the vision or methods of an individual but the post itself
is indispensable.
Borderline has now become little more than a venue and there are surely more
worthwhile ways of spending many thousands of pounds of public money than on
the administration of such a creatively impoverished company.
Catherine Czerkawska,
38 Patna Road,
Kirkmichael, Ayrshire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000009</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000009</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Maxwell jury takes break for Christmas</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011850</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Maxwell trial came to an unexpected halt yesterday when jurors told the
judge they would feel under pressure if they were sent out to consider their
verdicts before Christmas.
The trial, now in its seventh month, was adjourned until January 3.
Lord Justice Phillips said the last thing he wanted was for them to feel under
pressure and he said their request had shown ``some wisdom''.
He had told the jury he planned to begin summing up next Monday and hoped to
finish at the end of the week, when the jury would be sent to consider their
verdicts, spending the night at a hotel.
If the jurors had not reached verdicts by December 22, they would be allowed
home to celebrate Christmas and would return to resume their deliberations on
December 27, the judge said.
Yesterday, the jury sent a note to the judge saying they were ``feeling
concerned that, after a long and complex trial, they are under pressure
regarding their deliberation process''.
The judge assured the jury that ``at this stage of the trial, and indeed
throughout, you are the most important people. I am not going to send you out
to consider verdicts if you are going to feel under pressure.''
He said he had wanted to send them out as soon as possible while counsels'
final speeches were still fresh in their minds.
However, he said if it was not possible for the jury to feel without pressure
he would sum up after Christmas.
Mr Kevin Maxwell, 36, his brother Ian, 39, and former Maxwell executive, Mr
Larry Trachtenberg, 42, deny conspiracy to defraud by misusing shares belonging
to the pension fund.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
