<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000011</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000011</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Costs of care for elderly</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975011852</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN Helen Pridham's article, Budgeting for Old Age, Liz Mitchell of Age Concern
claims that ``private care costs up to #500 per week'' and that ``the Church of
Scotland (residential care homes) provide the lowest- cost care'' (December 2).
This statement is inaccurate because Liz Mitchell is comparing the most
expensive private nursing homes with voluntary residential care homes which
provide a lower level of care. She is not comparing like with like.
Furthermore, her information on relative costs in the different sectors is
wrong. According to the respected consultancy firm Laing and Buisson, the
average fee for a private nursing home place in the UK is about #330 per person
per week and in fact most private nursing homes receive just #295 per person
per week from the DSS or local authority.
By comparison most private residential care homes receive fees of #197 to #227
from the state. Voluntary residential homes, including the Church of Scotland
Homes she mentions, are in fact more expensive than private residential homes
though less expensive than local authority residential homes which average
about #350 per resident per week and can cost up to #440 per week.
These facts can be confirmed by reading the Scottish Office publication,
Residential Homes for Elderly People - their Costs and Quality (HMSO, 1992),
which concluded that private residential homes provide the cheapest care.
Dr Colin M Barron,
Chairman,
Scottish Association of Care Home Owners,
Ashlea House,
Bracklinn Road,
Callander.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000012</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000012</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>District council criticised over Lanark Blue case Cheese maker tastes victory</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011853</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHEESEMAKER Humphrey Errington has won his case against Clydesdale District
Council, which alleged that a #27,000 batch of his Lanark Blue cheese was unfit
for human consumption.
Sheriff John Douglas Allan yesterday turned down a bid by the local authority
to destroy 44 batches of the cheese, a favourite with the royal family. He also
criticised the district council for its methods.
Mr Errington said he was relieved but not surprised that he had won the
year-long case, which has attracted support from Prince Charles. However, he
has run up legal costs of around #120,000 and could still go out of business,
he said.
Mr Errington said he would seek compensation from the council for the batch of
cheese at the centre of the controversy because it was no longer fit for sale.
He added that efforts would be made to recover the full cost of the legal
challenge.
Lawyers acting on his behalf said the council could face a challenge in the
European Court of Justice and may be reported to the local authority ombudsman
for maladministration. The authority already faces a sizeable legal bill, which
could top #100,000.
Mr Errington said: ``It is a huge relief that after 12 months our position has
been vindicated.''
He said the authority had not carried out a full risk assessment of the product
and may not have conducted tests properly.
Mr Errington said there were times when he feared the system would fail him but
he added: ``I felt that, if we persisted, sooner or later it would be
acknowledged we were right.''
He said the public support he received throughout the legal battle had been a
huge boost to morale and added that the judgment had been a victory for the
underdog.
He promised to continue production of the cheese but warned: ``We could still
find when we've squared the legal account that our level of debt is greater
than the business could support.''
His solicitor, Mr Peter Braid, said every legal avenue would be explored to
reclaim Mr Errington's costs.
In his judgment, Sheriff Allan, sitting at Lanark Sheriff Court, said: ``It
does not appear to me upon the evidence that the 44 batches of Lanark Blue
cheese stipulated in the notices of 22 February 1995 failed to comply with food
safety requirements.''
Sheriff Allan said he ``deplored'' the way Mr Errington had been attacked in
Clydesdale's final legal submissions to cast doubts on his integrity.
He added that it would be much more satisfactory if the Environmental Health
Department ``fulfilled their statory functions in a less combative and
confrontational manner''.
The case rested on whether the levels of listeria monocytogenes were high in
the cheese and, if present to any great degree, were they likely to cause
illness. The sheriff said there was no evidence whatsoever to show that the
cheese had made anyone sick.
The sheriff was critical of Dr Syed Ahmed, a consultant in public medicine in
Lanarkshire Health Board. The sheriff said he had little first-hand experience
in dealing with listeria poisoning and was wrong to ``err on the safe side''.
Dr James McLauchline, the UK's top expert on listeria, was attacked by the
sheriff for his ``evasive and defensive responses'' while giving evidence.
On the other hand, the sheriff decided that Dr Richard North, an independent
food safety advisor giving evidence for Mr Errington, was ``open and frank and
did not seek to conceal relevant material''.
The Scottish Agricultural College gave evidence that they discovered very high
levels of listeria in the cheese samples. However, Sheriff Allan said he did
not find the results credible, particularly after he heard the evidence of
French Roquefort cheese expert, Frenchman Jean Devoyod.
The SAC was also criticised for not running strictly controlled tests to make
sure there was no cross contamination when analysing the cheese samples.
In his general conclusions, Sheriff Allan said there was just no evidence to
show the cheese was harmful, particularly after 63,000 portions of Lanark Blue
cheese had been consumed in 1994.
Clydesdale applied for the destruction order under the 1990 Food Safety Act.
When they started action against Mr Errington in December 1994, a EC directive
banning all listeria from food and the Dairy Products (Hygiene) Scotland
regulations 1994 were not in force.
Mr Errington agreed to withdraw his cheese from circulation after a random test
in Edinburgh revealed the cheese found in a delicatessen contained listeria.
The type of listeria found in the batches was serotype 3A and is very rarely
associated with disease. No human case in Scotland had been linked with this
type of listeria between 1967 and 1994.
A complicated legal battle followed which saw the case first before a JP at a
private hearing. That decision was overturned at a judicial review in the Court
of Session because Mr Errington had been denied natural justice. The case
finally went before Sheriff Allan in August.
The council was not available for comment last night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000013</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000013</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Date is set for man to take his bank to court</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011854</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GLASGOW garage proprietor yesterday continued an action for #800,000 damages
against the Bank of Scotland and a further action for #50,000 against one of
its managers at Glasgow Sheriff Court.
Mr Magnus Mowetta, 44, of Torogay Street, Glasgow, alleged breach of contract
against the bank and the manager of its Partick Cross branch, Mr Roddy Burgess.
The case was raised at an options hearing at the court. The hearings, which
have been designed to speed up the course of justice, presented the sheriff
with two options: whether the case could be settled by legal argument or
whether witnesses would need to be heard in court.
Sheriff George Evans decided yesterday, after listening to agents for the three
parties, that the case should proceed to legal argument. The case will now be
heard on February 26.
If it transpires that, legally, one party does not have a case, it could be
dismissed by the sheriff. Alternatively, witnesses could be called on points
established in the legal debate.
Mr Mowetta set up Autofare in 1979 in Havelock Street, Glasgow. By 1986, its
turnover had reached nearly #1m a year. Then in 1992 the premises were sold and
the business divided.
Mr Mowetta continued to trade in Havelock Street as Autofare Garage. In 1993,
he was evicted by one of his former partners and moved to Balmore Industrial
Estate.
The writ alleges the ``defenders negligently advised the pursuer to part with
his control of the business and premises of Autofare in transactions in 1986,
1988, and 1992''.
It further alleges that Mr Mowetta's cheques were dishonoured ``arbitrarily and
without warning''. Mr Mowetta claimed there was a substantial loss of
confidence in him and his business, which resulted in his turnover falling by
more than #800,000.
The Bank of Scotland has said it will ``vigorously defend the action raised by
Mr Mowetta as will the manager's own solicitors''.
</TEXT>
