<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000015</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000015</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Worried Dole postpones Senate debate</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011856</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington
THE Senate has put off its debate on Bosnia until next week, as Senator Bob
Dole seeks to persuade recalcitrant colleagues to support the President. His
deputy, Senator Trent Lott of Mississippi, has announced his opposition to
deploying American troops, and he must now be induced to accept the position
taken by the party leader.
Lott defeated Dole's candidate for the position of Republican Whip a year ago,
and would presumably succeed Dole if he wins the presidential election.
Relations between the two men are therefore a key to Republican politics over
the next few years and Dole does not want a public split to open now.
Lott is a noted conservative and isolationist. He is probably much closer in
attitude to the confrontational politics practised by Senator Phil Gramm, who
is running against Dole for the Republican nomination and vocally opposes the
Bosnian intervention.
The dispute, therefore, also concerns presidential politics.
Several senators want to use the resolution supporting the intervention to
criticise the President's past policies, and to urge him to arm the Bosnian
Government Army immediately.
Over in the House of Representatives, the Speaker, Newt Gingrich, has yet to
reveal his hand, but it appears that in the end the House will follow the
Senate's lead and support the President.
Former presidents Ford, Carter, and Bush have announced that they support Mr
Clinton, and a long and impressive list of former officials, both Republican
and Democrat, took out a full-page advertisement in the newspapers today making
the point that peace in Bosnia was an important American objective, and
abandoning the Dayton agreement now would do irreparable harm to Nato and to
American leadership.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dentists prepare to confront trust</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011858</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SENIOR dentists at Glasgow Dental Hospital and School are on the verge of
revolt over what they claim is a dictatorial style of management.
Ill feeling among the 45 consultants and other permament staff is likely to
come to a head tonight at the monthly meeting of the hospital's division of
dentistry.
The hospital became an NHS trust in April, under the chairmanship of Sir James
Armour, retired Vice-Principal of Glasgow University, but dissatisfaction goes
back about a year.
There are about 60 senior staff in the dental division, including 15
consultants employed by the NHS and 30 honorary consultants employed by Glasgow
University. Their complaints include a ``confrontational'' management style and
that clinicians are not being involved sufficiently in policy-making.
One dentist said yesterday: ``There is supposed to be a teamwork approach in
the running of trusts but we are not being brought into the team - we feel we
have no say in the way the hospital is being run.''
Although the board has become aware that grievances are being expressed, a
spokesman for the trust said nothing had been put to it formally. He added:
``The board has an open-door policy and if there are misunderstandings or
legitimate grievances, they are willing to sit down and discuss them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NEWS DIGEST</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011859</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Driver out-ran
police at 100mph
MOTORIST Darren Davidson, 25, of Green Road, Kinross, who was chased by police
for 15 miles along twisting roads, was fined #1500 at Perth Sheriff Court
yesterday. He was also banned for three years and ordered to resit his test.
Chasing police reached speeds of more than 100mph but could not gain on
Davidson, who admitted driving dangerously and at grossly excessive speeds.
Bird's ill wind
A RARE American cliff swallow, which should be enjoying hot weather somewhere
between Brazil and Argentina, has been blown off course into the icy British
winter, to the Isles of Scilly.
Positive reaction
THE Magnox-type Wylfa power station on Anglesey, whose operator Nuclear
Electric was fined #250,000 in September for four serious safety breaches in
July 1993, was cleared yesterday by the Nuclear Installations Inspectorate to
produce electricity until at least 2004.
Prison unrest
RECENT attacks on prison officers at Belfast's Crumlin Road jail were a
deliberate attempt by inmates to have it closed, the Prison Officers
Association claimed yesterday.
Sacking award
OFFSHORE scaffolder Tom Adams, 44, of Barnflat Street, Rutherglen, Glasgow, who
worked on the Brent Alpha platform in the North Sea, was sacked in a
``precipitate and unreasonable'' manner by Rigblast Energy Services, which was
ordered to pay him #6626 by an Aberdeen industrial tribunal yesterday.
Pool flooded
Work on a #3m swimming pool in Berwick upon Tweed has been delayed for four
months - because of flooding on the site.
Research cash
DUNDEE University's #22m Wellcome Institute, for biomedical sciences research -
into diseases like cancer, diabetes, and malaria - received a donation of
#500,000 from Tayside Regional Council yesterday. Scottish Enterprise Tayside
is also to donate #500,000 to the institute, and the university will provide
#1m.
Access denied
WESTERN Isles Islands Council has rejected a plan to spend #200,000 on
improvements to council offices at Stornoway, Tarbert, and Balivanich, to
provide proper access for the disabled and more privacy for people when paying
taxes.
Boy charged
A 15-year-old boy has been charged in connection with a serious sexual assault
on an 81-year-old woman, at her home in an old people's complex in Knottingley,
West Yorkshire, on November 25. He was expected to appear before Pontefract
magistrates yesterday.
</TEXT>
