<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tourism's flagship gets a new owner in #1 deal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011860</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CAPTAIN Scott's Antarctic exploration vessel was sold for #1 yesterday to
Dundee Heritage Trust.
The RRS Discovery was brought back to her home port from London nearly 10 years
ago and was leased for 20 years to the Maritime Trust.
Discovery has become the focal point of Dundee's growing tourism industry.
A replica #1 note from 1900, the year work started on Discovery's construction,
was handed over to the Maritime Trust's chairman, Admiral Sir Julian Oswald.
Sir Julian said the trust had not sold the ship simply to avoid expenditure.
However, he admitted: ``We maintain the Cutty Sark and one or two other ships
at the moment and it is expensive.
``It will be very important for Dundee to attract lots of visitors to come and
see Discovery to help pay the costs.''
Youngsters who were born on the day in April 1986 when Discovery returned to
Dundee presented the replica note, and its modern counterpart, to the admiral.
Dundee Heritage Trust operates the Discovery Point visitor centre beside the
ship's berth on the banks of the Tay.
Mr Jonathan Bryant, chief executive, denied that the purchase of the Discovery
had left the trust with a costly liabilty.
He said: ``We are confident of raising funds for further restoration and for
maintaining the ship as well. Dundee and Discovery are now inseparable.''
Discovery was designed to take Scott on his first journey to the Antarctic and
had a life expectancy of 20 years when she was built.
In the last few years, #1m has been raised for refurbishments and operations
such as hull repairs, remasting, and the removal of fungus from timbers. A
further #200,000 is needed to do work to the hull.
Television personality Loyd Grossman was touring the facility as part of a
campaign to increase public support for museums. He said: ``This is a
particularly exciting project. It shows how important it can be to a city
because museums and exhibitions like this are a focal point and encourage a lot
of local pride.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clyde granary closes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011862</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE vast granary on Clydeside, said to be the largest brick-built building in
Europe, has finally closed.
Its owner, Clydeport, is making the last 13 workers redundant.
Meadowside Granary has been used only partially in the last 10 years, either as
office space or for storing some of the European Union's surplus grain or a
small amount of grain for distilling.
There are no immediate plans for redeveloping it. Schemes to make the area a
vast redevelopment site like the London Docklands fell through at the beginning
of the nineties.
To some, the building, said to have been built with 20 million bricks, is an
eyesore. Others regard it as one of the most outstanding structures built in
Scotland this century.
</TEXT>
