<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Snow slows Nato advance guard</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011863</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sarajevo
HEAVY snow snarled Nato's flight plans into Sarajevo today, slowing the arrival
of advance parties to establish bases for the 60,000-strong peace
implementation force (IFOR).
``The winter weather clearly won't help Nato's deployment but it's not taking
anyone by surprise,'' said United Nations spokesman Lieutenant-Colonel Chris
Vernon.
``Setting up an operation under adverse weather conditions is always more
difficult than sustaining an existing operation. But these are field troops and
they trained for this. It will just slow things down a bit.''
Meanwhile, a British commanding officer in Bosnia said today that Nato's peace
implementation force would be more determined to quell atrocities than UN
peacekeepers it will soon replace.
Brigadier Richard Dannat compared the two mandates as different as ``chalk and
cheese''.
``Under the present UN mandate, I can do little other than observe, report it,
and actually express my outrage and the outrage of the civilian community of
the world against that kind of behaviour,'' he told reporters in Split, Croatia.
Brig Dannat referred in particular to looting and burning by Bosnian Croat
forces in Mrkonjic Grad and Sipovo - central Bosnian towns to be handed to
Bosnian Serbs under a peace agreement initialled in Dayton, Ohio last month.
Only a few hundred Nato soldiers have landed in Bosnia since the Dayton accord,
most of them communications and logistics specialists paving the way for a rush
of troops set to begin about four days after the peace deal is formally signed
in Paris on December 14.
The first US military flight into Tuzla landed today at the airbase where US
Army reconnaissance and liaison teams are setting up the Nato base for northern
Bosnia.
Tuzla will be the seat of the 20,000-strong US IFOR detachment.
About 1400 US troops are in the enabling force, with about 700 soldiers to be
sent to Bosnia and another 700 to be sent to neighbouring Croatia.
British forces began their Nato deployment in Bosnia in a low-key manner today
with four men and a truck.
As the vanguard of an advance party, the two signallers and two logistics
personnel arrived at the United Nations base in the town of Gornji Vakuf
without fanfare.
A foot of snow gave the early arrivals a foretaste of the harsh Bosnian winter
making many of the rugged mountain passes which Nato troops will cross to reach
their camps almost impassable.
The snow could also make it difficult to spot what experts say are millions of
land mines scattered along more than 600 miles of confrontation lines in Bosnia.
As Nato advance troops spread across Bosnia there were fears within the
alliance that humanitarian aid efforts to anchor peace could not keep pace with
the military deployment.
``There is concern that civilian aspects are lagging behind the military . . .
it is not Nato's intention to become a provisional government,'' said one
alliance source.
Nato sources say they want the UN's humanitarian organisations, such as the
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and the UN children's fund (Unicef) to
work alongside Nato troops from ``day one''.
``It is not Nato's job to distribute aid and help refugees,'' one diplomat
said. ``It is important to speed up preparation for the civilian side.''
q MORE than 400 Highland Gunners of 19 Regiment, Royal Artillery, will return
to their home base at Colchester today after concluding their tour of duty in
the former Yugoslavia.
They were deployed with their 105mm guns on Mount Igman overlooking Sarajevo in
July. Soon after their arrival in theatre, their guns fired out in anger as
Nato forces demonstrated their resolve to re-open a route for supply convoys
into the beleaguered city.
The regiment recruits largely in the Inverness area, hence their nickname. The
gunners will fly into RAF Lynham in Wiltshire this morning and then be bused to
their home base at Colchester.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Professor decides to quit health board over cuts in acute services</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011864</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH health board chief has resigned over cuts in acute services.
Professor Richard Olver, vice-chairman of Tayside Health Board for the last
four years, has handed in his resignation stressing that he was left in an
``impossible'' situation.
The professor, a senior paediatrician at Ninewells Hospital in Dundee, has
criticised the board for moving resources away from acute services and into
more community-based projects.
Professor Olver also said he found himself ``increasingly at odds'' with the
board's policy and the methods with which they are put into practice.
He was supported by Labour's Scottish health spokesman John McCallion, MP for
Dundee East, who called the resignation ``a measure of the complete bankruptcy
of current Government policy'' in the NHS.
In a statement issued yesterday, Professor Olver explained that, with the
introduction of an internal market to the NHS, there was bound to be a
``tension'' between his role as a member of the purchasing health board and his
work in an acute provider hospital.
He explained: ``Initially, I did not find it difficult to reconcile the two but
latterly, as resources have been diverted away from the acute sector, I have
found my position impossible.''
Professor Olver said he had a problem with the implementation of transferring
resources into primary care, not the policy itself.
He stressed: ``I am not convinced that our decisions to invest very substantial
resources in primary care and community projects are based on sufficiently good
evidence of likely cost effectiveness, or that we have adequate mechanisms for
monitoring whether this investment has been effective in improving health.''
The professor explained that, when he joined the board, he did not realise that
main elements of health board policy are set by the Scottish Office, leaving
the board with limited autonomy.
He added: ``In areas where the board does have the ability to act
independently, I have found myself increasingly at odds with its policies and
the way they are put into practice.
``Since I am bound by collective responsibility and cannot pick and choose
which of the board's policies I support formally, I have decided that
resignation is the only honourable course.''
Mr McAllion said he shared the professor's concerns.
He added: ``I am deeply saddened to hear of Professor Olver's resignation.''
Mr James Macfarlane, chairman of Tayside Health Board, said he ``regretted''
Professor Olver's resignation and added: ``It is not surprising that someone
who has to combine clinical responsibilities in a trust with health board
membership finds occasions when interests appear to conflict.''
The chairman defended the board's policies and described the increasing
emphasis on primary care as a UK move ``which has been agreed throughout the
NHS''.
He said: ``It makes sense to deal with as many health problems as possible as
close to the patients as possible and Tayside Health Board is committed to this.
``The shift to primary and community care aims to avoid unnecessary
hospitalisation and reduce the demands on hospital services, enabling
clinicians to concentrate on specialist care and enhancing both primary and
secondary sectors.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000022</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000022</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Theatre   Hysteria, Duke of York Theatre, London.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Nicola Dillon</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975011865</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Royal Court's inspired season of classics continues in the West End with
Hysteria by Terry Johnson. Only two years old, one might question the
confidence with which it has been given the status as a ``classic'' but within
moments of the curtain going up there is no mistaking the quality of the
playwright.
Set in Freud's study in Hampstead, near the end of the doctor's life, Johnson
sets out to give us an ``Analysis of an Obsessional Neurosis''. Salvador Dali
comes to tea with Sigmund Freud (a true event) and Jessica, a young woman who
displays most forms of neurosis witnessed in Freud's notebooks, forces her way
into the study.
Abraham Yahuda (Freud's doctor and friend) is an authority figure, attempting
to stop the publication of Moses and Monotheism. As the play becomes
increasingly nightmare-ish it is clear that we are witnessing the analysis of
Freud's own obsession.
Hysteria deservedly won the 1994 Olivier Award for Best Comedy and Johnson
elegantly carries the play through a range of styles - farce, thriller, serious
drama - using wit, slapstick and surrealism. His dialogue is sharp as he weaves
in and out of ideas, teasing the audience with notions of real and unreal,
conscious and subconscious. It requires the excellent direction of Phyllida
Lloyd and the strong cast to carry it off; not to mention the very good set and
lighting design.
Henry Goodman and Tim Potter return as Freud and Dali respectively. Aisling
O'Sullivan joins them as Jessica. It is her shift in moods and direction which
drives the play forward and provides most of the drama. O'Sullivan handles this
superbly; shifting effortlessly from hysterical victim to tormentor, pausing to
be nursemaid and sex object.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Insult to injury</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975011866</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOU report that Strathclyde's director of education will be looking for a job
in April. In the unlikely event of Mr Pignatelli having to sign on at his local
DSS office at least he will be able to write his name.
In a recent article (Dear David: I do wish you could read this) I recounted the
experience of a former Strathclyde pupil left illiterate four-and-a-half years
ago after 11 years of schooling and who has been signing on for these
four-and-a-half years by making his mark.
While failure to make a pupil literate is bad enough, to enter such a pupil, as
is the practice in Strathclyde, for Standard Grade exams at both Foundation and
General level using a scribe (myself in David's case) to read out questions and
write down answers is merely to add insult to an intellectual injury that could
last a lifetime.
John McLellan,
44 Terregles Avenue,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
