<DOCNO>GH951207-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jackson collapses on stage</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011867</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
New York
MICHAEL JACKSON was taken to a hospital in New York tonight after collapsing on
stage while rehearsing for a TV special, a spokesman for the Emergency Medical
Service said.
Jackson, 37, was suffering from low blood pressure, but was awake and alert
when he was taken from the theatre by ambulance, the spokesman, John Hanchar,
said.
His condition was described as stable by the hospital.
Hanchar said help was summoned by a security guard at the Beacon Theatre, where
Jackson collapsed.
Jackson had been rehearsing for a cable television special, which was scheduled
to be taped on Friday and Saturday for broadcast on Sunday night.
Hancher said initial reports to emergency services indicated that Jackson was
not breathing but he added: ``Paramedics responded and found him to be awake
and alert.''
However, he added that it appeared to be ``a serious condition''-Reuter/Ap.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Music   Ralph Kirshbaum and Roger Vignoles, RSAMD, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Conrad Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975011869</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CELLO recital that begins with works by Bach and Beethoven can thereafter go
in any direction. But the harmonic compression of Bach's C major cello suite
and the structural tautness of Beethoven's D major cello sonata, Op.102, No.2,
may be thought to demand something even more concentrated to follow.
Last night Ralph Kirshbaum and Roger Vignoles settled for Webern's Drei kleine
Stucke, Op.11, for cello and piano, three pieces so short they hardly exist.
But what does exist in these laconic studies in intensity, as the performance
made plain, is so expressive that a whole world of musical experience is
crammed into a couple of minutes.
Each tiny stroke, each small rustle, each barely perceptible gesture made an
impact far beyond its brief duration.
As an experience, the performance - like all good performances of Webern's
music - was immensely bigger than the sum of its parts.
But having reached so minuscule a goal, the recital had either to stop or
expand. So it expanded into the bleak and skeletal lyricism of Shostakovich's D
minor sonata, in which Vignoles's stalking piano lines darkly shadowed the
warmer flow of Kirshbaum's cello part.
Earlier, things had been more uneven. To the first movement of Bach's solo
suite, Kirshbaum brought somewhat nasal tone and the odd rasp before he and his
rich Montagnana cello settled into the hall's acoustics.
But the performance soon progressed into a strong, free flowing, subtly
coloured exploration of each movement, just as the Beethoven grew into
something greater than its splashy opening might have suggested.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>FOREIGN DIGEST</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011870</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ten die as bus
plunges into lake
VIENNA: A double-decker bus carrying German tourists toppled into an icy
mountain lake near Salzburg yesterday killing up to 10 people and injuring more
than 30.
The bus, carrying Germans from Landshut, about 40 miles northeast of Munich,
skidded and fell into Lake Wolfgang, apparently while on a narrow two-lane
highway overlooking the lake. Seven bodies were reportedly discovered and three
people were missing, feared dead.
Embassy protests
JAKARTA: East Timorese protesters forced their way into the Russian and Dutch
embassy compounds in central Jakarta today, the 20th anniversary of Indonesia's
military invasion of East Timor. After scaling the embassy walls, there were
about 58 in the Dutch compound, and 40 in the Russian.
Simpson to talk
O J SIMPSON has agreed to give his first television interview to CNN, but no
date has been set and there would be no ground rules, network legal analyst
Greta Van Susteren said yesterday.
Election violence
CAIRO: Twelve people were killed in clashes in Egypt yesterday during
parliamentary elections marred by reports of widespread fraud by police and
supporters of President Hosni Mubarak's ruling National Democratic Party.
Rebels attacked
BUJUMBURA: Heavy fighting rocked Burundi's capital yesterday after the
Tutsi-dominated army mounted what Western diplomats said was their biggest
operation to flush out Hutu rebels in the city.
Grenade deaths
MOSCOW: A man demanding money seized a kindergarten in southern Russia and blew
up two hand grenades, killing three young children and wounding several other
people, including himself. Police said Yuri Kardanov, a resident of
Vladikavkaz, about 930 miles south of Moscow, entered the local kindergarten at
noon on Tuesday brandishing the two grenades.
PM has operation
ATHENS: Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou, in hospital for more than two
weeks with pneumonia, yesterday underwent a tracheotomy operation.
Bobbitts divorce
VIRGINIA: John Wayne Bobbitt has severed his wedding vows with wife Lorena with
a pen stroke - drawing a small sketch of a knife beside his signature. Bobbitt
finally signed a property settlement agreement with the woman who cut off his
penis with a kitchen knife two years ago, said his lawyer in Manassas, Virginia
. . . and the divorce will be final within a few weeks.
Snake jam
NEW DELHI: A cobra crossing a busy road caused a traffic jam several miles long
during morning rush-hour yesterday in India's capital New Delhi. Most Indians
will not harm cobras because it was the mythical pet of Shiva, one of the most
revered Hindu gods.
Tree cheers
NEW YORK: A rousing cheer went up from crowds in central Manhattan as children
helped David Rockefeller light the traditional Christmas tree last night. The
75ft tree is wired with more than 25,000 multicoloured bulbs strung over five
miles of electrical wire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
