<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975011873</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS a fairly well-known member of the Scottish National Party I am often asked
why the SNP is not represented on the Scottish Constitutional Convention. My
answer is always the same. The convention's terms of reference (agenda) were
drawn up by the Labour Party specifically to exclude any debate on the
independence option and this exclusion was unacceptable to the SNP. It is as
simple as that.
Whether the independence option was excluded for fear the logic of the
independence argument would carry the day or because the Labour Party knew that
its exclusion would be unacceptable to the SNP, is immaterial, but it was
undemocratic, to say the least.
Now that the convention has debated and cogitated over the last six years it
has at last hatched a scheme which is very little different from the one the
Labour Party put forward at the 1979 Referendum, and which that same Labour
Party could not implement because of opposition within its own party (see Jim
Callaghan's Memoirs) - even when a clear 77,435 majority of the Scots
electorate had voted for it.
Despite assurances given by Tory Blair and George Robertson there are already
rumblings in the ranks against the new proposals and I very much doubt if they
will ever get off the starting blocks.
While I agree that Scotland has a right to a parliament we have no right to
have a parliament in Scotland in which English opinions and interests are
excluded while we, simultaneously, have a say in England's Parliament at
Westminster.
We can't eat our cake and still have it. It doesn't make sense, and this is the
rock on which the convention's ploy will perish.
For this reason the so-called parliament can be little better than an enhanced
Scottish Grand Committee and will, ultimately, be responsible to Westminster
and only allowed to do what Westminster permits.
English MPs would be daft to grant us anything better, but they would have no
option if we voted for independence.
Tom McCallum,
7 Barnton Place, Dumfries.
</TEXT>
