<HEADLINE>NEWS DIGEST</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>NEWS DIGEST</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011874</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Police search for
missing man, 78
A POLICE helicopter search on land and sea was under way yesterday for missing
Bute pensioner Alfred Palmer, 78, of Church Cottage, Townhead, Rothesay.
Mr Palmer was last seen on Sunday night. Strathclyde Police say there is
concern for his safety.
Traffic move
BORDERS Regional Council plans to spend an estimated #10,000 on traffic calming
measures in the High Street in Coldstream because of speeding and congestion.
Labour choice
CHRISTIAN Aid worker Paul Brannen, 33, has been named as the Labour Party
candidate to challenge MP Alan Beith, deputy leader of the Liberal-Democrats,
in the Berwick constituency at the General Election.
Gays' request
GAY rights group OutRage! will not disrupt the enthronement of the new
Archbishop of York Dr David Hope tomorrow, it announced yesterday. However it
has asked him to make a commitment to ``queer emancipation'' in his address at
York Minster.
Meningitis fear
A SECOND youngster has died and six others are ill in an outbreak of meningitis
in north-east England, it was revealed yesterday. Four-year-old Reece McCawll,
from Middlesbrough, Cleveland, died last Friday. A 16-year-old from Durham has
also died.
Asylum delay
NIGERIAN refugee Abiodun Igbindu, 25, who is seeking asylum in Britain, has
been granted permission to stay while representations by MPs on his behalf are
considered, his solicitor said yesterday.
Arrest after blast
A 45-YEAR-OLD man has been arrested after a parcel bomb exploded at a Royal
Mail sorting office in Bishop Street, Coventry. More than 300 postal workers
were evacuated from the building before the blast. No-one was hurt.
Murder charge
A FOSTER mother has been charged with murdering a two-year-old boy. Mrs Angela
Harris, 30, from Leeds, was remanded in custody until December 14 yesterday
following the death of Patrick McKenzie from Yeadon at Leeds General Infirmary.
He had suffered head injuries.
#5m in basket
A PAINTING - entitled The Finding of Moses - was sold for #5,061,500 at
Sotheby's in London yesterday. Painted by court artist Orazio Gentileschi in
1633-4 for Charles I, it was sent to Spain during the Civil War but returned to
Castle Howard in Yorkshire during the 1790s. The proceeds of the sale to a
private collector will be used to refurbish the castle.
</TEXT>
