<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>3p tax power affirms English supremacy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975011875</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE media have given extensive exposure to Michael Forsyth's tartan tax, which
may or may not arrive, depending upon the outcome of the next General Election.
But the media never comment upon the ``tartan tax'' which prevails at present.
Motorists in the Highlands and Islands of Scotland pay about 10p more tax than
motorists in Manchester on each gallon of petrol. Why does Mr Forsyth not do
something about this real imposition?
On George Robertson's proposals for a Scottish parliament it seems that he is
recommending that the English (Westminster) Parliament should stipulate the
taxation powers of his Scottish parliament, by his plus or minus 3p on basic
income tax. What he is doing is ensuring that the English Parliament
effectively controls the new Scottish parliament. He is affirming the
sovereignty of the English Parliament over the Scottish parliament.
Is Mr Forsyth, when objecting to this tax, implying that the English Parliament
should not have sovereignty over the Scottish parliament? Is his statement
about an independent Scotland by 2002 really a hope and not a fear (December 4)?
Frank Thomson,
11 Moorfoot Way, Bearsden.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
