<HEADLINE>Pre-Christmas trial date set for Rabin's assassin</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011876</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Tel Aviv
ISRAELI Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin's confessed assassin was today ordered to
face trial, set to start on December 19, after a prosecutor read out murder and
conspiracy charges in court.
Gunman Yigal Amir, wearing a grey sweatshirt and a black skullcap, sat on a
bench in a Tel Aviv court, nodding from time to time as he heard the
accusations against him.
Amir is to enter his plea on December 19. Amir has told investigators and a Tel
Aviv magistrate that he killed Rabin. However, his defence lawyer, Mordechai
Ofri, said today he hadn't decided yet how his client would plead.
Even if Amir pleads guilty, there will be a trial, with the three judges
assigned to the case expected to ask the prosecution to present evidence.
If convicted, Amir's mandatory sentence is life in prison. The death penalty in
Israel is reserved for Nazi war criminals and offenders who harm state
security, such as spies.
The defence attorney said he needed more meetings with his client to decide on
a line of defence, but said he would not bring politics into his arguments.
``I see this as a criminal trial, a murder trial that has no political
implications,'' Ofri told reporters after the hearing.
Amir, a fervently religious Jew, has said he killed Rabin to prevent the
implementation of the Israel-PLO autonomy agreements under which Israeli troops
are to withdraw from parts of the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Religious Jews
consider those areas part of the biblical land of Israel.
Amir is also represented by Jonathan Goldberg, an immigrant from the United
States seven years ago who lives in the West Bank settlement of Emanuel.
Goldberg, who has defended Jewish militants in the past, told the Yediot
Ahronot daily newspaper:
``I couldn't believe that he did such a thing. He is sweet, he has a good
heart, and he appears to be a decent human being.''
According to the indictment, Amir decided sometime after the first Israel-PLO
accord, signed in 1993, to kill Rabin. The charge sheet said he recruited his
brother Hagai, 27, and a friend, Dror Adani, to help him.
The court ordered Hagai Amir and Adani to be held until January 7, charged with
conspiracy and weapons violations.
</TEXT>
