<DOCNO>GH951207-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour's consistent tax-raising record</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975011877</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JUST how far out of touch with reality can Ruth Wishart be? Her miserable
attempts to rubbish Daphne Sleigh's views on the Scottish Constitutional
Convention's blueprint for a Scottish assembly were not only ``over the top''
but clearly identified Ruth Wishart as having leanings towards the
``wild-eyed'' left (December 4).
To suggest that if a Scottish assembly were set up it would not use its powers
to add a further burden of tax on the Scottish people is totally unrealistic
and just plain foolish. Over the past 40 or so years, Labour Governments have
consistently raised all forms of taxation. This hardly fills anyone with
confidence that they will not do so on future occasions.
To complain that Daphne Sleigh happens to have facts and figures in respect of
the costs of a Scottish assembly is hardly fair. After all, the Constitutional
Convention seems to be very coy about telling anyone the real costs of anything
they have proposed and at the end of the day the Scottish people - and only the
Scottish people - are going to have to pay the real costs of any taxation
imposed.
The rest of the UK will pay less in tax while a Scottish assembly is free to
impose extra taxes only on Scottish people. That, among many other proposals
made by the convention, is just sheer economic madness.
Loving the Scottish nation is what this debate is all about. Far from being
prophets of doom, the Scottish Conservative and Unionist Party, as always, is
living in the real world. The emotional fantasies propounded by Ruth Wishart
and her like, if they were ever implemented, would reduce the Scottish nation,
in the longer term, to a second-rate banana republic.
Daphne Sleigh quite rightly pointed out the dangers that lie ahead if the
Scottish assembly ever gets off the ground.
Alastair Mackenzie,
Deputy Chairman,
West of Scotland Conservatives,
7 Westfield Drive, Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
