<HEADLINE>Which? report hits out over `appalling' financial advice</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011879</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALMOST one in three financial advisers gives bad advice, according to a report
published today by the Consumers' Association, which says some advice provided
to clients is ``appalling''.
Researchers for the CA's magazine Which? visited 48 advisers, asking for
investment advice in August this year, and concluded that only one in two gave
good advice and that the desire to earn commission influenced some advice more
than the needs of customers.
The researchers found that agents who sold just one company's products were
worst, independent advisers best, and solicitors and accountants ``mixed'' in
the quality of advice they gave.
The magazine report says two researchers consulted 24 advisers each, with
``unambiguous needs'', but almost a third of the advisers recommended an
unsuitable type of investment.
In the worst case, when the best advice was to tell a researcher to leave his
#15,000 redundancy cheque in a risk-free bank or building society savings
account, the adviser recommended he put it all in an investment bond. That
would have earned the adviser almost #800 in commission and left the researcher
with no money to live on.
Which? said that, despite the clear needs of the investigators, advisers
suggested a range of financial products, including life insurance, personal
pensions, Tessas, personal equity plans, and investment bonds.
Ms Kate Scribbins, head of money at Which?, said: ``Too much investment advice
is still poor and some of it is appalling.
``The needs of our Which? investigators were absolutely clear-cut: access to
their money at short notice or within a fairly short period, and therefore
saving without risk.
``Yet some advisers recommended a range of financial products including
unnecessary and unsuitable products such as personal pensions and investment
bonds. In the circumstances, none was superior to a simple, risk-free savings
account. However, these don't earn the adviser commission.''
The Which? report added that the current system of regulating financial
advisers is not working.
One financial adviser, Mr Leonard Mann, proprietor of Atlas Financial
Consultants, of Kilmarnock Road, Shawlands, Glasgow, responded to the report
yesterday.
He said: ``You will always get the salesman mentality selling any product - and
financial services is no exception. But generally we are a very professional
body of people.''
</TEXT>
