<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Music   Runrig, Glasgow Royal Concert Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Iain Ross.</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975011881</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WELCOME to Baldsville. Not a particularly flatter-   ing description of
tonight's audience but, ecologically speaking, we could be on to something very
important here.
As the high-powered stage lights swept the sea of bobbing pates in the crowd,
reflecting beams became magnified to mega dazzle. If focused properly, possibly
into a large prism situated at the back of the hall, this untapped energy
resource could go some way to lessening our dependence on fossil fuels.
And there's surely no better band than Runrig, with their extensive portfolio
of paeans to the elements, and large defoliated following, to investigate this
possibility further.
Saving the world aside, we were given a glimpse of what Runrig could, and
perhaps should, be. Opening with Nothing But the Sun and Day in a Boat from
their new album Mara, we were transported to a land inhabited by Deep Forest
and the likes. Celtic sentimentality meets dance sensibility. Unfortunately
this was swiftly submerged beneath the torpid, middle-stadia wash of sound that
has become their trademark.
It seems churlish to criticise the chaps for not being more interesting than
they are, what with them being the first band to popularise the mix of Gaelic
lyrics with a rockish sound.
Regrettably, in the eight or so years since those heady vanguardist days,
they've progressed, musically, a very short distance. Then again, if they are
selling out decent-sized venues, why should they hunger for more?
If music be the food of love, tonight we dined on potted hough.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
