<DOCNO>GH951207-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Accountants face ruin after court's decision Award of #65m shocks industry</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011884</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TOTAL of 150 accountants could face financial ruin after a record #65m
damages award against their firm in the High Court yesterday.
An electronic security company won the damages from accountant BDO Binder
Hamlyn after a judge severely criticised crucial information the firm
volunteered during a takeover bid.
The award, believed to be the biggest in the UK against an accountancy firm,
will send shock waves through the profession.
Mr Jonathan Sumption QC, representing the firm, told Mr Justice May that his
client's insurance cover fell short of the total damages and interest by #34m.
Legal sources said this would mean the 150 partners of BDO Binder Hamlyn were
now liable for the shortfall.
``It could mean ruin for them,'' one source said. ``No-one in the profession
would ever have believed they would be liable in this way.''
Mr Sumption was allowed a hearing to ask for a stay of settlement until an
appeal could be heard.
BDO Binder Hamlyn had valued Britannia Securities Group, target of the takeover
bid, at #105m.
However, the judge found the accountants had been negligent in their audit of
the company, and it was worth only #40m. He awarded bidder ADT the difference
between the audit and true values.
BDO Binder Hamlyn worked for BSG - not ADT, the electronic security company
seeking to buy out the shares.
The judge found the firm had assumed responsibility to ADT at a business
meeting in January 1990, when it gave information about BSG's worth.
Mr Chris Foster, representing ADT, said: ``It was a hard fought victory. I
think it is the biggest single award against accountants in the UK.''
Mr Foster estimated that, with interest payments dating back to the takeover in
1990, the final settlement would be in the region of #95m.
The High Court case hinged on ADT's claim that Mr Martyn Bishop, audit partner
of BDO Binder Hamlyn, assumed responsibility to it at the January 1990 meeting
by restating that the 1989 accounts, which his firm had audited, showed a true
and fair view of the state of affairs of BSG.
ADT claimed the accounts did not give a true picture and that this was caused
by BDO Binder Hamlyn's negligence and it had suffeed loss.
On BDO Binder Hamlyn's information, ADT believed that a premium over the BSG
share price of 25% would lead to an agreed takeover.
ADT director Mr John Jermine told the court that, at the crucial meeting, Mr
Bishop had told him that he had no reason to change his mind over the BSG
accounts, which showed true and fair view of the company's financial position.
Mr Justice May said in his judgment: ``I judged Mr Jermine's oral evidence to
be generally quietly impressive and entirely credible. I was less impressed
with Mr Bishop's credibility.''
He said that if Mr Bishop had qualified his statements on BSG, ADT would have
taken stock.
``I have held that, on January 5, 1990, Mr Bishop stood by the accounts and
thereby assumed responsibility to ADT for the professional competence with
which they had been prepared, and I have held that ADT relied on what Mr Bishop
said.''
q The #65m award will send shockwaves through the accountancy profession.
It could start a rush to abandon hundreds of years of custom, whereby partners
in top accountancy firms are often personally liable for claims against their
companies.
In future, they may seek to ``ring-fence'' themselves, so that the firm would
be liable.
KPMG will split off its business that audits the books of 700 of Britain's
biggest companies next year into a new entity, called KPMG Audit plc.
KPMG senior partner Colin Sharman said: ``Firms often pick up the full cost of
company collapse despite being only partially responsible, and when auditors
themselves have been subject of fraud and deceit.
``It is clear from the size of some of the largest claims that if one were to
succeed, it would wipe out a firm.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Simpson agrees to TV interview</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011885</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
O J SIMPSON has agreed to give his first television interview to CNN, but no
date has been set, network legal analyst Greta Van Susteren said yesterday.
Van Susteren said in a CNN broadcast that she spoke for four hours with the
former American football star last weekend and he was ``adamant'' that there
would be no ground rules for the interview.
``He has promised CNN an interview with no rules whatsoever,'' said Van
Susteren, who provided legal analysis for CNN during Simpson's murder trial.
Simpson was acquitted on October 3 in the June, 1994, knife murders of his
ex-wife Nicole Brown Simpson and her friend Ronald Goldman.
Shortly after his criminal trial ended, Simpson backed out of his previous
agreement for a broadcast interview because of a pending civil case, set for
April.
Meanwhile, the Daily News in New York reported that Simpson was negotiating a
multi-million-dollar deal to sell a video proclaiming his innocence.
Simpson hopes to sign with a Los Angeles-based company as soon as some
well-known personality agrees to appear with him in the two-hour video entitled
O J Speaks Out, the newspaper quoted a source as saying.-AP
</TEXT>
</DOC>
