<DOCNO>GH951207-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000040</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>One in four young homeless attempt suicide</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011886</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE in four homeless young people has tried to commit suicide in the past year
through despair and psychiatric disorders, a mental health professional said.
Mental Health Foundation director June McKerrow said Budget announcements
restricting housing benefit to the under 25s could soon lead to greater numbers
on the streets.
Results of a three-year survey of 161 people, announced yesterday, showed:
q young homeless are twice as likely to suffer a psychiatric disorder;
q more than half had experienced severe parental neglect or abuse in childhood;
q parents of young homeless people were three times more likely to have had
psychiatric treatment themselves;
q only 15% of those with a psychiatric disorder received help.
Full details of the survey - Off to a Bad Start - are due to be published early
next year.
Ms McKerrow said: ``Our research clearly shows that young homeless people are
vulnerable to mental health problems and some are so desperate about their
futures that suicide seems the only answer.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>How Scotland would gain from a tartan tax-break</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HAMISH PATON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011888</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THANKS to the indefatigable efforts of Michael Forsyth and his colleagues we
are hearing a great deal about the so-called ``tartan tax''. If we are to
believe the Unionist doomsayers, the mere possibility of a Scottish Parliament
having the power to vary personal taxation rates would lead to a flight of
industry and commerce and the subsequent ruination of the Scottish economy.
Yet, curiously, we hear much less about the possibility that a Scottish
parliament would use its powers to lower rather than to raise taxation levels -
a tartan tax-break rather than a tartan tax. In doing so Scotland could easily
increase its total tax revenue.
Even if the power to lower taxes were restricted to the modest 3p in the #1
proposed by the Scottish Constitutional Convention, the resultant tax-break for
high earners (#100,000pa and over) would be several thousand pounds a year. One
can imagine that every financial adviser south of the Border would be urging
his clients to establish Scottish residency for tax purposes. Given that most
of the English upper classes seem able to claim a Scottish granny or auntie or
second-cousin-once-removed, a considerable number will find this relatively
simple.
Since such individuals command a disproportionate share of total taxable income
their reassignment to a Scottish tax residency will have an effect quite
disproportionate to their actual numbers. Scotland's notional tax base will
soar, possibly to double current levels. So, paradoxically, lowering the tax
rate could lead to almost doubling the Scottish parliament's income tax
revenues.
There is, as always, a catch. In this case, it is that the above scenario only
works if the Scottish parliament collects its own tax revenues. The Scottish
Constitutional Convention proposed originally that their Scottish parliament do
precisely that. Only in the last stages was this option dumped in favour of a
block grant from Westminster. George Robertson presented this change at the
time as a ``technical'' modification of no real political significance. On the
contrary, it changes the whole ball game.
Imagine what would happen if a Robertson-model Scottish parliament attempted to
lower income tax by 3p in the #1. The notional Scottish tax-base would expand
as before but, instead of Scotland gaining extra revenue, the full cost to the
Whitehall Treasury of the loss of their UK revenue would be deducted presumably
from the Scottish parliament's block grant. The Scots would end up subsidising
tax-avoidance schemes for wealthy Englishmen, while suffering huge reductions
in the income available for essential services.
By dropping the requirement that Scottish taxes be collected in Scotland, the
convention partners have shot themselves in the foot. The compelling logic for
a Scottish parliament, of whatever political complexion, is to lower rather
than to raise tax rates. Yet this they cannot do because the tax-gathering
machinery rests with Westminster.
This has other consequences beyond the missed opportunities for raiding the
English tax base. We are told that higher taxes in a self-governing Scotland
will lead to a loss of jobs. One recent newspaper poll came up with the figure
of 9000 jobs to go in the event of a 3p increase in income tax.
Conservative businessmen assure us that the reasons for such an outflow have no
basis in anti-Scottish bigotry or in any distaste for democracy. They are
simply a matter of business logic. If this is so, and who am I to challenge
such sober-minded calculation, then the same economic imperative presumably
operates in the opposite direction. English and multinational firms, finding
that income tax was 3p less in Scotland, would come flocking over the Border.
And, since there are 10 times as many of them as of us, the effects would be 10
times as great.
Thus, if the Unionists calculate that a 3p rise in Scottish income tax will
lead to 9000 jobs lost then, by the same token, a 3p reduction will mean 90,000
jobs gained.
The signatories of the Convention's Claim of Right asserted the sovereignty of
the Scottish people over that of the Westminster Parliament. Yet the plans they
have now produced foresee the legitimacy of the Scottish parliament as being
rooted in an Act of the Westminster Parliament rather than in the sovereign
power of the Scottish people. Probably this about-face has been due to the fact
that when the concept of popular sovereignty was considered in depth the only
logical outcome was seen to be independence - the project of their hated rivals
in the SNP.
Antipathy towards SNP policies and personalities is something quite separate
from the merits of independence. If the Scottish business community could only
have the confidence to see the opportunities available in an independent
Scotland, then they might even aspire to lead it.
For any clear-sighted entrepreneur the economic potential that can be unleashed
by independence is staggering. The tartan tax-break paradox means that lower
taxes mean higher revenues, not just for income tax but also for corporation
tax and excise duties. With all this going for it an independent Scotland,
oil-rich and debt-free, could rapidly regain its place among the wealthiest
nations on the planet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
