<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish teachers face call for strike</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011889</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DELEGATES attending a special weekend conference of Scotland's biggest
teachers' union will be asked to back a call for a national one-day strike
followed by a rolling programme of industrial action in a campaign against
underfunding in education.
Strike action will, however, be opposed by the leadership of the Educational
Institute of Scotland, which wants the campaign to focus on areas such as
reducing class sizes, pressing central and local government for greater
investment in education, involving parents and students, and holding a national
demonstration against cuts.
The union believes that underfunding is the single biggest issue facing
schools, colleges, and universities, and underpins many of the problems in the
sector.
Another motion re-affirms the union's opposition to compulsory redundancies at
further-education colleges. Strike ballots will be held in colleges which make
lecturers redundant against their wishes.
The meeting was requisitioned by more than 5000 EIS members who signed a
petition calling for a special conference on underfunding.
EIS concerns are also reflected in the union's response, published today, to
the Government's Higher Still reform of upper secondary schooling.
It said the programme could not be implemented until adequate resources were
made available. The Government has put #4m into developing courses for fifth
and sixth-year pupils but the union said supplementary funding from local
authorities had been necessary to ensure that principal teachers could take
part in the consultation.
It also said that Budget statements from Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth
made it clear that education spending would be so tight that the minimum
requirements of Higher Still could not be met.
Underfunding and the many demands being made on schools meant that the 1998
deadline for implementing the programme - extended after the Government was
told that the original timescale was too tight - could not be met, it said.
Confirming that the EIS would continue its boycott of Higher Still as part of a
wider workload campaign, the union's general secretary, Mr Ronnie Smith, said:
``If adequate funds are not made available, it would be quite irresponsible for
the EIS to advise its members to take part in what would be a botched job,
likely to do irreparable harm to a generation of pupils and students.''
</TEXT>
