<HEADLINE>No end in sight as more join nationwide stoppage French unions step up protest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011891</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris
ON the 13th day of France's crippling public-sector strikes, unions today
widened their offensive against government plans to overhaul the debt-ridden
welfare system.
Government and union leaders dug in their heels in a test of strength that
appeared to have no end in sight.
With teachers, hospital staff, and airline workers poised to join the strikes
tomorrow, union leaders called for more stoppages in both the public and
private sectors as well as nationwide demonstrations.
About 700,000 people demonstrated in cities around France yesterday in protests
that at times turned violent. Strikers clashed with police in Paris and wounded
21 officers in Nantes in the western region of Brittany.
The Force Ouvriere union, a key player in the two-week wave of stoppages,
called for more walkouts tomorrow in both the public and private sectors and
for marches across the entire country.
Workers' Force accused the Prime Minister of rejecting its demand for full
negotiation on welfare reform.
``It is necessary to continue the struggle,'' said Louis Viannet, communist
head of the CGT General Confederation of Workers, the largest union.
The CGT issued a statement calling for strikes and demonstrations in all
regions in both the public and private sectors following the call from the
non-partisan Force Ouvriere.
``The CGT congress urges that December 7 be a new and powerful date for united
action by all professions, in making strikes and demonstrations more widespread
across the country,'' the statement said.
Here is a summary of the main disruption caused yesterday, or expected later in
the week:
Transport - No rail or Paris public transport services. Bus and metro services
restricted in main provincial cities. Stoppages to spread to Marseille, Nantes
and Lille today.
A drop in temperatures worsened misery for commuters, but morning traffic jams
were less severe than earlier this week.
Limited Eurostar trains between Paris, London, and Brussels.
Marseille, Nantes, Dunkerque, and Saint Malo dockers on strike. Ferry services
from Calais, Dunkerque, and Dieppe disrupted.
Air France and Air Intercabin crews expected to go on 24-hour strike tomorrow.
Air controllers in regional centres are on strike, causing up to 90-minute
delays on most flights out of Orly and Charles de Gaulle airports. Ground
navigation personnel expected to stop work tomorrow.
Government offices - Widespread stoppages by local authority workers. Bank of
France expected to strike tomorrow and on Friday.
About 3.7% of civil servants, 58,000 workers, are on strike, with the economic
and finance sectors hardest hit.
Public sector: Postal officials say 77 of 135 sorting centres have been closed
and 43 disrupted. Several post offices are closed and 17% of staff are on
strike. Air mail sorting centres at Orly and Charles de Gaulle airports are
also hit.
France Telecom said 46% of its employees were on strike.
Sixty-three hospitals are operating at minimal levels and 40 social security
processing centres have joined the strike.
Meanwhile the Government, under world fire over its nuclear weapons tests,
today said it would complete the bitterly disputed South Pacific experiments
before the end of February, three months ahead of schedule.
