<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clinton vetoes Congress's seven-year budget proposals</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Patrick Brogan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011893</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Clinton has vetoed Congress's proposals for balancing the budget over
the next seven years. He said that he would offer his own budget tomorrow.
The Bill was a vast measure, completed over several months' work, revising
every aspect of the American Government, cutting many programmes and
eliminating others entirely. It also cut taxes by $240bn in the seven years.
Most of the money for the tax cut would come from a reduction of $270bn in the
planned expansion of Medicare, the health insurance plan for retired people,
and from Medicaid, the health insurance plan for the poor and disabled. It is
these reductions that are most unpopular and which Mr Clinton has denounced
most strongly.
He agrees, however, that the expansion of Medicare and Medicaid must be slowed.
At the moment they increase by about 10% a year, a rate that cannot be
sustained indefinitely.Both he and the Congress would raise premiums paid by
Medicare recipients, the president to $77 a month in 2000 and the Congress to
$88.90.
Mr Clinton also rejects many of the proposed cuts, particularly cuts in
education, welfare, and environmental protection. He considers them much too
draconian. He restores some $475bn over the seven years, partly by offering a
smaller tax cut, partly by using a different calculation of the rate the
economy might be expected to grow.
This is a crucial question: if the President's more optimistic figures are
believed, it will be fairly easy to balance the budget. Congress prefers to
believe that the economy will grow more slowly, thus raising government revenue
more slowly than the President expects - and making deeper cuts necessary to
balance the budget by 2002.
Washington
</TEXT>
