<DOCID>GH951207-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bruton urges all parties to join preliminary talks</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011895</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IRISH Prime Minister John Bruton yesterday urged all political parties to
co-operate with an international body being established to oversee the
decommissioning of arms in Northern Ireland.
He also called on politicians to apply themselves to preparatory discussions
for all-party talks on the future of Northern Ireland.
Mr Bruton made his double plea in the Dail, the Dublin Parliament, in the face
of rejections spelled out this week by Ulster's two main unionist parties in
response to talks invitations from Ireland's Foreign Minister Dick Spring.
The Irish premier declared: ``We have agreed that we will consider
constructively any practical suggestions that could help to bring all parties
into negotiations.
``Everyone concerned - particularly the parties in Northern Ireland - have
responsibilities to build on this opportunity for substantial forward
movement.''
Mr Bruton indicated he felt the reply from Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble
``left room for exploratory dialogue''.
Mr Trimble had ruled out talks on Northern Ireland with any ``foreign
government''.
Mr Bruton confirmed he would be having bilateral talks on the peace process
with Prime Minister John Major next week during a European heads of government
meeting in Madrid.
Northern Ireland Secretary Sir Patrick Mayhew and Irish Foreign Minister Dick
Spring are to review Ulster peace process developments at a meeting in London
on Friday.
They will consider the response of political parties to invitations to
preliminary discussions on all-party talks, issued by their two Governments
earlier this week.
The invitations followed last week's Downing Street agreement on ways of
advancing the peace process.
Both of Ulster's Unionist parties have turned down the invitations.
Nevertheless, Mr Spring and Sir Patrick will press on with a consideration of
the structure for talks and the prospects for following up last week's visit to
Ireland by United States President Bill Clinton.
</TEXT>
