<DOCNO>GH951207-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Singer begins legal bid</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011896</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER Take That star Robbie Williams yesterday began legal action in the High
Court in a bid to break away from his record company.
He is claiming his contract stops him pursuing a solo career because the
company have exclusive call on his talents and this is an unreasonable
restraint on trade.
The full trial, to be heard before Mr Justice Jacob on February 26 next year,
echoes the long legal battle fought by George Michael against his record
company, Sony Records.
Williams's record company, BMG Records, said his contract with them allows him
to pursue his career and they would be seeking an injunction to stop him going
elsewhere.
Mr Ian Mill, representing BMG, said if Williams wanted to pursue a solo career
how could the company's contract with him - even if it meant he must stay with
them - be restrictive.
</TEXT>
