<DOCNO>GH951207-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dropping in on a hostile giant</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS BOYCE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011897</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is more than 1000 times the size of Earth and almost half a billion miles
away. What feeble sunlight reaches it falls into layer upon layer of gaseous
cloud because it has no solid surface. To top it all, its atmosphere and
general environment would prove fatal to any known living creature.
So why spend a billion pounds and more than six years mission time sending a
probe to one of the most inhospitable places imaginable?
The Americans are at fault. They spent the cash and they put the Galileo probe
into orbit about Jupiter. And, of course, let us not forget that none of this
space nonsense would have amounted to anything if they hadn't taken the humph
at the Soviets launching the first satellite - about the size of a decent
Christmas pudding - into space. Every sensible person knows that all this money
poured down the cosmic plughole could have been much more intelligently spent
here on Earth.
This kind of thinking misses the spot, like a diver hitting the edge of the
swimming pool. It is, like most things that are wrong with the modern world,
again the fault of America. Had the Conquistadors not returned from Central and
South America with ships groaning under the weight of their gold cargoes
perhaps we would not have developed the mind set which expects big bucks from
any and every venture into the unknown.
The point of science is to explore the unknown, to erase those dragons of
ignorance from the mind's great map of what goes on around and within us and
replace them with knowledge.
There is, of course, a well-known spiral here. The more we know, the clearer
our vision of what we call reality, the more dragons we perceive.
This is why we have gone to Jupiter with Galileo. In the 1970s the Voyager
probes streaked past this vast world, bigger than all the other planets of our
solar system scrunched together. Images came back which left astronomers' jaws
swinging in the wind. They discovered that Jupiter has a ring system like
Saturn. They received close-up pictures of atmospheric super-storms which would
swallow the Earth with hardly a burp. They encountered a stunning
electromagnetic field.
They also found its moons were wild, weird and utterly unexpected.
Io, the innermost moon, is the most volcanic place known to humankind. It is so
close to Jupiter that it spins round it in less than two days. By comparison
our moon takes a fortnight to orbit Earth. The tides on Io scarcely compare
with the ones down here, where changes in sea level are measured in feet. The
pull of Jupiter on Io stretches the surface, the crust, out by half a dozen
miles at its equator. This is a spectacular laboratory for those who want to
understand better the way such forces work, the way vulcanism can operate at
these scales, where individual eruptions can be seen from the Hubble telescope
orbiting just above our heads.
Farther out from the colossal planet are Europa and Callisto. The former is a
great ice ball which some suspect to contain an ocean tens of miles deep and
warmed by the same tidal forces which disrupt Io so severely. The interesting
point here is that if such an ocean exists, does it contain life? Not all life
on our world needs sunlight to survive. In fact, there are bizarre microbial
lifeforms which grow around the mouths of underwater volcanoes on the floors of
our own oceans. Many scientists who once pinned their hopes on Mars as an abode
for extraterrestrial life now look to the oceans of Europa instead. How life
started on Earth is a mystery. Will we find some indicators there?
Clues to the secrets of beginnings are scattered about the whole Jovian system.
Callisto, another moon - bigger than the planet Mercury - and Ganymede, farther
out still, look like repositories of answers to the enigmas which still veil
the processes which were at work during the birth of our solar system.
But the vast shrouded giant itself will surrender some of its own secrets when
Galileo's descent package enters the upper layers of the atmosphere today. This
will send back information on those incredible weather systems, the composition
of the gases at various depths and, hopefully, give us some inkling of what
lies way down in the ebb and flow of the liquid metallic hydrogen swirling in
the hot heart of this strange world.
So, let's return to the original question. Why visit Jupiter?
Well, why any scientific experiment? It doesn't matter whether they're
researching the moons of Jupiter or the reproduction techniques of viruses.
What scientists do is prospect the landscape for us and give us information
with which we can build new roads to a slightly improved tomorrow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000051</DOCNO>
