<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Edinburgh joins wonders of the world Anne Johnstone reports how the Athens of the North is living up to its reputation as it becomes a World Heritage Site</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANNE JOHNSTONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011898</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHAT does Auld Reekie have in common with the Taj Mahal, the Grand Canyon and
Mont St Michel? Not much, except that from today two large chunks of the
Scottish capital join the others in qualifying as a World Heritage Site.
In ancient times there were reckoned to be seven wonders of the world. Today
there are 440, according to the scheme's organisers, the World Heritage
Secretariat, a branch of the controversial Paris-based United Nations cultural
agency, Unesco. The list, which takes in both natural and cultural sites, was
begun in 1972 and continues to grow by about 30 a year. To qualify, sites and
monuments must be ``considered to be of such exceptional interest and of such
universal value that protecting them is a concern of all mankind''.
There was general rejoicing yesterday in ``the Athens of the North'', among
planners and conservation bodies at news of Edinburgh's accolade, despite some
confusion as to precisely how the city stood to benefit.
Britain now boasts 14 World Heritage Sites, though the only other one in
Scotland is St Kilda, the group of islands to the west of the Hebrides,
deserted in the 1930s when its dwindling population was reduced to the verge of
starvation. Today its only inhabitants are members of the Royal Artillery.
Yesterday a spokesman for St Kilda's owners, the National Trust for Scotland,
said he couldn't think of any way the archipelago had benefited from its
illustrious designation, beyond the kudos of belonging to such a list of elites.
Like Unesco itself, the World Heritage Secretariat faces a constant funding
crisis and the tiny World Heritage Fund, with barely #2m a year to distribute,
gives grants almost exclusively to the poorest among its 143 member states.
Mr Graham Duncan, the City of Edinburgh Council's director of planning, said
yesterday: ``Though there is no immediate reward, we hope this designation will
give us extra leverage in attracting public funding, including European
funding. It puts us into the top league of cities in terms of conservation.''
The extension of traffic-calming schemes, such as the one recently completed in
the Royal Mile, will be a top priority.
Mr Terrence Levinthal, secretary of the Cockburn Association, Edinburgh's
leading conservation body, said he hoped the award would help raise the
standard of both conservation work and new-build projects: ``We hope that this
designation means that the `just about good enough' approach to planning and
conservation we've sometimes seen here will be deemed no longer acceptable.
We'd hope it will add greater conviction to the imperative of ensuring that
central Edinburgh will be only enhanced and not diminished by future
development. We'd like to see a more holistic approach in considering the
future of these areas.''
Edinburgh will be the biggest urban site in Europe to land the designation.
What impressed the selectors was the juxtaposition of the old city, dominated
by its medieval fortress, and the neo-classical New Town. Both the New Town and
a large part of the Old Town are included in the citation. ``The city has
exerted far-reaching influence over European urban planning,'' said a Unesco
spokeswoman yesterday. The only other British city on the list is Bath.
The decision to invite Edinburgh to join this exclusive club is being announced
today at a four-day meeting of the World Heritage Committee in Berlin. It marks
the end of a 10-year campaign by Historic Scotland and the city council. In
theory, all sites which satisfy the strict criteria laid down and are deemed to
be ``places of equal splendour'' qualify to join the list. In practice, the
process is lengthy and bureaucratic, not to mention rife with political
manoeuvring. For example, the French have 21 designated sites, compared with
Britain's 14 and there are more than three times the number of cultural sites,
compared with natural ones.
``Lists like this are meant to be objective but when you know the process, you
realise they are nothing like objective. In practice, it is the opinions of the
great and the good at any one moment which decide whether an application is
successful,'' says Mr Jim Arnold, manager of New Lanark, Robert Owen's model
industrial town at the Falls of Clyde, which applied to become a World Heritage
Site in 1986 and is still awaiting the outcome.
Although Iron Bridge Gorge in England is a designated site, it is one of around
only 10 industrial sites in the world to have got through the selection
process. Britain can nominate just one site a year and, although the New Lanark
application is still on the shortlist, it is unlikely to get any further until
the International Council of Monuments and Sites completes an assessment of
industrial sites throughout the world.
Probably the most valuable aspect of World Heritage Site designation is the
protection it can offer. At present 17 places, including the historic city of
Dubrovnik and the Florida Everglades, are on a special list of sites in danger.
Earlier this year Unesco intervened dramatically to prevent the Egyptian
government from building a new road close to the Pyramids, the only one of the
seven wonders of the ancient world to have survived.
Ironically, today New Lanark probably needs the sort of protection World
Heritage status can bring more urgently than Edinburgh. The conservation trust
which runs New Lanark is currently locked in a dispute with local landowners,
who have opposed a proposal to extend the area covered by the trust.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Juppe left to stew in his own juice</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICHOLAS POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011899</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nicholas Powell reports from Paris how the embattled French Prime Minister has
few allies, and his own political survival is now at stake
PRIME Minister Alain Juppe has become the loneliest politician in France.
When he made his long-awaited speech to justify his deeply unpopular welfare
reforms in the National Assembly on Tuesday, up to a million workers were
protesting in the streets of French towns. Yet Mr Juppe, who later repeated his
arguments on television, has hardly budged in the face of protest.
He insists his reforms are vital for the survival and the future health of
France's welfare system.
Civil Service pension schemes are going to be the subject of a government White
Paper. But there will be no discussion with unions and no change to the other
reforms. There is, Mr Juppe might have said, no alternative.
The attitude of unions hardened yesterday. With more demonstrations planned
today and no end in sight for the strikes which have been playing havoc with
France's economy and the lives of her citizens for nearly a fortnight, the
Prime Minister is completely entrenched.
His survival and that of his Government is pinned on pushing through the
reforms to the welfare system and the railways. Not only the unions, but the
Socialist opposition, his enemies on the right, and President Chirac himself,
are all watching his slightest move.
The National Assembly debate gave the Socialists, virtually silent since the
beginning of the strikes, the opportunity to rise to the attack. And although
Mr Juppe, thanks to the large right-wing parliamentary majority, was in no
danger of being outvoted, many conservative politicians in the corridors of the
house were critical of the clumsiness, to say the least, with which the reforms
have been imposed on the country.
Part of Mr Juppe's isolation is due to the very mechanisms of the Fifth
Republic created by General de Gaulle in 1958. The Prime Minister is the front
man responsible for implementing presidential policy, who acts as a shield, and
a dispensable shield, for the man in the Elysee Palace.
Whatever behind-the-scenes advice President Chirac may have given Mr Juppe over
recent days, his official and visible support has been sparse.
Mr Chirac retreated from the political fight, spending three days last weekend
at a conference of French-speaking nations in Africa, where he reiterated his
support for the Government's reforms.
He also pointed out that he, as President, had time. While the presidential
mandate runs for another six years, Mr Juppe's job could end tomorrow. If the
situation worsens, sacking the Prime Minister may be the only solution for the
President to save face and retain his authority.
Mr Juppe's political loneliness is also partly self-imposed. His attitude to
the strikes has been to refrain from comment in the press and, until two days
ago, on television. Already highly unpopular on account of indecisive policies
during his first months of office and because of a property scandal, his
standing in the polls is now rock bottom, with barely 30% of people satisfied
with his performance.
Mr Juppe's political enemies, such as his old rival Philippe Seguin, the
Gaullist president of the National Assembly, and, further to the right,
Philippe de Villiers, have also left the Prime Minister to stew in his own
juice by remaining uncharacteristically silent, or obliquely critical, since
the beginning of the strikes.
Former Interior Minister Charles Pasqua, meanwhile, spoke out today to decry
the reforms as ill-prepared and badly presented.
Mr Juppe's stubborn adherence to his reform programme is founded on a solid
belief that France desperately needs to cut back on its public spending.
Juppe's career now depends on a change in public opinion, still mainly
favourable to the strikers, and a quick end to the unrest so that France's
economy, and especially the franc, emerge relatively undamaged.
After Mr Juppe's performances in the National Assembly and on television,
nothing seems less sure. The next week or so will make or break the Prime
Minister.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>More power to the players</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN BEATTIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011900</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The formation of a Scottish arm to RUPA, the Rugby Union Players' Association,
came one step nearer as meetings were held between interested parties in
Edinburgh yesterday, with Gavin Hastings and Keith Robertson two of a potential
three initial representatives for the players in Scotland. Craig Chalmers is
believed to be the third. The SRU are set to give the organisation their full
blessing.
Richard Moon, the Welshman whose idea sparked the formation of the Britain-wide
organisation, held talks with Robertson and Hastings after his arrival in the
capital. I understand that Hastings wanted clarification of the status of any
future role should he become involved.
Moon then held a further meeting with Rob Wainwright, the Scotland captain, and
Craig Chalmers. From there, Robertson and Moon went to Murrayfield to meet Jim
Telfer and Fred McLeod.
``A body like this will be good for all the players in the country,'' said
Craig Chalmers yesterday. ``It will give them representation, and Richard Moon
has had a very positive reaction from both the RFU and the WRU, who have given
him their full backing. We have to have a set-up that protects some of the
younger players, to give them advice. Richard Moon has spoken with the
equivalent football and cricket organisations, and there has been a great deal
of fact finding.''
Telfer expressed his good wishes about the project. ``Both Fred and I told the
players that we were delighted that they had come to us,'' he said. ``It was an
excellent meeting, and very positive, and that is what we will be telling the
committee. We are very glad that they have not gone behind our backs.''
q.I UNDERSTAND that the endless targeting of Scottish players by English clubs
carries on unabated. Latest in a long line is Melrose winger Craig Joiner, who
has been approached by both Newcastle and Wasps. Joiner, a university student
in Edinburgh, could conceivably travel to Newcastle three or more times a week
without affecting his studies too seriously.
``All of our best players are being approached by English clubs,''says players'
agent Ian Mclauchlan. ``Some don't want to move, but if there's enough money
then they will go, as others have in the past. I expect a few more will be
looking for advice.''
English clubs have been phoning other players, among them Graham Shiel, and
many Scottish players have travelled to England to see the facilities at the
bigger clubs.
q.MURRAY Clayton, the former Whitecraigs referee, was across grading the New
Zealand man in charge of the Ireland v Fiji game. It was one heck of a night
after, and in the morning a suitably restrained Neil Francis was walking
guiltily through the corridors of the team hotel.
It transpires that Francis was rooming with Simon Geoghegan, who is an
inveterate snorer. Unable to stop the flying winger from snoring, Francis had
woken up constantly through the night. At last, he saw a glass of water at
Simon's bedside and downed it thirstily.
As he lay there some hours afterwards, Francis was first aware of a punching
sensation in his ribs, and a yelling noise in his ear. He was being punched, by
his room mate indeed. And the yelling noise was: ``What the hell have you done
with my contact lenses?''
q.I RECKON Cartha Queens Park do as much to promote rugby in Glasgow as anyone
else, and I also hear that Grangemouth, in the centre of the country, play the
same role there. Twenty schools have been targeted by their own rugby
development officer Corey Kennett, a New Zealander who can play too - last week
the 24-year-old scored a hat trick of tries against Kilmarnock.
It's yet another concept that has been ``sportsmatched'' by the Sports Council,
doubling the funds available to promote sport. Russell and Aitken, the lawyers,
are the main sponsors of the SRU accredited course, and Midland Bluebird are to
bus the kids to the rugby ground.
q.JIM Telfer was a busy man yesterday. What with all the meetings, and then
being interviewed by six little lads from Balerno school. They were going to
give all their quotes to Brian Meek.
</TEXT>
