<HEADLINE>Laying plans for the Prez</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011902</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOPHISTICATED romantic comedy, once a Hollywood staple, is on offer in Rob
Reiner's super glossy, highly entertaining, but in the end shallow look at what
happens when the man in the White House falls in love, The American President.
The film is at its best when it shows how the President's thinking is done for
him, how there is always an aide at his elbow to prompt him with a name so that
the person encountered is properly flattered, and how his diary is manipulated
by his advisers. It is also interesting when it reveals the ruthless politician
behind the man-of-the-people exterior, but unfortunately at its least
convincing when it gets down to the romantic stuff.
Michael Douglas, playing a good guy for a change, or as good a guy as any
politician who gets to be President of the United States is likely to be, is
Andrew Shepherd, a widower with a terribly understanding teenage daughter. She
actively encourages Daddy to get laid, which is nice for him. Although the film
does not attach political labels to Shepherd, or his opponent, the unscrupulous
Senator Rumson (Richard Dreyfuss) - it is election year - there are no prizes
for guessing which one is the Democrat, which one the Republican.
When Shepherd, with 10 minutes to spare, looks in on a meeting between one of
his aides and a pressure group he wants to influence, he interrupts Sydney Wade
(Annette Bening), an environmental lobbyist, in full flow about his
shortcomings. For him it is love at first sight. She does not know where to
look, and is astounded when later he calls her up and asks for a date.
So how does he go about courting her, this man trapped in the White House?
Reiner began planning his film on the premise that a President today is never
alone, there is always some media nosey parker watching, and things have
changed drastically since the days when John F Kennedy managed to run his
hyperactive love life on the side from the White House without the world
knowing.
While Shepherd's second-time-around romance is deftly handled - he invites her
to a state banquet - Reiner has failed to get to grips with how the media not
merely intrudes into matters which are not its concern, but shapes the agenda
of events. Senator Rumson exploits the affair - ``What a scandal, here is the
father of the nation having sex in the White House while his daughter sleeps
upstairs'' - and Shepherd's poll ratings duly plunge.
But nothing positive is ever done about it by his staff, and the fight back
against this sort of character assassination would have been fascinating to
see. Instead we get romance with Miss Bening, which is fine in its way, but far
from gripping and not a patch on Kevin Kline wooing Sigourney Weaver in Dave,
also about White House amours.
The trouble is that Bening, while undeniably elegant, is really not up to
filling the shoes of the likes of Myrna Loy, Claudette Colbert or Jean Arthur.
She is too twitchy, too eager, and lacks the necessary comic attack. Maybe one
is asking too much, but Miss Weaver made a better stab at it.
Douglas, on the other hand, his locks exquisitely blow-waved, immaculately
suited, is ideally cast. He has managed to slough off the oily, slick, nasty
persona of his sex shocker films like Basic Instinct, and comes over as a man
of some warmth and integrity. His President has the necessary gravitas for the
job, more gravitas, it has to be said, than Bill Clinton can muster, while
Dreyfuss, as his political foe, reeks of smoke-filled rooms and devious doings,
a veritable Tricky Dicky.
Aaron Sorkin's script has its fair share of funny lines, but the sub plot
involving a couple of bills before Congress, one of which, a new anti-gun law,
the President wants passed, the other a green affair she is lobbying for, is
incomprehensible. American audiences may know what is going on, but the
wheeling and dealing left me bothered, bewildered, and far from bewitched.
Martin Sheen, the White House Chief of Staff, Michael J Fox, the Domestic
Policy Adviser, Anna Deavere Smith, the White House Press Secretary, David
Paymer, the resident pollster, and Samantha Mathis, the President's aide, whirl
madly around the great man like a shoal of little fish skittering around a
whale.
These patently difficult scenes, during which the characters talk as they rush
down corridors and through rooms, have been put together by Reiner with great
skill, and undoubtedly convey some impression of what a President's life must
be like. Harassed is the word.
</TEXT>
