<TEXT>
n.A SIMPLE blood test could predict the risk of suffering a stroke, according
to research reported in The Lancet. If the test reveals a high level of amino
acid homocysteine then there is a greater risk within the next 13 years. The
researchers from the Royal Free Hospital, London, examined records from 18
general practices around the country. They found that those with the highest
levels were three times more likely to suffer a stroke than those with the
lowest.
n.OLDER women are to be screened for breast cancer in a new pilot study early
next year. This follows a Health Select Committee report which recommended the
raising of the upper age limit from 64. In the pilot study women up to 69 will
undergo mammography, says a report in GP, the doctors' weekly medical magazine.
n.THOSE suffering from arthritis may be aware that exercise helps, but some
activities are more beneficial than others. A new book, Arthritis: What
Exercise Really Works, by Dava Sobel and Arthur Klein, examines the best. It is
based on more than 1000 people with osteo and rheumatoid arthritis. The results
indicate that a combination of exercise and diet is the most effective
treatment. Copies are available from Robinson Publishing, 7 Kensington Church
Court, London, W84SP, price #5.99.
n.GOOD news for those health professionals who have access to the Internet. A
one-stop medical information shop has just been launched which contains an
entire catalogue of hundreds of CD-ROMS and books, along with an enormous
resource base of health-related issues. We particularly liked the interactive
multi-media CD-ROM on human anatomy. Users can simulate dissection, study
individual structure and examine ethnic make-up. Built by Healthworks Ltd, this
``site'' also hosts Disabilities Access, the on-line based information service
for disabled people and their carers. Here you will find information supplied
by all the leading British charities such as Mind and Mencap. You can also read
their digital magazines. To access the site: http:// www.healthworks.co.uk/
n.SHORT women are more likely to suffer from heart disease: a 14-year study of
more than 121,700 nurses aged between 30 and 55 rated risk according to height.
Women over 5ft 7in tall were 27% less likely to develop angina or have a heart
attack than those who were under 5ft 1in according to a report in the American
Journal of Epidemiology.
n.VERY few parents take the initiative in talking to teenagers about sex, yet a
World Health Organisation report reveals that at least half of all HIV
infections are in the 15-24 age group. Now a new magazine, Talkabout, launched
by the Health Education Board for Scotland, offers practical advice for parents
on how to start discussing the subject. It suggests listening as well as
talking to teenagers, using TV soaps as a possible way of starting a discussion
and advises honesty and openness. Talkabout also suggests parents should not
jump to the conclusion that all teenagers are having sex. While it is true that
research shows that up to half 16-year-olds do have sexual experience, on the
other hand 50% do not. Research shows that sex education at home and school is
likely to encourage youngsters to be more cautious. Copies of Talkabout will be
distributed to health boards throughout Scotland and will be available from
health centres, community centre and surgeries.
</TEXT>
