<HEADLINE>How to get in touch with your feelings</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARK FISHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011905</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I DON'T want to make a point of doing down my own sex, but a consensus of
opinion has grown up that says when it comes to dealing with emotions men are
the hopeless amateurs and women the consummate professionals.
Worse than that, or so the argument goes, while women are busy empathising,
tuning in and generally being all-round sensitive spirits, men wouldn't spot an
emotion if it shook them to the ground and left them with a stomach ulcer.
Which is a point worth bearing in mind.
The choreographer Lloyd Newson said as much after he had a stint in hospital
and noticed that his only visitors were his female friends. ``I realised that
all my relationships with men were about doing things, and all my relationships
with women were about being together,'' he was reported as saying earlier this
year. Furthermore, his friends, both male and female, agreed that in an
emotional crisis it would invariably be a woman to whom they would turn for
support.
Recently the Australian feminist thinker Dale Spender made a similar point as
she promoted her book about women and the Internet. Men, she argued, had made a
computer system that women found intimidating. Had she invented it, she told
one journalist, things would have been the other way round. ``All you would
have to do is make them disclose an emotion as a password,'' she said. ``No man
would ever get in.''
Such sniping at men is, I guess, about as much as we deserve, but there is a
more serious issue at stake. Whatever the social or biological reasons for men
not expressing their feelings - and in evolutionary terms I can think of some
pretty persuasive ones - the things that do not go away are the feelings
themselves.
Women don't have better feelings than men, they're just better at recognising,
reacting and responding to them. The fact that men are less good at that kind
of stuff simply shifts the pressure somewhere else - often to be released in
outbursts of heavy drinking, aggressive sports or a shot of old-fashioned
violence. And whoring of course.
But what do men do when they recognise that for all the tension-release in an
alcoholic binge or a punch-up, these are not things that address the cause of
the tension in the first place?
You're not emotionally equipped to go for a quick weep round at your best
friend's house, you haven't done any sport since your PE teacher said you
lacked basic hand-eye, hand-foot co-ordination, and as far as you can tell
every place offering full-body massage is actually a front for a knocking shop.
Everyone's telling you you've got feelings you should be getting in touch with;
rather fewer are telling us how.
The first time I had a therapeutic massage was five years ago as a Christmas
present. Perhaps that's the best way to start off. I didn't have any physical
complaints, I wasn't aware of any mental tension, I had no great expectations;
it was a present and it sounded like a pleasurable thing to do.
The fact that I have been returning on and off ever since; the fact that after
a few months of sessions I had come face to face with a ``psychosomatic'' pain
I'd spent more than 10 years convincing myself I no longer had; the fact that
even now I view my body (that thing that joins my head to the floor)
differently after each visit, suggests that it's rather more than that.
The official line of the Glasgow-based Society of Holistic Practitioners is
that massage aims to integrate ``the energies of the body, mind and spirit
through a two-way flow of touch and response''.
If that sounds too much like a New Age lifestyle option to you, don't let it
put you off. It is, of course, perfectly acceptable to have a massage purely
for relaxation - as simply and uncomplicatedly as that.
But you don't have to go very deep into it to realise that the body is a
complex receptacle not just of physical strains but emotional tensions as well.
Easing the physical tension can expose an unexpected cargo of forgotten
feelings.
Sometimes that can be scary. One friend of mine stopped being massaged because
he wasn't ready to face what his body was telling him about himself. At other
times it can be an unnerving but revitalising release. I was shocked to find
myself crying during one massage as whatever anxiety I'd somehow locked into my
muscles many years previously was at long last liberated.
Those reactions are two extremes. As often as not there are no blinding
revelations, but rather you find that the knot in your back feels a whole lot
freer, or you notice your voice has dropped an octave because your vocal system
has relaxed. On my most recent visit to my practitioner, Lucinda Cunningham, we
began to realise how much my bodily awareness is centred on my head, like I've
mentally pulled the body's actual physical centre up-wards. It'll take time to
correct something like that, but the theory is that if we do, it will relieve
my head of a good deal of inappropriate physical effort.
As someone whose line of work involves nothing more manual than lifting his
fingers to a keyboard, I tend to have a rather detached view of my body.
Massage helps to make the connections. It's a rare and pleasurable sensation to
discover that your physical identity is just as important as your cerebral one.
``It's a great thing for men to be massaged because it has a quality of
softness that can be quite a challenge to them,'' says Cunningham, who has been
practising for five years. ``It can put them in touch with deep feelings, about
when they were a child, for example, when they were allowed to be loved and
touched.''
Social conditioning denies a whole range of emotional reactions particularly to
men. It's not just that the world at large discourages us from expressing them,
it's that we also discourage ourselves from feeling them.
``In general men have been taught from very early on that feelings are weak,''
says Cunningham. ``Men tend to have a greater investment in their mental
ability. It's a real strain to have to be this big mind all the time.''
I laugh out loud when she suggests that you'll never hear a man say: ``I'm
feeling a bit scared today.'' The idea sounds ludicrous. But why should it? As
an expression of an emotion it would only be honest. But there are some truths
we want neither to say nor to hear.
``Massage gives you permission to have all your feelings,'' says Cunningham.
``It's a relief to be allowed to feel anger or jealousy. No drama, they're your
feelings and they're not bad. It's about being in charge of your feelings
instead of your feelings being in charge of you.''
How you respond to massage, if indeed it's the thing for you at all, depends
very much on you. It's down to your existing physical and mental states and on
the reasons for wanting a massage in the first place.
``Some people come to me and they're very in tune with their bodies and they
immediately feel things,'' Cunningham explains. ``I touch them and they say,
`Oh, I can feel how angry I am in there'. Then they'll drop into their hurt and
they might feel great and their energy will zing. And other people, to begin
with, can't feel anything at all and they're just pleasurably unwinding a
degree of physical tension.''
Importantly, that physical awareness gives you an often more honest indication
of how you are reacting to the world and all its surprises, excitements,
anxieties, passions and problems. The mind is as capable of deceiving itself as
it is of deceiving others, but the body can only tell the truth.
n.The Meadows Chiropractic Clinic, 7 Fingal Place, Edinburgh, 0131 667 4412.
The Whole Works, Jacksons Close, 209 High Street, Edinburgh, 0131 225 8092. A
complete list of practitioners is available from The Registrar, The Society of
Holistic Practitioners, 4 Craig Park, Dennistoun G31 2NA.
</TEXT>
