<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tourist bed tax plan gets airing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011906</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW'S former tourism chief has proposed a #1-a-night bed tax in Scotland
generating an estimated #9m a year to promote the industry.
He also wants tourism administration overhauled and put in the hands of
business leaders away from the ``security blanket of the public sector''.
Mr Eddie Friel made his comments yesterday as he delivered his inaugural
lecture as visiting professor of tourism at Strathclyde University's Scottish
Hotel School.
He also questioned the new structure of area tourist boards, claiming the
Government-led reorganisation was little more than a game of musical chairs
which would do little to harness the dynamism of the Scottish business
community.
``There are, thankfully, individual Scottish companies performing well within
the industry, but what of the plethora of organisations supported by public
funds? One thing is certain, if we were starting with a blank sheet of paper,
the last thing we would draw is what we have today.
``Does anyone really believe that the creation of the Argyll, the Isles, Loch
Lomond, Stirling, and Trossachs Tourist Board was the result of consumer
research into recognised brand names? Or was this the dead hand of bureaucracy
divorced from the market-place?''
Tourism, he insisted, was much too important to be the plaything of amateurs,
and it was terrifying that the new boards were to become statutory bodies.
``Scotland, who exported the ideas inherent in an enterprise culture across the
world, is creating a situation where you will need an Act of Parliament to
remove incompetence,'' he claimed.
He felt that more power should be given to successful business executives so
that tourism could become more accountable and more oriented towards results.
He also brought into question the present funding arrangements of tourist
boards - receiving money from local councils and Government agencies - which he
described as an annual begging bowl principle.
Proposing the bed tax, which operates in many US cities, he estimated that a
#1-a-night tax, with an annual occupancy rate of 50%, would generate over #9m -
#1m more than current local authority funding of tourist boards.
The cash should then be matched by the Government through VAT on tourist
services, to fund a Visit Scotland programme.
Mr Friel argued that the Scottish Tourist Board should then have no financial
input into the area tourist boards, and no control over their management, which
would be freed to create a more dynamic results-oriented tourism sector by
employing more professional managers.
The result would be a more focused concentration on the development of staying
visitors, a basis for funding destination-marketing agencies, allow performance
measurement, improve the quality of customer care, and create recognisable
brand identities for what the boundaries of the area tourist boards should be.
He told the students: ``Tourism is much too important to be the plaything of
amateurs. Places are in the business of marketing the difference, and the
difference is our history, heritage, and culture.
``Scotland has no need to apologise for its history, heritage, and culture, but
in our tourism administration we have chosen a poor delivery mechanism to
convince the world it is worthy of attention.''
A spokesman for the Scottish Tourist Board said it was understandable that such
lectures had to provoke comment, but it was premature to decry the new boards
before they were fully operational.
A widespread consultation exercise showed the majority of people had wanted a
reduction in the number of area tourists boards, which is what was happening,
he said.
The STB was also not in favour of a bed tax as the industry was already heavily
taxed.
</TEXT>
