<HEADLINE>Head of export control forced to retract MoD `restraints' allegations in Iran weapons inquiry DTI climbdown over arms claims</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011907</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Department of Trade and Industry was forced to stage a humiliating
climbdown last night after a senior official claimed Defence Ministers tried to
block access to crucial papers in the arms-to-Iran affair.
The head of the DTI's export control organisation, Dr John Meadway, earlier
told a Commons committee that the Ministry of Defence had placed
``constraints'' on access to papers seized from the arms company at the heart
of the affair.
He said the decision not to allow DTI investigators to see the documents seized
by MoD police followed discussions at ``ministerial level'' between the two
departments.
However, amid signs of a full-scale Whitehall row, the DTI last night issued a
retraction.
``There is no suggestion any efforts were made by the Ministry of Defence to
block access to the papers,'' a DTI spokeswoman said.
Although the then-President of the Board of Trade Michael Heseltine discussed
the papers with Mr Roger Freeman, then a Defence Minister, he was seeking
information only to answer questions in a parliamentary debate.
The inter-departmental dispute marked an extraordinary start to the trade and
industry select committee's arms-to-Iran investigation.
The inquiry follows a Commons statement last June by Mr Heseltine when he
disclosed components for naval guns, made by the BMARC company and licensed for
export to Singapore by the DTI, ``could well'' have been destined for Iran in
contravention of Government guidelines.
The DTI said Dr Meadway had been taken by surprise when MPs on the select
committee started asking him about the papers as they had not been thought
relevant to the department's internal inquiry.
That inquiry had concentrated on how the DTI continued to grant export licences
to BMARC despite receiving specific intelligence in 1988 which could have
linked it to attempts to use Singapore as a diversionary destination in order
to evade restrictions on arms sales to Iran during the Iran-Iraq War.
The DTI inquiry concluded it would have been ``extremely difficult'' for
officials to have connected the intelligence report - which referred to BMARC's
former parent company, the Swiss firm Oerlikon - to BMARC.
Between 1985 and 1991, BMARC submitted 88 export applications listing Singapore
as a final destination and a further six with Singapore as an intermediate
destination.
However, only two people in the DTI had seen the 1988 intelligence report, Dr
Meadway told the committee.
``I think the likelihood is that it didn't ring any alarm bells because it
didn't appear to refer to exports that originated from the UK,'' he said.
``When the report was looked at in isolation, it didn't stand out to make any
of the readers think there was something worrying about this from a UK point of
view.''
Committee chairman Martin O'Neill suggested that Singapore was ``well known''
in the 1980s as a conduit for arms destined for other countries.
Dr Meadway replied: ``We have no documentary evidence to suggest that that was
taken on board in the DTI.''
He admitted, however, it was known that as far back as 1985 Sweden had changed
its policy relating to Singapore because of such concerns.
In the late 1980s, export licence applications had reached a peak of 90,000 a
year, creating tremendous pressure on the 38 licensing staff involved in
processing them.
To the obvious incredulity of some MPs, he said they had had to rely to a large
extent on the honesty of the exporters when they were making applications.
Committee member Roger Berry said: ``It is the easiest thing in the world - a
five-year-old could do it - to get round any restrictions on arms exports in
the UK.''
Dr Meadway replied: ``Obviously the system can be evaded but reputable British
companies don't spend their time doing that.''
</TEXT>
