<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Baron Matthews of Southgate</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN McCOLL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011908</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Baron Matthews of Southgate, born December 5, 1919, died December 5, 1995
WITHIN the hour of winning control of the virtually bankrupt Express Newspapers
in June 30, 1977, Victor Matthews arrived in Fleet Street in his Rolls-Royce
TRA.1, to inspect his new property.
Waiting to greet the new boss from Trafalgar House were the Beaverbrook board
and top management. The alleged carpet-biting Jocelyn Stevens, then
vice-chairman, did the introductions.
When my turn came Jocelyn said: ``Ian McColl heads our Scottish operation.''
There was no handshake. A saturnine Mr Matthews advanced, almost eyeball to
eyeball. In a Cockney accent he demanded: ``Tell me - does the Scottish Daily
Express believe in Dee-volution?
My response: ``Not only 100%, sir, but 1000%.''
My new boss: ``That's a pity - I don't.''
End of conversation. End of the forthright devolution policy laid down by Lord
Beaverbrook and continued by Sir Max Aitken.
At the next main board meeting the devolution issue was discussed. Jocelyn
Stevens said it would never do to have the Scottish and London Daily Express
proclaiming different policies.
I told Chairman Matthews - not yet ennobled - that Lord Beaverbook in the
sixties instructed me to attack the then Dr Beeching's savage rail cuts in
Scotland. This we did with relish and labelled him Butcher Beeching, while the
London Express were praising him.
The London editor soon phoned me to protest: ``What's going on? We're thinking
Dr Beeching is saving the railways.'' I replied: ``I think, sir, perhaps you
should speak to Lord Beaverbrook.'' The editor did not respond.
Chairman Matthews was unimpressed by advocacy.
``You've had your innings,'' he said, ``the Express is against devolution.''
Thus it fell to me to institute the ``No to devo'' campaign - one of the
greatest U-turns in Scottish journalism and the No's won in the 1979
referendum.
Lord Matthews from modest beginnings became chairman of a building firm,
Trollope &amp; Colls, which in turn was taken over by the conglomerate Trafalgar
House, headed by himself and Sir Nigel Broackes.
Later Sir Nigel was to write an astonishing letter to the London Evening
Standard. This said Trafalgar House had bought the Express to give Victor a new
interest in life at a time when personal matters were not exactly going well
for him. Victor Matthews in my view made a success of his Express chairmanship.
Realising that the Daily Express would never again reach the three or four
million circulation mark, he created the Daily Star in Manchester with
virtually the same staff to rival the tabloid brigade of the Sun and Mirror.
Again he succeeded with the expert accounting assistance of Mr Ian Irvine in
unlocking the fabled Reuter gold. This led to a very substantial infusion of
Reuter cash to newspaper shareholders.
How came the unlikely Matthews to boss the Express?
In the last midsummer days of Express control in 1977, millionaire Sir Max
Aitken and his board, which included three other millionaires, agonised over
the need to raise #10m in cash to pay off debts and bank loans.
Three suitors were sought out - Rupert Murdoch, Sir James Goldsmith, Lord
Rothermere - in a series of tortuous negotiations. All three were rejected for
various reasons by the controlling Beaverbrook Foundation.
The unlikely Trafalgar House came into view. At first they were not believed.
What did they know about newspapers? Trafalgar House persisted with an offer of
hard cash with no strings or conditions.
Finally Express Newspapers were bought out by Trafalgar House for an incredible
#14m. In due course Victor, now Lord Matthews of Southgate, sold out to United
Newspapers, headed by Lord Stevens of Ludgate for what is now reckoned to be
worth around #300m.
Victor retired to the Channel Islands with an estimated #8m fortune.
</TEXT>
