<DOCNO>GH951207-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Turkey is free as a bird</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011909</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TURKEY is not going to have its neck wrung at Christmas, after crusading
vegetarian Linda McCartney paid #3000 to save it from ending up stuffed on the
festive table.
The wife of ex-Beatle Paul McCartney out-bid all comers to buy the bird, the
star lot at a livestock auction at Henley-in-Arden, Warwickshire.
She was responding to an appeal from animal lover Janet Taylor.
The turkey, which weighs around 50lb, will celebrate Christmas in comfort at Ms
Taylor's animal sanctuary, and the #3000 goes to a local charity, BRMB Cash For
Kids.
Mrs McCartney, well-known for her campaigning on behalf of animals and her
vegetarian convenience food range, said: ``The only reason I bid as much as I
did was because the money goes to a good cause and I saved a life.''
Free As A Bird - the title of the first Beatles single for 25 years - was
released this week and is in the running for Christmas Number One.
Ms Taylor, who has 350 animals at her 60-acre sanctuary at Broad Green,
Worcestershire, said the bird would have two female turkeys to keep him company.
``I did this because I am appalled that anyone can just walk in off the street
and buy these birds to slaughter themselves.''
</TEXT>
