<DOCNO>GH951207-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Husband back to Bosnia</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011910</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WISHAW man said yesterday he would return to the spot where his wife was
gunned down while on an aid convoy mission to Bosnia.
Mr Alan Witcutt plans to return to the notorious Sniper's Alley in Sarajevo on
an Edinburgh Direct Aid mission.
Yesterday, he revealed he had given up hope of the Bosnian-Serb militia sniper
who killed his wife Christine ever being brought to justice.
Mr Witcutt, 65, said: ``I remember the shooting so vividly, almost as if it
happened yesterday. We were going through this wide boulevard with shells and
gunfire all around. There was a sudden break in the barrage, then I heard a
single shot from a tower block near the road. Christine was in the vehicle
behind mine. I immediately knew something was wrong but we had to keep driving
about another mile to get out of the gunfire.''
The bullet entered through a side window, struck a metal partition and
ricocheted, hitting Mrs Witcutt.
</TEXT>
