<HEADLINE>Contract signed with former Scottish Milk vice-chairman Dansco goes direct to milk producers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS, Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011912</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LANARKSHIRE dairy farmer Jim Brown, former vice-chairman of Scottish Milk, will
from next month be selling his milk to a direct purchaser new to the Scottish
scene - Dansco Dairy Products of Loanhead.
Mr Brown is Dansco's first direct supplier, but the company indicated yesterday
that it was prepared to consider, over time, switching from its existing
Scottish Milk contract to 100% direct supplies.
Peter Eddleston, the company's technical director, confirmed at a news
conference at Mr Brown's farm - Gaindykehead, near Airdrie - that he was in
talks with three other dairy farmers in that area. The company, a subsidiary of
McKain Foods, is also speaking to dairy farmers in Wales about supplies for its
plant there.
Dansco uses 140 million litres of milk a year - 35 million in Scotland - for
the manufacture of mozzarella cheese for the burgeoning pizza market. One
reason for the decision to begin sourcing milk directly from farmers was a lack
of confidence in the ability of the co-operatives (Scottish Milk and Milk
Marque) to meet its demand for a consistent supply of high quality milk, Mr
Eddleston said.
Mr Brown resigned from the board of Scottish Milk in July when it became
apparent he was not going to succeed to the chairmanship. He had earlier
believed he had almost total support from his eight fellow directors.
He conceded that a final split with the co-operative was inevitable but took
consolation from the fact that he was opening a new door for producers. The
Dansco contract was very attractive, he said, and would pay close to 26p a
litre compared to the 24.3p he had received from Scottish Milk in October. Mr
Brown has 140 Holstein cows and produces up to 2500 litres a day.
In the wake of deregulation, producers should look at all the options, he said.
The Dansco contract would reward farmers who produced high quality milk in
hygienic conditions. It was also the first contract in Scotland to pay a bonus
for a level supply pattern, he added.
In contrast, he said, many Scottish Milk suppliers were unhappy at deductions
made from their monthly cheques because of the payments system the co-operative
was using.
Mr Eddleston said that when de-regulation came in last November his company had
had the impression that farmers wanted to support the co-operatives. Dansco
decided not to rock the boat and to buy from them. ``Unfortunately it hasn't
worked,'' he said. ``We find that to make sure of production we have to have a
direct interest. In Scotland we are concerned about getting sufficient milk to
make our product.''
He expected the Dansco price to farmers would be somewhere near the top of the
payments league table.
John Duncan, chairman of Scottish Milk, said last night that it had had no
complaint from Dansco about difficulty in obtaining supplies. In the past,
mozzarella manufacturers had not been at the higher end of the price spectrum.
The news of the arrival of another direct buyer on the scene comes in the wake
of an announcement from the Caledonian Cheese Company at Stranraer that it is
anxious to begin direct sourcing from farms in its area because of a shortage
of supplies.
Mr Duncan said Scottish Milk was facing up to the competition and believed it
could offer a price structure which would make it very difficult for
competitors to draw producers away.
``We have been having a series of meetings with farmers up and down the country
and have had a very positive response,'' he said. ``They believe we are going
the right way about facing up to the challenges.''
</TEXT>
