<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Unitary councils need debt write-off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011914</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH local authority leaders yesterday called on Scottish Secretary Michael
Forsyth to give the new unitary councils a fresh start by writing off the loan
debt which they will inherit from the regions and districts.
Cosla's Labour president, Councillor Rosemary MacKenna, said there was an
English precedent for such a move as the debts of the public water authorities
there had been written off when the industry was privatised.
It also emerged yesterday that the Government was considering writing off the
#1500m debts of the three new Scottish public water authorities but the
Scottish Office insisted this was a technical matter and would not provide them
with any more cash.
Mr Forsyth has already announced that their rises in charges would be capped at
6%.
So far as the new water authorities are concerned, the Scottish Office insists
any debt reduction would mean their external income from grant and other
sources would be reduced to take account of the write-off. The same would apply
to a write-off for council debts, as the amount of money councils receive from
grant would also be reduced because debt charges are funded pound for pound in
this way.
Cosla experts, however, argue that spending is supported only at a level of 85%
and council tax payers have to pick up the difference. Because of this, debt
reduction would have a significant impact.
The background to Cosla's call for debts to be written off is the anger of
council leaders about a clampdown on their debt levels announced last week by
Mr Forsyth.
Cosla has already warned that, as a result of these ``draconian measures'',
council investment in construction would be slashed by more than #100m next
year and double that a year later when 50% of capital receipts had to be used
to pay off debt.
Mrs McKenna said the Scottish Secretary should ``wipe the slate clean'' and
give the councils a fresh start, so they could provide better services for the
people of Scotland.
</TEXT>
