<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000068</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000068</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Donald Patience</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011915</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Donald MacAngus Patience, venture funder; born March 10, 1937, died November
30, 1995
THE death of Donald Patience, in Glasgow on St Andrew's Day, after a brief
illness, robs the Scottish venture capital community of one of its most
inspired and inspiring practitioners. In a sometimes grey world where balance
sheets and business plans can crowd out more human values and priorities,
Donald Patience excelled because he cared deeply about the people he chose to
back and the ventures they were embarked on.
``I like to see the bricks going up,'' he would say, with a chuckle. Or
``That's a great wee company,'' as he added to his already prodigious knowledge
of diverse industries, countless businesses, and the rich human glue which
makes them work.
First at ICFC, the forerunner of development capital group 3i, then from 1982
onwards, as director of the growing investment arm of the Scottish Development
Agency, Patience demonstrated a colourful brilliance of judgment which paid his
employers handsome returns.
Just this year, for example, the sale of Spider Systems to new American owners
netted Scottish Enterprise (the inheritor of the SDA's equity portfolio) a gain
of some #7m. Donald Patience was not infallible. But he produced individual
returns of that magnitude again and again. And, in the process, he helped some
of Scotland's emerging companies - from Inveresk Research and Stagecoach to
Calluna - to grow and flourish.
Donald Patience was also a hugely influential teacher. The school of Patience -
former staff from both his 3i and SDA days - today represents a powerful
network right across the investment industry. Former colleague Dr George
Mathewson of the Royal Bank, who worked with Donald Patience at ICFC and
recruited him into the SDA, says: ``He was a brilliant talent. One of the best
business minds I've ever met.''
Born in the Ross-shire village of Fearn, where he was laid to rest yesterday,
Donald Patience was schooled at Tain Royal Academy and then completed an
honours degree in chemistry at the Dundee campus of St Andrews University. He
spent four years as a research scientist with GEC and a further three as a
production manager with EMI in Middlesex before, in 1967, joining ICFC (3i) as
area manager in the group's Liverpool office.
There he honed his remarkable ability to find the right ventures to back. He
would scour the situations vacant columns to see which local firms were hiring
staff. He was not averse to phoning companies up because he had seen their vans
in the street and liked the look of their livery. After the salesmanship and
the introductions came the deals. Liverpool grew to be second only to London in
the ICFC hierarchy.
Inevitably Donald moved south eventually to manage the entire London office.
Between 1980 and 1982, he was director of FCI, the arm of ICFC devoted to
investments in quoted companies. But the nitty-gritty of general management was
not what inspired him.
Later, at the SDA, he did little to disguise his irrita-   tion at the
political wrangling over whether the agency should be in the venture capital
business at all. For Donald Patience, doing good deals was what mattered. He
had even, George Mathewson recalls, pioneered a scheme in Glasgow to lend money
to youngsters to fund their entrepreneurial instincts.
Scottish Development Finance, as the SDA offshoot was known, was built around
Patience's prodigious personal skills. ``Under his guidance SDF became a
successful and credible player within the venture capital industry in Scotland,
while at the same time helping to create and safeguard many thousands of
jobs,'' says Calum Paterson, SDF's current head.
With the threat that SDF's portfolio might be privatised and the subsequent
transition to Scottish Enterprise, Patience's enthusiasm for the challenge
visibly cooled. In May 1993 he took early retirement and became a corporate
banking consultant to the Royal Bank, with a desk in its Glasgow head office
and a mission to raise the deal flow.      He also retained the
vice-chairmanship of SDF's advisory board.
Donald Patience is survived by his mother, his wife Pat, three daughters
Arlene, Caroline and Louise, and his beloved grandchildren. His legacy to
corporate Scotland will burn bright for years to come.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dutch potato growers invest #3m in brown rot screening</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>COLIN LEYa</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011916</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUTCH potato growers have spent #3m since the beginning of October in an
attempt to protect their #700m-a-year seed and ware industry from the ravages
of brown rot.
From the moment in late September when a Dutch farmer found his country's first
brown rot tuber until now, four teams of specially recruited workers have been
collecting between 6000 and 7000 samples a day to test for the disease. The
screening programme is due to be completed by Christmas, with no Dutch seed
being released for sale either within the Netherlands or for export until a
clean result is recorded for the consignment.
The test and isolation programme, which has so far cost #3m, will be paid for
by growers, with no indication of any contribution being made by the Dutch
government.
``To date we have found brown rot on 46 farms, traceable to clonal contact,''
said Dr Marie-Josee Jenniskens, head of phyto sanitary development at the Dutch
Ministry of Agriculture's Plant Protection Service at Wageningen.
``We found those farms during our first two weeks of testing and have had no
confirmed cases since then.''
Under terms agreed with the EU's plant health standing committee all potatoes
grown within a 3km radius of each of the 46 diseased fields have been subjected
to close examination, an undertaking which immediately affected no fewer than
700 farmers.
The testing procedure for seed involves collecting a small sample from 200
tubers for every 25 tonnes of seed and examining each one for brown rot
bacteria. Any which prove suspect are put through a more detailed examination
using a growth test involving tomato plants.
Seed from the 46 diseased fields has been removed from commerical sale and is
due for disposal under the control of the Plant Protection Service.
``Each of the 46 fields will be removed from potato production for five
years,'' said Dr Jenniskens. ``They will then be put into grass for three years
after which they will be allowed to grow non-potato crops for a further two
years before being allowed to go back into potatoes.''
While farmers in the Netherlands are happy the problem appears to have been
contained, many have had to accept a disrupted programme for grading and sales.
Polders farmer Piet Koekoek was anxious to stress, however, that nothing was
being left to chance on his own farm. ``It has obviously taken us a lot longer
to move our seed this year, sometimes leaving us to wait several days for test
results to come through before we can trade,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Prisons chief hits out `No easy answer' to jail suicides</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011917</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE head of the Scottish Prison Service yesterday warned that simplistic
solutions were not the answer to the spate of suicides in Scotland's only
women's prison.
Three young women have hanged themselves in the remand unit of Cornton Vale
prison, near Stirling, in the past six months. In the most recent incident, a
prisoner was found hanged in her cell on Sunday night. Two other suicides
occurred within a four-day spell in June.
SPS chief executive Eddie Frizzell called a news conference yesterday at the
prison to put the record straight about the latest tragedy, although he
declined to comment in detail on the three deaths as they are under official
investigation.
He said he was concerned at speculation over the reasons for the deaths and the
apparent need to find ``simplistic solutions'' before any full investigations
had been completed.
Talk of a sense of ``crisis'' in the prison was also dismissed, although staff
were distressed and angry at some of the media coverage. Mr Frizzell warned
that speculation about the reasons behind the deaths could increase tension in
Cornton Vale, where he said relationships between prisoners and staff had been
``among the best of any prison in Scotland''.
While the chief executive conceded that Cornton Vale had a higher number of
prisoners considered at risk, he also cited the prison's much higher
staff-prisoner ratio, which was reflected in its being more expensive to run
than other comparable establishments.
There had been only four suicides at the prison since it opened in 1974.
Mr Frizzell made his comments after a three-hour visit to the prison, during
which he chatted to prisoners and staff, mainly in the Romeo remand wing, where
the three deaths occurred.
Mother-of-two Joanne O'Reilly, 26, was found hanging by a bedsheet in her cell
on Sunday. Kelly Holland, 17, and Arlene Elliot, 17, died in June. A fatal
accident inquiry into the deaths of Ms Holland and Ms Elliot has been adjourned
until next month.
Mr Frizzell defended the suicide prevention strategy operated by the SPS, which
is responsible for a prison population of 5800.
Ten suspected or confirmed suicides have occurred this year in Scottish jails,
compared with 16 last year. The previous annual average had been six or seven,
although nine were confirmed in 1992.
The results of two expert studies commissioned by the SPS to assess ways it can
prevent jail suicides are expected early next year. Mr Frizzell spoke of his
determination to establish the underlying reasons for the recent cluster of
deaths at Cornton Vale but emphasised that it was difficult to establish any
common thread to jail suicides.
The general mood in Cornton Vale during his visit had been very sombre, he
said. ``I have seen as many red-eyed staff here today as I have red-eyed
prisoners.'' There was also a mood of anger among staff, who were frustrated
about the ``rush to judgment'' over the cause of the deaths.
``That causes me great concern, because they (the staff) are committed,'' the
chief executive said, pointing out that staff had been working rest-days and
coming in voluntarily to deal with the situation. ``I have seen the best
example anywhere in this service of interaction between staff and prisoners and
care.''
Mr Frizzell rejected suggestions that Cornton Vale was understaffed. ``It is
always the case when something happens that people say we need more staff. But
we have to get away from looking at the question of suicides in prison as being
all about resources. It is about what you do with the resources and whether you
make procedures work or not.''
SPS staff locked up 184 prisoners in Cornton Vale on Tuesday night. Of those,
48 were untried and on remand in the Romeo wing - 41 aged 21 or older and the
other seven younger than 21.
Thirty-one of the prisoners in the Romeo wing were subject to observation. Four
were on strict suicide supervision, 21 supervised every 15 minutes, while six
were checked every hour.
Measures already taken to cut down on suicides include the introduction of a
new type of ``at risk'' cell - 10 of which have been completed at a cost of
#30,000 each. Canvas gowns and blankets have been replaced with non-tear
clothes and sleeping bags, and ``crash packs'' of resuscitation equipment in
prisons have also been introduced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ego trip to oblivion</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011918</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE trials of making low-budget movies are examined in the wickedly funny,
Living in Oblivion, directed by Tom De Cillo who, a few years back, made Johnny
Suede starring Brad Pitt. The pop-eyed, cadaverous Steve Buscemi plays Nick
Reve, director of a low-budget film called, naturally, Living in Oblivion. We
follow his struggles with his cast, his camerman, his confused old mother, who
turns up out of the blue and interrupts filming, and a distinctly bolshie dwarf
who objects strenuously to being used in the fantasy dream sequence.
The film works at a series of levels. We shift between the crew at work in the
studio on Living in Oblivion, to scenes from the film itself, to dreams the
actors are having, the reality being in colour, the imaginary stuff in black
and white. Buscemi holds the whole fragile concoction together with a most
polished performance, abetted by Catherine Keener as Nicole, his leading lady.
The best moment comes when Chad (James Le Gros), the leading man, a truly awful
soap star with an ego as large as his talent is small, plays his big love scene
with Nicole.
It is all about an affair they once had and getting together again, but we
know, although the director does not, that the pair spent the previous night
together, and she hates him, while Chad loves himself. Le Gros gives a
magnificent display of rampant ego, allegedly based on an actor not a million
miles from Brad Pitt.
Since DeCillo asked Pitt to play the part, which he would have done, had he
been free, perhaps that is just gossip, or maybe Pitt is as difficult and dumb
as Chad, in which case he would have agreed to play the role since he would not
would have understood the double send-up. Either way, this is one of the best
and funniest films about movie-making.
Edward Burns's The Brothers McMullen takes a perceptive look at the problems
faced by three brothers, Jack (Jack Mulcahy), Barry (played by Burns) and
Patrick (Mike McGlone), brought up to be good Irish-American Catholic boys
after the death of their father. The film, which Burns also wrote and directed,
opens with their father's funeral at which their mother announces she is off to
Ireland to marry the man she really loves, they must fend for themselves, and
not make the same mistakes she did.
Doing so proves difficult for the trio. Jack, who is happily married, gets an
attack of the seven-year itch and is tempted into a pointless affair with a
neurotic woman; Barry, who is serially single, begins to wonder whether it is
time to settle down with what could be the right girl if only he would stop
wasting her time; while Patrick, throughly confused by what the Church says he
should do, and what he feels like doing, turns to his brothers for advice.
The playing is extremely good and Burns's script is very observant and while
making mock of what it is like to be Irish, American and in thrall to the Pope,
manages to make some serious points as well. Would-be Scots film-makers could
benefit from taking a look at it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
