<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Thumbs down for fish fingers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011919</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONSUMER watchdogs yesterday pointed the finger at children's favourite fish
dish.
Only two out of 27 UK fish finger brands tested contained more than 65% fish,
says a report in the Consumers' Association's Which? magazine.
Bird's Eye Fish Fingers in Crispy Oven Batter were top with 70% fish.
Somerfield Fish Fingers came last with 49.9%.
Other coated fish products had an even poorer fish content, says the report.
Five out of 28 brands of coated fish fillets and steaks tested contained less
than 50% fish.
Some had so little fish they should not be labelled ``fish products'', said
Which?
Bernard Matthews Fish Dinosaurs were worst, with 37% fish. Macfish New Low Fat
Cod Fillets were top with 75.3%.
``In the UK, the minimum meat content of meat products has to be listed on the
label. We think applying a similar rule to coated fish products would help
consumers discover exactly what they are buying,'' said Which?
</TEXT>
