<DOCNO>GH951207-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BBC gets its first foot in the door</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALLAN LAING Entertainments Writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011921</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BBC Scotland is set to gatecrash Edinburgh's big Hogmanay party this year when
it celebrates the arrival of New Year direct from Princes Street.
The traditional before-the-bells programme will be hosted by Lorraine Kelly and
Gordon Kennedy and feature live music from the Kinks, Edwyn Collins, Eddi
Reader, Big Country, and Gary Glitter.
More than 250,000 revellers are expected to attend the capital's big bash and
BBC Scotland will broadcast the show live. Among the guests providing
(pre-recorded) seasonal greetings will be Ronnie Corbett and, two of the
best-known Scots in the business, Paul Gascoigne and Terry Wogan.
In what is one of the biggest nights of the year for Scottish viewers, the
programme will be preceded by a new one-woman show from Dorothy Paul, and the
traditional Hogmanay visit to the manse of Scotland's cheeriest minister, the
Rev.I.M Jolly.
Earlier in the evening, there will be a special tribute to Gavin Hastings, who
retired from international rugby this year, with a film which looks back on his
life and career.
</TEXT>
