<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Ibrox four' escape prosecution</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011922</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RANGERS and Aberdeen footballers who were involved in controversial on-field
incidents during an explosive match between the clubs in Glasgow last month are
not to be prosecuted.
The procurator-fiscal for Glasgow said last night he had considered a police
report on the match at Ibrox on November 11 and had decided ``to take no
proceedings against any person on this occasion''.
A brief statement issued by the Crown Office on the fiscal's behalf did not
name any of the footballers involved - or say how many had figured in
investigations by Strathclyde police - but Rangers players Paul Gascoigne, John
Brown, and Alan McLaren, along with Billy Dodds of Aberdeen, are widely
believed to have been involved in the police investigations.
Meanwhile, Gascoigne was sent off in last night's Champions' League match
between Borussia Dortmund and Rangers in Germany.
He was ordered off after his second bookable offence in the match, apparently
dissent, having earlier been yellow-carded for fouling an opponent.
The decision not to prosecute the four players came just a day after the same
procurator-fiscal confirmed that another Aberdeen player, Stewart McKimmie,
would not be prosecuted for an elbowing incident which led to his being sent
off in a match against Partick Thistle at Firhill in Glasgow last Saturday.
McKimmie, the Aberdeen captain, was also fined #500 by his club.
The four players involved in the match at Ibrox - dubbed the Ibrox Four - were
the latest Scottish footballers to be caught up in the debate about how far the
law should intervene in matters previously assumed to be for football's
governing bodies to sort out.
None of the four was booked in the game but two of them, Gascoigne and Brown,
were suspended for one game by an SFA disciplinary hearing on November 30.
Television viewers saw Gascoigne appear to be involved in several elbowing
incidents in the match and in what some construed as a head-butt.
It was alleged that Gascoigne's reaction to a challenge by John Inglis was
unacceptable and the Rangers midfield player also was involved in another
incident with Paul Bernard. Brown and McLaren got themselves involved in an
incident with Dodds.
Police were asked by Crown officials to provide a report and further inquiries
were then ordered. The final police report was submitted at the end of last
week.
The full statement issued by the Crown Office said: ``The procurator-fiscal has
now considered reports submitted by Strathclyde Police, together with other
relevant material and information relating to incidents at the Rangers-Aberdeen
football match at Ibrox stadium on November 11. ``The procurator-fiscal has
decided to take no proceedings against any person on this occasion.''
Rangers expressed relief that the police investigation into their three players
had been dropped. Speaking before Rangers' match against Borussia Dortmund, the
Ibrox club's vice-chairman, Mr Donald Finlay QC, said: ``Although it has taken
a long time, I am delighted it has come to a conclusion.
``I am a bit concerned that the Stewart McKimmie case could be decided within
24 hours while our own case took longer.''
Mr Findlay said: ``Now the players can get back playing football again without
this hanging over them. Rangers would be happy to attend any meeting with the
relevant authorities to apply guidelines.''
Rangers and every other club and also the SFA, for that matter, still believe
they should be allowed to police football themselves but if procurators-fiscal
are intent on reaching into the game, then guidelines must be laid down.
``We must have clear indications if others are going to interfere in future,''
Mr Findlay said.
The secretary of the Scottish Professional Footballers' Association, Mr Tony
Higgins, was also delighted that investigations into the incidents involving
the players had ended without further action being taken.
``Hopefully the procurator-fiscal will never get involved again but lessons
must be learned by players about their behaviour on the pitch,'' he said.
Meanwhile, Mr Dennis Canavan MP, convener of the all-party Scottish Sport
committee in the House of Commons, has arranged a meeting with the Lord
Advocate, Donald Mackay, and Solicitor-General Paul Cullen, on Tuesday, along
with a delegation from the committee to discuss the role of procurators-fiscal
in sports events, particularly football matches.
He said: ``I can't speak on behalf of the committee before meeting the Lord
Advocate but my own view is that I can well understand that there is no way in
which behaviour on football pitches can be immune from prosecution.
``But, nevertheless, there is considerable public concern about inconsistencies
of recent decisions by procurators-fiscaland I think that it would be helpful
if the Lord Advocate were to publicly state the criteria on which their
decisions are taken whether to prosecute or not.''
Meanwhile, Gascoigne is likely to be given the SFA version of a ``slap on the
wrist'' for his playful slap on the rear which offended a member of the public
so much that he or she wrote, suggesting the Ibrox man was bringing the game
into disrepute.
The complainant saw a picture of Gascoigne pinching the rear end of Hearts
striker Alan Lawrence during the Premier division game at Ibrox on October 21
and, as a result, the executive committee looked into the possibility that the
English internationalist had ``brought the game into disrepute''.
The SFA wrote to Rangers about the incident and the club has responded by
letter but it is understand that the committee's decision, which will probably
be announced today, will be a minor admonition.
Meanwhile, Gascoigne will have to sit through the next two league matches,
against Partick Thistle on Saturday and Motherwell on December 19, as a result
of suspensions imposed by the SFA.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fred Urquhart</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LORN MACINTYRE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011923</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Fred Urquhart, writer; born July 12, 1912, died December 2, 1995
THIS is a season of sad departures for Scottish literature. Elspeth Davie died
recently, and now Fred Urquhart, another of our seriously neglected writers,
has gone.
Here was a young writer who found his own authentic voice, not through the
imposition of university courses, but through the developments of his own
talents in the hard school of life. Born in Edinburgh, he attributed his love
of reading to his granny, who apparently kept fourpenny detective novels in the
pocket of her pinny to dip into during the household chores. On the family's
removal to Wigtownshire he went to Stranraer Academy, transferring to Broughton
Secondary when they moved back to Edinburgh.
Urquhart's father was a chauffeur, and the family's association with big houses
and estates provided Fred with the widest range of social contact for his
future fiction. As he recalled: ``I spent a lot of time in the drawing-rooms
and the servants' halls - the best of both worlds.'' His novel, Palace of Green
Days (1979), is based on childhood years spent at Taymouth Castle, with his
father appearing as the character Jim Lovat.
Fred Urquhart left school at 15 and worked as a bookseller's assistant and
labourer. His first novel, Time Will Knit, was published in 1938, and was
heavily influenced by Virginia Woolf. Urquhart used his fiction as a vehicle
for his pacifism, and like Norman MacCaig, became a conscientious objector in
the Second World War.
Detailed to do agricultural work, he went to the Laurencekirk area and turned
his experiences into classic dialect stories centred on his fictional town of
Auchencairn. Later he was to deny vigorously that he had been influenced by
Lewis Grassic Gibbon in his rural Scottish fiction.
At the war's end Urquhart went to London, and in the congenial pubs of
``Fitzrovia'' met writers and artists - notably James Kirkup, George Barker,
and Robert Colquhoun. His short stories, published in literary magazines, began
to appear in volumes with catchy titles, such as The Last GI Bride Wore Tartan.
George Orwell admired Urquhart's work and John Betjeman gave him fiction to
review.
Though he spent a large part of his life in the South, Urquhart remained a
Scottish writer - but with the eye of a realist, not that of the sentimental
exile. As he said: ``I put the Scots on paper as I see them. I don't think that
some of the stories are very popular in Scotland because the Scots don't want
to see themselves as others see them.''
Urquhart's fiction is distinguished by his masterful use of dialogue and by his
profound understanding of human nature with its humour as well as its sinister
aspects. Probably his greatest gift as a writer is his ability to tell
convincing stories through female characters, as in the two novels The Ferret
was Abraham's Daughter and Jezebel's Dust, about Bessie Hipkiss's escape from
an Edinburgh slum.
His thematic range encompasses present and past, from the ``emotional indecency
of contemporary life'' (Alan Bold's phrase) to historical fiction and
supernatural stories.
In 1947 Fred Urquhart met Peter Wyndham Allen, a former dancer, and they were
to live together for 43 years. Urquhart had a variety of occupations: literary
agent; a reader for MGM of novelettes that would never reach the light of the
screen; a reader and editor for Cassell the publisher, where he rejected
Flannery O'Connor.
The decline in the market for short stories in the post-war world forced him to
turn to reviewing, and to reading for other publishers. Despite these
difficulties he continued to develop his gifts, and his Collected Stories were
published to critical approval in the late 1960s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000077</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000077</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#50,000 bail for baggage handler FBI's open and shut gems case</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES McKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011924</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 19-YEAR-old airline baggage handler was accused of stealing the Duchess of
York's diamond necklace and bracelet yesterday, then was freed from a New York
court on #50,000 bail.
Gilbert Terrero's parents signed his release papers promising to pay should he
abscond.
He is believed to have admitted he was responsible.
``He had no idea of the enormity of what he was getting involved in,'' an FBI
spokesman said. ``He does now.''
The Duchess of York was last night overjoyed that her stolen jewels, a present
from the Queen, had been recovered, although the main piece of her necklace had
been broken up and five diamonds were missing. The FBI was confident they would
be recovered.
The necklace was recovered from a shed at the home of Terrero in Queen's, New
York. The stolen bracelet was earlier found in his locker at JFK airport.
He now faces the possibility of a 10-year prison sentence if found guilty of
theft from an inter-state shipment, a federal offence.
It emerged yesterday that the Duchess had personally carried the gems in her
hand baggage from Washington to New York in the first stage of a journey back
to London.
However, as she caught a Concorde flight to London she entrusted the jewels to
her dresser, Mrs Jane Dunne-Butler, who was catching a later British Airways
flight.
Mrs Dunne-Butler placed the jewels in her luggage, which was unlocked, before
it was loaded into the hold of her London bound aircraft.
The two other parts of the Queen's gift, diamond earrings and a ring, were not
stolen.
Mr James Hallstrom, assist-ant director of the FBI's New York operation, opened
a news conference by declaring: ``We have recovered the Crown Jewels.''
He added: ``All I can say about the offence at this stage is that the bags were
rifled. If it were me I would not put such valuable stuff in the hold.''
Terrero's family yesterday told of their shock at learning of the arrest.
They told how he came home on Monday afternoon with what appeared to be a
handful of ``trinkets''. He showed them to his mother and sister, asking:
``Look at these, do you think they're real?''
His sister looked through a store catalogue to compare them with pictures of
similar pieces, and concluded that at most they were worth ``300 bucks''.
He claimed to have found them while loading cargo into the plane.
The #250,000 jewels were reported missing on Monday evening. The subsequent
investigation involved security services on both sides of the Atlantic,
Scotland Yard, the New York Police Department, and British Airways own security
personnel.
During the investigation, a workmate of Terrerro pointed a finger in his
direction. His locker was searched and the bracelet was found.
The FBI was brought in and agents quickly surrounded his home. He gave
permission for a search without a warrant and the broken up necklace was
discovered in his shed.
A spokesman for the Duchess later described the decision to place the jewels in
the unlocked luggage as ``a mistake''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Geoffrey Cameron</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MILNE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011925</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Geoffrey Cameron, broadcasting executive; born February 5, 1941, died December
2, 1995
GEOFFREY Cameron was a civilised man. He entered the world of broadcast
journalism in Scotland when it was imperfectly understood; he helped it achieve
a respected maturity; and he has left it too soon.
Successive generations of producers and performers owe a debt of gratitude to
Geoff Cameron. He and the BBC grew up together, and those who worked with him
reaped the benefit of a founder's faith in his creations. In a career spanning
30 years of public-service broadcasting, he developed much of the core product
of what is now Radio Scotland, and was launching into the world of independent
production when he died. His name lives on with every transmission of Good
Morning, Scotland; Newsweek; and Eye to Eye.
Geoff arrived at BBC Scotland from newspapers. His first journalistic job was
with the Paisley Express, after leaving Hutchesons' Grammar School. From there,
he joined the Scottish Daily Mail - a background that matched the BBC's image
of the reporting talent the corporation was cautiously introducing to Scottish
living rooms. This was 1964; television worked in black and white; reporters
worked in TV and radio; contracts were issued for the ``Scottish Home Service''.
Geoff Cameron and his colleagues were pioneers - the electronics toolkit that
is ``the media'' was placed in their hands: what we watch and listen to each
day is of their devising.
Geoff chose to apply his talents to radio - an act of faith he never regretted,
despite the growing appeal of TV as the mass medium, with commensurate budgets.
As he pursued a career which culminated in his appointment as editor, current
affairs, Radio Scotland, his progress was marked by programmes distinguished by
their quality of language and intellectual rigour. This claim I make on his
behalf -Geoff was never presumptuous. Those who contributed to his output will
share a memory of unfailing courtesy, coupled with a scrupulous attention to
detail. Some will always be able to call to the mind's eye that patrician head
and jutting jaw shaking gently in polite dismay, as he intoned in the ear of an
errant presenter: ``No, no, no!'' - followed by an elaborate and embarrassed
apology. The technique always worked.
Geoff was a private man in an intensely public profession. But his family life
was rich, and he, Susan and their three children delighted in sharing their
pleasures with their friends.
It is typical of Geoff Cameron that he overcame illness to return to
broadcasting, apparently restored to fitness, indeed, with a raffish air. We
had looked forward, with him, to what he might achieve as an independent. He
was only 54.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A question of growth</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>business comment</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975011927</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE sharp fall in industrial production in October was erratic. The warm
weather played havoc with demand for electricity and gas and drought conditions
impeded water output. North Sea gas fields also suffered.
The bulk of industrial output comes from the manufacturing sector, for which
specific figures are produced. Here production is barely increasing, and may
retreat as destocking gains momentum.
Revisions to earlier industrial production figures could result in third
quarter gross domestic product being revised up a touch, but would still leave
annualised growth at 2%, well below the Treasury's much questioned forecast of
3% next year.
The optimism among Kenneth Clarke's mandarins is largely dependent upon a
forecast of strong growth in consumer spending, which they are projecting will
increase by 3.5% next year. In the third quarter consumer spending rose by
0.7%. The public seem to be spending their money on almost anything except
shopping.
Evidence is now emerging that new car sales have picked up sharply in the last
two months. The Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders claims car
manufacturers' marketing drives are responsible. Cheap finance may have been
the greater catalyst.
There is nothing unusual about economies pausing for breath in mid-cycle. The
key question is whether interests rate should be cut at this stage. The
Americans were quick to do so in July and the current bull market on Wall
Street is largely a testimony to the belief that a soft landing has been
achieved. The Federal Reserve may have more rate cuts up its sleeve.
Here the Chancellor's 3% growth forecast has wrong-footed the pundits. Many are
arguing that its validation necessitates a cut in rates at next week's monetary
meeting. But Kenneth Clarke has denied that his number crunchers were relying
on rate cuts.
The contrary view is that Mr Clarke could hardly demand a cut in rates
immediately after projecting above trend growth next year. City opinion seems
to be moving away from its earlier view of an imminent rate cut, especially
since the Bundesbank stayed its hand last week. The building societies'
quarter-point off mortgage rates has taken some of the pressure off the
Chancellor.
But each piece of evidence that the economy is not living up to the
Chancellor's high hopes will add to the pressure for lower rates, but probably
not until the new year. Top economists reckon it will take at least two
half-point cuts, taking base rates down to 5.75%, to do the trick.
Boxing clever
DESPITE a strong profits performance, Carlton Communications' results have a
defensive air to them as well they might given the group's commitment to
traditional independent television networks.
There are those in the industry who believe the future lies with cable and
satellite and while terrestrial broadcasting is hardly going to fade away it is
a mature market. Carlton is already the largest commercial terrestrial
broadcaster and is unlikely to be allowed to expand further through adding a
third franchise.
Carlton's chairman Michael Green believes firmly that British television
viewers will continue to look to broadcast channels for most of their
entertainment and information for the foreseeable future. This may well be so,
though they will be under increasing pressure if Sky contues to snap up the
rights to leading sporting events. But the growth in the market is undoubtedly
going to come from cable and satellite. So while Carlton is doing well from
programme making it is not clear where the growth is going to come from.
One would think the video and film interests should be growth areas but if they
weren't in the past year they are unlikely to be in future. Video and sound
products is a good high-margin niche area and its future looks more secure.
Carlton's answer is to expand overseas, such as in the booming Asia-Pacific
region, but there seems to be no major deal on the horizon and many companies
want to muscle in there. Mr Green's track record suggests he will pull
something out of the hat to keep growth going but there must be some doubts
over the future, which are already reflected in the share rating of 15 times
historic earnings.
Under orders
WHAT price Ladbroke? Higher than they should be unless there is a bid from Bass
is one thought. The shares rose 2!sp to 160p on a fair turnover yesterday on
speculation that there would be a natural tie-up between the eponymous betting
side and the Bass Coral Racing subsidiary.
However, Coral has recently bought the 114 strong Arthur Prince slightly
up-market betting chain which would only muddy the waters.
More important why should Bass need more brand names with its Holiday Inns
growing at a tremendous rate. Putting this into context, Holiday Inns Worldwide
increased its exposure from 1925 to 2080 units last year and there are at least
500 coming into the group in the current year with already 487 having been
approved.
In contrast, the Ladbroke total of under 170 hotels is relatively insignificant
even if they are highly profitable in that their current financial year outturn
of perhaps about #160m is very much in line with the Holiday Inns result for
last year. Marrying the two profit systems together with franchise competing
with direct ownership raises major problems.
There is also the telling point that a Ladbroke purchase would be earnings
dilutive with its shares trading at around 18 times likely earnings compared
with the Bass ratio for the current year of under 15 times on the basis of
profits rising to #665m.
There are better bets in the market than Ladbroke.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots link in UVF gun plot</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN Home Affairs Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011928</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOYALIST Lindsay Robb and two Scottish followers were yesterday found guilty of
being part of a terror ring supplying guns to the outlawed UVF.
Robb, 28, was a leading figure in the Ulster peace talks with Northern Ireland
Minister Michael Ancram at Stormont earlier this year.
Robb, 28, of Mournview Avenue, Lurgan, Northern Ireland was found guilty at the
High Court in Glasgow. Also convicted of the conspiracy were John Johnston, 49,
of Campbell Crescent, Laurieston, Falkirk; and William McArthur, 41, of Ure
Crescent, Bonnybridge.
Three other men, Francis Hives, 45, of Liverpool; David White, 29, of Northburn
Avenue, Airdie; and Alexander Davidson, 23, of Lurgan, were cleared of the
conspiracy, but found guilty of lesser charges.
White was convicted of possessing two guns; Davidson of having two bullets; and
Hives of handing over two guns for terrorist use.
Lord Sutherland said he would sentence all six in Edinburgh on December 20.
During the 11-day trial, the jury heard how MI5 and Special Branch surveillance
experts targeted suspect terrorists as they devised the gun plot in Tam Bain's
public house in Laurieston, Falkirk.
The three Scots accused, Johnston, McArthur, and White, were followed by police
to a Liverpool bar, the Market Public House, where Hives was the tenant.
There they were handed a home-made machine pistol and a Hungarian-made Browning
type automatic.
The three were arrested on their way back, in an Airdrie suburb.
After officers wearing bullet proof vests ordered the three men from a car at
gunpoint they found a cardboard box in the vehicle, and, neatly wrapped up in
an orange shirt, guns for the loyalist cause.
The court heard that Davidson, the son of a Lothian Labour councillor, was
later caught with two bullets in his car as he got the ferry back to Ulster. He
told police Robb had given them to him in Tam Bain's.
MI5 officers and Special Branch detectives also pulled in Robb.
In public life, Robb was a leading figure in the Progressive Unionist Party.
Although involved earlier this year in peace talks, Robb was a suspected
terrorist Godfather at the head of a group, members of which were responsible
for some of the Province's most horrific loyalist outrages.
It was known that Robb was offered resettlement in Scotland by the RUC after he
gave evidence in an IRA murder trial. He was given #2000 and officially loaned
an automatic pistol with 25 rounds of ammunition for self-protection.
However Robb, who was involved with two Scottish women, did not settle in
Scotland. He did travel extensively throughout the country with the Craigavon
Protestant Boys' Flute Band, playing at various loyalist functions.
MI5 officers watched the comings and goings of Robb as he visited two Scottish
loyalist pubs, the Drumgelloch in Airdrie, locally nicknamed the Drum G, and
Tam Bain's.
Into their snare fell the accused.
MI5 officers who gave evidence for the first time in a Scottish court, their
identities covered by a screen, gave Johnston the code name Speaker's Choice
and McArthur, Bad News.
During the trial the court heard how loyalists raised cash for Ulster prisoners
and their families at so-called UVF dances in the Falkirk area, and were
thanked by UVF ``colour parties'' (two hooded men in full combat gear) for
their help in winning the ``bloody war''.
</TEXT>
