<HEADLINE>Hart to be Kiwi coach</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011930</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEW Zealand rugby union chiefs yesterday named John Hart as the new All Blacks
coach after turning him down three times.
Hart will be New Zealand rugby's first professional coach, with a
performance-related salary package.
He had lost previous battles for the coaching spot against Alex Wyllie in 1988
and Laurie Mains in 1992 and 1994.
Mains guided the All Blacks to the final of the World Cup earlier this year,
where they lost to South Africa.
``The All Blacks are an icon, they are very important to New Zealand and I
think it's important that we maximise whatever we can do in terms of the All
Blacks and what they can do for New Zealand,'' Hart said.
Hart, who played 26 times for Auckland and twice for Taranaki in the 1960s and
70s, celebrated his fiftieth birthday yesterday.
He faces a daunting calendar of fixtures next year, with two tests against
Scotland, one against Western Samoa, two against Australia and five against
South Africa.
</TEXT>
