<TEXT>
A PROGRAMME of hands-on help open to firms which are no longer start-ups but
have not yet the clout of major concerns is being mounted by Dunbartonshire
Enterprise.
It will take the form of two-day skills seminars at the Business Creation
Centre at Clydebank Business Park and will involve practical advice rather than
theory.
The Business Creation Centre is the only ``incubator'' for fledgling firms in
Scotland which provides under one roof, and initially free, office space,
computers, telephones, secretarial back-up, and business advice.
The first seminar starts tomorrow and continues on Monday. It will deal with
raising funding and will involve funders such as the Scottish Office Industry
Department, the Clydesdale Bank, and venture capital group 3i, as well as
companies with their own stories to tell.
According to Danny Cusick, business development executive at the centre, these
companies will be sharing their experiences warts and all.
Speakers at the first seminar will include Ian Steele of Rutherford, Manson &amp;
Dowds; Gillian Mason, business banking manager at the Clydesdale Bank; Ken
Beaty, investment controller at 3i, and Jim Allen of the innovation division at
the Scottish Office Industry Department.
The programme, which is free, will also tackle subjects such as markets and
marketing, selling techniques, financial management and cash flows, the law and
product protection, and VAT and business taxation.
</TEXT>
