<HEADLINE>Home again</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANN SHAW</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011932</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NICHOLAS was in his final year studying sociology at Glasgow University when he
started ``hearing voices'', and writing to newspapers and embassies urging the
world to start a revolution.
It was the beginning of his long descent into mental illness, one from which he
did not emerge for nearly 10 years. During this period he made three suicide
attempts, underwent several spells of compulsory admission to mental hospitals,
and re-ceived electro-convulsive therapy.
Today Nicholas is leading a quiet, normal life, with his own flat in Glasgow's
West End, and taking part three days a week in a computer training programme.
He is also doing some voluntary work. Drug medication and a supportive circle
of family, friends and professional aid have helped him reintegrate into the
community. For Nicholas is one of the succcess stories of people discharged
from long-stay mental hospitals.
Meeting him in Shawpark Resource Centre, Maryhill, it's difficult to believe
that this soft-spoken man, now 37 years old, has been to hell and back. For
Nicholas is one of the country's schizophrenics, an illness little understood
by the public.
He will be among a group of 50 sufferers, between the ages of 18 and 40, taking
part in a year-long pilot project starting next month in Glasgow.
This innovative study, aimed at encouraging schizophrenics to take control over
their illness, is the idea of clinical psychologist Andrew Gumley and
psychiatric nurse David McCrae at Shawpark Resource Centre, in Glasgow's
Maryhill area.
It is based on a personal plan, a detailed booklet drawn up over a three-month
period by patients working in conjunction with a health professional. This
developed because the closure of long-stay mental hospitals and the switch to
``care in the community'' called for more effective ways of handling mental
illness. At the top of the agenda is the realisation that prevention is better
than emergency admission to hospitals.
The key is co-operation with the individual and those suffering from mental
illness are often loath to admit they have a problem. ``You have to work with
them when they are well,'' says McCrae. ``It's too late when they are in the
throes of a psychotic episode.''
The importance of taking medication is spelt out: 70% of those not taking it
will relapse within a year compared to 30% who stay with a regular drug regime.
McCrae says: ``We are trying to get them to control the illness by educating
them about it. An important step is getting them to identify the stress factors
in their lives, and what tactics they have developed for coping with it.
``Often they have never articulated the fact that they do have their own coping
mechanism - maybe it's going for a walk or talking it over with a member of
their family. Once identified, it's a matter of getting them to strengthen
these coping skills so that when they feel another episode starting they know
how to stop it before it becomes a major problem.''
Time and time again stress is mentioned as the trigger factor in a
schizophrenic episode: after losing a job, the end of a relationship,
bereavement or financial worries.
If the year-long project proves successful then personal plans will become
widely available, providing a tool to help sufferers cope with one of the most
crippling of mental disorders.
n.For further information: National Schizophrenia Fellowship (Scotland), 40
Shandwick Place, Edinburgh (0131 226 2025). Link, 58 Fox Street, Glasgow (0141
204 2270). Scottish Association of Mental Health (0130 229 9687). NHS Helpline
(0800 224488).
ANN SHAW
</TEXT>
