<HEADLINE>Kenneth Goldstein</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HAMISH HENDERSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975011933</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Kenneth S Goldstein, folklorist; born in Brooklyn, New York, March 17, 1927,
died in Philadelphia, November 11, 1995
FOLKLORE studies in Britain have, since the nineteenth century, owed a
tremendous amount to American scholars, and in this distinguished line the name
of Kenny Goldstein will certainly not be accounted the least.
Starting in the mid-fiftes as an enterprising record producer, he liaised with
folk singers on this side of the Atlantic such as Ewan MacColl and A.L Lloyd,
and through them he made contact with Scottish ballad singers such as the great
Jeannie Robertson.
This was at a time when the BBC and British record companies were largely
ignoring our native traditional song; consequently, his work in this field may
be said to have played an important part in the rapidly developing modern folk
revival.
In 1959 he was awarded a Fulbright scholarship, and was accepted by the School
of Scottish Studies of Edinburgh University as a field-worker; the school
directed him to the Aberdeenshire village of Fetterangus, where he was
introduced to the notable singing family of ``traveller'' Stewarts, and
particularly to the magnificent ballad singer Lucy Stewart, whom he made the
principal subject of his study.
Establishing himself with a hospitable family in Strichen, he shortly built up
a chain of useful informants, and during his year in Buchan he regularly sent
back valuable tapes of songs, stories, and local legends to Edinburgh.
Among the dozens of LPs which he masterminded, one outstanding one was Lucy
Stewart's Classical Ballads (Folkways SG3519). It includes superlative versions
of the Battle of Harlaw, Tifty's Annie (The Trumpeter of Fyvie), The Laird o'
Drum, The Bonny Hoose o' Airlie, and Barbary Allen.
Another favourite of my own is The Merry Muses of Caledonia, as sung by Ewan
MacColl. Kenny's notes to this fine LP are a real contribution to bawdy ballad
scholarship.
His experiences in the North-east provided a firm basis for his first
publication in book form, A Guide for Field Workers in Folklore, which appeared
in the States in 1964; it was for this work that he was awarded a PhD by the
University of Pennsylvania.
Although he took a keen interest in folklore researches in other parts of
Britain and Ireland, it was Scotland which captured his allegiance - indeed,
one might almost say his devotion - and in later years he returned many times
to Aberdeenshire.
Kenny's wife Rochelle - his staunch comrade in arms throughout his career -
survives him.
</TEXT>
