<HEADLINE>Look to future, Scots warned</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011934</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS in Scotland should be asking pointed questions about how devolution
could affect it, the chairman of CBI Scotland, Mr Andrew Cubie, said yesterday.
Mr Cubie said that with political parties seeking to set out constitutional
conditions, business ``should be involved in issues of public policy, and
should be seeking the fullest information on the impact of proposals''.
Earlier, at a conference in Edinburgh, organised by Sybase and Gamut
Technologies, Mr Cubie said that new technology had to be embraced, otherwise
the prospects of business growth into the next century would be ``gloomy''.
``There must be an enthusiasm to embrace technological change,'' he said,
adding: ``I am positive that if we can, on a much wider basis, particularly
with small or medium-sized businesses, embrace quality and training, the future
augurs well.''
Mr Cubie said a competitive edge had to be achieved for businesses to survive
and flourish.
For that reason, he said, knowledge was essential.``Without knowledge, business
is stuck. Too many businesses look at their historic effort, but budgeting and
corporate systems are moving on.''
He recommended that there should be moves made in database planning,
recommending that those involved in venture capital should be encouraged by
innovative thinking.
A spokeswoman for Gamut said that despite heavy investment in computer
technology, many organisations were still unable to analyse their markets
effectively and quickly.
The new system of ``data warehousing'' was designed specifically for use by
senior executives and business users, allowing information on manufacturing
costs, market share, and customer opinion.
</TEXT>
