<HEADLINE>Nato billions in poker pot</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ian bruce</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011935</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PEACE is a commodity which will not come cheaply in Bosnia this winter. In
financial terms, it will cost Nato an estimated #3 billion to police the
fragile cease-fire lines for a year. Goodwill and stability may be more
expensive still.
American involvement is the major political stake in the game. Facing a
re-election fight, President Clinton has committed 20,000 ground troops to an
international effort which is Nato-led but also involves Russian and other
non-aligned forces.
At one and the same time, it is Nato's and Clinton's finest hour. Nato is
fielding an army in a potential combat zone for the first time in its history.
The alliance may also have found a reason to believe in itself for the first
time since the end of the Cold War.
Clinton has decided to ante-up for the poker game of his career. He has
domestic budgetary problems which would become terminal to his chances of a
return to the White House if bodybags start coming back to smalltown America.
It is a supreme gamble.
Britain's contribution to the new force is largely in place. Most of its
8000-man contingent currently on call to the UN's Protection Force will simply
change berets and allegiance. They will be reinforced by tanks, heavy
artillery, helicopter gunships and the other paraphernalia of a combat division
numbering close to 13,000.
UK personnel will also comprise about 60% of the headquarters staff of the new
Nato Implementation Force (I-For) contingent in Sarajevo. The headquarters of
the 3rd UK Division will fly out to supervise the deployment of troops in
north-western Bosnia, Britain's assigned sector.
The French are to step up their current deployment of 6600 soldiers to 10,000
men, including naval, air force and support teams. France's territorial
responsibility will be Sector South, including the failed safe havens of
Sarajevo, Mostar, and Gorazde. French and Italian combat groups totalling 4000
men will serve under French command.
The US First Armoured Division, the spearhead of UN victory in the Gulf war,
will take responsibility for the rest of the shattered country. Historically,
2500 Russian troops will operate under its command, as well as German armoured
cavalry and mechanised infantry.
This single, beefed-up division will have almost as much firepower as the
entire British Army combined. Its striking power is awesome, with
multiple-launch rocket batteries, long-range artillery, strike helicopters and
the back-up of fighter-bombers based in Italy.
But it is also the most vulnerable part of the alliance. If the Bosnian Serbs
decide to become awkward, it is the Americans who must be the logical targets
for a guerrilla war which could scupper the entire effort.
Tanks and helicopters are the essential and impressive hi-tech tools of modern
war. In the wide-open spaces of the Saudi and Iraqi deserts, they reigned
supreme, killing targets at ranges in excess of two miles.
However, in the confined, mountainous hinterland of central Bosnia in winter,
their effectiveness could be reduced to the point where a handful of guerrilla
fighters hold the whip hand.
On paper, Nato is sending an unstoppable force against fragile and ill-armed
militiamen. It should be one-way traffic. In clear weather, it would be,
inevitably, a one-sided fight.
Life, is, as they say, not like that. The timing is wrong for the application
of what modern military strategists describe as ``surgical force''. Winter
weather will close down most of the options offered by air power. Despite
laser-guidance and ``smart'' weapons, pilots cannot hit what they cannot see.
The use of punitive and pinpoint-accurate artillery or missile strikes is also
limited by the field of vision. The ``collateral damage'' of civilian
casualties must be avoided at all costs.
As the UN's complex, contradictory and nonsensical rules of engagement are
scrapped overnight, Nato spokesmen say they will adopt a more robust system of
self-defence. Breaches of the cease-fire will be met with force. But it remains
a theoretical ideal.
If Bosnian Serb commander General Ratko Mladic decides to resist the imposition
of the US-brokered deal, his window of opportunity will open within the next
two months as Nato's closes with the coming of cloud cover.
Mladic, a manipulative and single-minded soldier, has anything up to 80,000 men
under arms. Most will follow him after four years of almost continuous victory.
Some will follow to avoid the possibility of trial as war criminals.
He is the architect of Greater Serbia, the conqueror of the Croat Krajina, the
man who shattered the myth of UN safe havens in Bosnia. He is undisputed master
of the Bosnian Serb army, but he is not entirely crazy.
Mladic knows that he can no longer depend on the vital aid of Serbia itself.
President Milosevic, his sponsor, can no longer afford to buck international
opinion. More to the point, Serbia cannot afford the reimposition of
international sanctions.
The general now has a limited timescale, coupled with a limited ammunition
stock, to make his own deal with the world. His options for giving Nato and the
US a bloody nose remain numerous. A guerrilla campaign in terrain which favours
the local insurgents is what the Pentagon fears most.
In an ideal world, US forces would simply wait out the winter, ride with the
blows, and respond in the clarity of spring skies with a decisive hand. In
reality, its commanders will be under strict orders to minimise casualties. War
for America is no longer a purely military phenomenon.
Even in a country like the former Yugoslavia, instant media communications
systems can bring every action into the living-rooms of hundreds of millions of
voters. Public perception, shaped by the Falklands and the Gulf, anticipates
short, low-loss conflict.
Clinton, like the Grand Old Duke of York, is about to march Nato to the top of
the hill. Marching it back down again may not be quite so simple.
</TEXT>
