<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011937</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
START-UP losses at Century Radio in Newcastle have been holding back profits at
Border Television.
Television advertising revenue grew by a healthy 12% during the six months to
October 31, but operating profits remained flat at #1.1m.
The Carlisle-based company said the second half of the financial year was
unlikely to bring much improvement.
Century Radio is expected to break even as it enters its second year of
operation, but Border, in common with other ITV stations, is suffering from
lower than expected pre-Christmas advertising revenue.
``It has slowed quite dramatically,'' said finance director Peter Brownlow,
noting it would be lucky to get the same advertising revenue for November as
last year.
Border chairman Melvyn Bragg was cautious about the company's prospects for the
second half. ``While some growth should be maintained, we expect it will be
marginally below that achieved during the first six months,'' he said.
Mr Bragg announced last week that he would step down as chairman at Easter
because of the pressure of other work, but he will stay on as a non-executive
director. A new chairman is being sought.
Although the latest results show no improvement at the operating level, pre-tax
profits rose to #1.1m from #849,000 in the first half of 1994, when they were
hit by an exceptional charge of #297,000. That related to start-up costs at
Century Radio and Scot FM in Edinburgh.
Border sold its 37% stake in Scot FM in May after disposing of a similar
minority stake in Lancaster's Bay Radio last year to pursue a new policy of
controlling radio stations outright.
It should hear the result of its recent application for a radio licence
covering Derby and Nottingham by the end of December. It also plans to apply
for the Yorkshire regional radio licence in February.
Mr Brownlow said Border would consider buying an existing station, but it was
not prepared to pay the high prices these commanded.
He said the company was also attracted by the idea of setting up a local cable
channel in northern England or southern Scotland, which could use its
headquarters in Carlisle as a base.
Border has accumulated #2.5m which it is under increasing pressure to invest.
Mr Brownlow said the board had discussed the idea of a share buy-back, but had
rejected it for the time being.
In the longer term, Border is worried it may fall prey to a takeover. Its main
fear is that the Government will ease restrictions on media ownership,
encouraging a round of bids.
That would leave it looking very vulnerable since its ITV franchise covering
North-west England and southern Scotland is one of the UK's smallest.
Mr Brownlow said Border was wary of its southern neighbour Granada Television,
with which it already shares an advertising sales operation.
If cross-media ownership rules were relaxed it might also become vulnerable to
groups such as Caledonian Publishing, the owner of the Herald and Evening
Times, he added.
Despite a 16% improvement in the interim dividend to 2.3p, Border shares were
unchanged at 217p.
</TEXT>
