<HEADLINE>Indian summer rains heavy on  utility output</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011938</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
R E DUNDAS
Chief Financial Editor
THE Indian summer hit output of the electricity, gas, and water utilities and
production in North Sea gas fields and was largely responsible for a sharp fall
in industrial production in October, according to the Central Statistical
Office.
But its main constituent, manufacturing output, edged ahead, despite signs of
destocking, after declining in September.
Separate figures from the Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders showed a
sharp pick-up in sales of new cars last month.
Overall, industrial production fell by a seasonally adjusted 0.9% in October,
much weaker than had been generally expected. The mild weather was blamed for a
drop of 3.9% in oil and gas extraction between September and October and a 6.4%
decline in the output of the onshore electricity, gas, and water industries.
Electricity, gas, and water output declined by 1.6% in the latest three months
and was 3.7% lower than in the same three months a year.
By contrast, mining and quarrying, which includes oil and gas extraction,
increased by 2.8% in the latest three months and was 3% higher than in the same
three months last year.
The annual rate of increase in industrial production fell back from 0.9% in
September to 0.5%. In the latest three months industrial production grew by
0.3% and was 0.8% higher than in the same three months a year ago.
Revisions to the figures for earlier months increased third quarter industrial
production by 0.2% above previous estimates and opened up the prospect of an
upward revision to the quarter's gross domestic product from 0.4% to 0.5%.
Manufacturing output, which accounts for 84% of industrial production, rose in
line with City forecasts by 0.2% in the month, taking the annual gain to 0.9%
from 0.7% in September. It was also 0.2% ahead in the latest three months
compared to the previous three and 1% higher than in the same three months a
year ago.
There were month-on-month increases in just over half of the manufacturing
industries, including textiles, up 0.6%, and engineering, up 0.8%.
Chemicals output fell by 0.4%, suggesting that the large build-up in stocks in
the sector is beginning to unwind.
Output of the food, drink, and tobacco industries fell by 1%.
In the latest three months, statistically a better guide to the underlying
trend, only engineering is showing a significant rise, 0.5% higher than in the
previous three months. Food, drink, and tobacco fell by 0.7% and textiles by
1.7%.
James Capel's Adam Cole said the underlying trend in manufacturing remained
little better than flat.
``With manufacturers' stocks up #1300m in the second and third quarters, an
imminent recovery in output is unlikely, even if final demand holds up well,''
he added.
``In our view this is exactly were the risks to the Chancellor's bullish 3%
growth forecast lie. However, with further evidence required that 3% is
unachievable, we remain of the view that base rates are more likely to fall
early next year than between now and Christmas.
q  At 143,055, new car registrations in November were 12.77% ahead of the same
month last year, but manufacturers said the increase reflected aggressive
marketing rather than a sudden return of the ``feel good'' factor. Cheap
finance is also readily available.
It was the second month running to show an increase and took total sales for
the first 11 months of the year to 1,873,826 from 1,837,696 in the
corresponding period in 1994 - a gain of 1.97%.
The figures lent credence to the Treasury's view that consumer spending, which
rose by 0.7% in the third quarter, remains strong.
However, SMMT chief executive Ernie Thompson said: ``Although, at first sight,
these figures are encouraging, they largely result from aggressive marketing
initiatives by individual manufacturers to stimulate demand, rather than from a
sudden return of the `feel good' factor following the Budget.''
