<HEADLINE>Lottery hits Rank hard</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011939</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RANK Organisation's operating profits in the 12 months to early November rose
by 11% to #250m, the leisure group reported in a trading update.
Rank noted that the National Lottery had absorbed about all the real increase
in leisure spending and had hit its bingo operations hard.
As a result recreation division profits were down about a quarter in the year
to early November. Smaller clubs are being shut and resources concentrated on
larger units which have been little affected.
Chief executive Michael Gifford declared that the outlook for trading
conditions in 1996 ``appears more favourable for the group's businesses than at
any time since 1990.''
The other divisions have moved ahead, notably leisure, whose profits advanced
40%. Nightclub admissions were 13% ahead after new openings and spend per head
up 5%. Hard Rock cafe also opened new branches in the US.
Film and television saw a 20% advance on the back of higher volumes in photo
processing and better margins. Odeon cinemas benefited from margin improvement
and Pinewood studios had a good year. Holidays were 10% ahead.
Rank Xerox's underlying profits improved but Rank's contribution declined as a
result of the reduction in Rank's stake.
This pushed down overall pre-tax profits for the group from #376m to #360m.
Rank shares gained 16p to 425p on the statement.
</TEXT>
