<HEADLINE>Recipe for park's success</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stewart MacIntosh</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>commercial and industrial property</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011940</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THREE land sales worth a possible #1m should provide a food park with the
recipe for growth. For the last couple of years Motherwell Food Park has been
shoved onto the back burner by the bubbling success of the adjacent Strathclyde
Business Park and nearby enterprise zone sites, but owners Caledonian Land have
shown that the park can still attract inward investors and find a new role for
itself.
In the largest deal, a 4.9-acre site was sold to dairy product producers Robert
Wiseman &amp; Sons Ltd for #375,000. Catering firm Brake Brothers Foodservice Ltd
bought a 3.7-acre site for #360,000. A 2.6-acre site was sold to Man Truck &amp;
Bus (UK) Ltd at an undisclosed price.
However, the average selling price for development land in the other two deals
was #87,000 per acre which, if achieved in the Man Truck deal, would mean a
total price of more than #960,000 for the three sites. Only one vacant plot
remains unsold at the park and letting agents Richard Ellis and J Trevor
Webster are in discussion with a potential purchaser.
Recognising that the park is also home to non-food companies, Caledonian Land
has decided to `re-brand' the industrial estate. From now on it will be known
as Motherwell Food and Technology Park.
Glasgow is responding to the challenge from Lanarkshire by offering specialist
foodpark facilities closer to the city centre. The #12m M8 Foodpark at Port
Dundas has attracted Ambassador Frozen Foods and Dark Island (both part of the
Ambassador Group).
The companies specialise in frozen foods for the catering industry and
currently occupy outmoded premises at Port Dundas. The move into purpose-built
facilities will alow for expansion. When complete the M8 Foodpark, which is
being developed by Glasgow Development Agency and the private sector, will
provide some 140,000 sq ft of modern industrial units designed specifically for
food processors. The scheme is the second initiative aimed specifically at the
food manufacturing industry in Glasgow.
The Glasgow East Foodpark at Cambuslang has already attracted a number of
occupiers, including Carousel Wafers and Joseph Dunn Group.
</TEXT>
