<HEADLINE>Revolt by business leaders CBI faces demand to oppose home rule</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011941</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROMINENT Scots businessmen are expected to demand today that CBI Scotland
drops its neutral course on devolution and declares outright opposition to a
Scottish parliament.
There has been increasing disillusionment among CBI members, who fear business
interests are not best served by the organisation's failure to become involved
in the political debate over constitutional change.
It is also understood that a number of leading companies are considering the
withdrawal of annual subscriptions unless perceived support for Labour is
abandoned.
The Confederation of British Industry's 52-strong Scottish Council, elected by
the grassroots membership, is likely to be urged today at its private meeting
in Glasgow to:
q Oppose the promised Labour-Liberal Democrat parliament with tax raising
powers, and:
q Prepare a list of questions about devolution for Labour leader Tony Blair,
who visits Scotland tomorrow.
One source said: ``A number of prominent Scottish businessmen are very angry,
to say the least, over the bland, neutral stance adopted by an organisation
which is supposed to represent their interests.
``They plan to condemn the timid and weak approach to devolution, and insist
that CBI Scotland comes out strongly against what is on the table in terms of a
Scottish parliament.
``They also want concerns that a Scottish parliament would damage business to
be addressed by Tony Blair, and are preparing a series of questions they
believe he will be unable or unwilling to respond to.''
In August, new chairman Andrew Cubie said he planned to steer a neutral course
on devolution. ``We will involve ourselves in the public policy discussions,
but not in the party political discussions''.
Mr Cubie, a senior partner with an Edinburgh law firm, said the CBI would not
adopt an attitude for or against devolution.
However, the source said the CBI ``must, for businesses' sake, listen, agree a
line, and not just hide behind its apolitical stance. We want strong leadership
on the issues arising from constitutional change.''
Scottish Industry Minister George Kynoch recently called on business leaders to
speak up for the Union to protect growth in manufacturing and record breaking
exports. Newspaper surveys have also claimed that up to 15 leading companies
would ``quit Scotland'' if the Scottish parliament came to pass.
It is well known that some of Scotland's top businesses and CBI Scottish
Council members, including the Weir Group and Scottish and Newcastle, are
opposed to a tax-raising assembly.
CBI director Iain McMillan said last night he was not aware of any move to
reach a formal decision on devolution.
He denied the organisation was ``sitting on the fence'', arguing that it had
said all along that devolution was a constitutional and political matter to be
decided by individual companies, and through the ballot box.
He was also unaware that any Scottish company was considering holding back on
subscriptions, which vary from a few hundred to thousands of pounds.
Lord Goold, chairman of the McTaggart and Mickel building group, and former
Scottish Conservative Party chairman, was equally unaware of today's planned
protests. However, he said: ``I am not happy with the CBI's neutral stance on
devolution as proposed by the Labour Party.''
Lord Goold confirmed that his firm's subscription notice, normally paid
automatically, had been passed to the board for a decision on whether to pay.
He said: ``I know some other firms have done the same''.
</TEXT>
