<HEADLINE>Property capital growth rate slow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stewart MacIntosh</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>commercial and industrial property</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975011943</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S retail, office, and industrial sectors continue to mark time,
according to the Richard Ellis Scottish Monthly Index which is produced
exclusively for the Herald.
Capital growth in the office sector went down by 0.2% in November, producing an
annual growth rate of 0.7%. Retail capital growth stood still during November,
but over the year is some 3.2% higher than 12 months ago. Capital growth in
industrials went up by 0.1% in November, helping to maintain an annual capital
growth rate of 1.0%. Taken together, the three sectors are seeing an annual all
property capital growth rate of 1.6%.
Office rentals went down by 0.2% over the month, returning to similar levels of
a year ago. Retail rentals also stood still, marking some six months of nil
rental growth on Scotland's high streets - although rentals are some 1.2%
higher than they were one year ago. Nor was there any growth in industrial
rents during November. Annual rental growth on the industrial estates is firmly
shuttered up at 0.7%.
Total annual returns in the office and industrial sectors stand at 8.7% and
10.2% respectively, while retail's total annual returns have shaded down from
9.5% to 9.3%. There have been no changes in the average initial yield and
equivalent yields stand at 7.5% and 7.6% respectively, showing no changes in
either figure since July.
