<HEADLINE>Soft-drug users get option of treatment</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011944</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOFT-DRUG offenders in the Highlands will avoid prosecution if they undergo
rehabilitation.
People caught with soft drugs - such as amphetamine and cannabis - will be
offered the option of a six-month course of treatment.
The scheme - launched in Ross-shire this week - is a first for Scotland and
will be extended to Inverness and the rest of the Highlands if successful.
However, procurator-fiscal at Dingwall, Mr David Hingston, insisted the fight
against drug dealers and hard-drug users - who will not be offered the course -
would continue.
Mr Hugh MacMillan, Northern Constabulary's chief constable, welcomed the move
yesterday. He said: ``This is a sensible way of dealing with minor offenders
and every opportunity should be given to assist in rehabilitation.''
Mr Hingston - who now has the power to divert offenders to the Highland
region-run training programme - denied it was a soft option for offenders.
``At this stage, it is primarily, though not exclusively, for first-time
offenders. Those undertaking the programme will have quite some commitment to
make,'' he said.
Mr Hingston added: ``I'm not going soft on drugs - I see it as one possible way
of breaking a habit.
``If they complete the course successfully and commit no further offences,
there will be no conviction for the offence. If they fail to co-operate
properly, I retain the right to prosecute and that person will instantly be
back in court.''
Mr Hingston stressed: ``I'm not prepared to contemplate involving those caught
in possession of Class A drugs like heroin, ecstasy or cannabis oil, nor will
this be offered to people dealing in drugs of any kind.''
The scheme was approved by the Scottish Office after a report by a ministerial
task force under Lord Fraser of Carmyllie. Highland region's social work
department has earmarked cash for the project which will initially deal with
about 20 offenders.
The pilot project will be purely educational and office-based, involving
90-minute group or one-to-one discussions on drug abuse.
</TEXT>
