<HEADLINE>Glasgow suffer as North and Midlands run in eight tries</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRIAN MEEK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011945</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR so long the Cinderella district of Scottish rugby, the North and Midlands
are suddenly having a ball. Last month they dumped the touring Western Samoans,
last night they crushed Glasgow at Beveridge Park, Kirkcaldy - their
biggest-ever win against the city.
The home side ran in eight tries, making light of the Arctic conditions which
included a biting wind and showers of hail. Kenny Harper was an outstanding
scrum half, Rowen Shepherd showed his class at full back and John Kerr's direct
running was a delight.
Even without injured Scotland skipper Rob Wainwright, the North back row
covered the park like a rug. Martin Waite, the Edinburgh Academical flanker,
grabbed two of the tries, David McIvor was an inspirational skipper, and Gareth
Flockhart underlined his promise.
There was not a lot that could be said in Glasgow's favour. Cammy Little
battled bravely at scrum-half but they certainly missed the injured Stirling
trio, Kenny Logan, Ian Jardine, and Kevin McKenzie.
A sizzling Harper break carried on by Flockhart sent Waite to the line for the
opening score. Shepherd converted.
After 16 minutes Calum MacGregor put a penalty goal over for the visitors but
it was short-lived relief.
Mark McKenzie popped up a pass to Flockhart who went over like a plough through
snow. Shepherd converted.
There was a short scare when two sets of lights went out but a Simon Burns try
brightened up the home fans.
MacGregor kicked his second goal yet the flags had barely come down before
Waite crashed through phantom tacklers and Shepherd converted to make it 26-6
at the break.
George Breckenridge, on for Angus Turner, hinted at a Glasgow revival with a
try in the corner.
It was a false dawn.
Kerr, looking as sharp as the frost, hurtled through a gap and Shepherd goaled.
The full back decided to bag a try for himself, rumbling in from all of 50
metres.
A long Harper break gave Burns his second touchdown which Shepherd again
converted.
The last home try was from Alex Carruthers. Little was rewarded for all his
efforts with a consolation try which MacGregor converted. The North and
Midlands were determined to have the last kick and local lad John Mitchell,
another of the replacements, popped over a dropped goal.
North and Midlands - R Shepherd (Melrose); S Burns (Edinburgh Academicals), A
Carruthers (Kirkcaldy), P Rouse (Dundee High School FP), J Kerr (Watsonians); M
McKenzie, K Harper; J Manson, R Cairney (all Stirling County), D Herrington
(Kirkcaldy), S Campbell (Dundee High School FP), S Hamilton (Stirling County),
D McIvor (Edinburgh Academicals), G Flockhart (Stirling County), M Waite
(Edinburgh Academicals).
Glasgow - C Sangster (Stirling County); T Mathewson (Glasgow Academicals), T
Sanderson (GHK), A Garry (Watsonians), A Turner (Stirling County); C MacGregor
(Glasgow Academicals), C Little (GHK); J Gibson (Stirling County), G Bulloch
(West of Scotland), G McIlwham (GHK), M Norval (Stirling County), G Perrett
(West of Scotland), J Brough (Stirling County) , M Begley (Glasgow
Academicals), I Sinclair (Watsonians).
SCORERS: North and Midlands - Shepherd, 1t, 5c; Burns, 2t; Waite, 2t,
Flockhart, 1t; Kerr, 1t; Carruthers, 1t; Mitchell, 1dg. Glasgow - MacGregor,
2p, 1c; Breckenridge, 1t; Little, 1t.
</TEXT>
