<HEADLINE>Catering for all tastes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>COLIN LEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975011946</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Catering for all tastes
LA Cage is an exciting restaurant which has very recently opened up in what
used to be The Crannog eatery, which will be remembered by some discerning
Glasgow diners.
Glasgow catering firm Premiere Cuisine Limited has taken over the complex at
Cheapside Street which includes two complementary establishments, Madame
Gillespie's Cabaret Bar and Madame Gillespie's Night Club, and they have spared
no expense in getting things right in terms of comfort, decor and general
ambience.
Although La Cage is a gay restaurant - believed to be Glasgow's first - manager
Kevin Slaven assures me that being straight is definitely not a problem, and
there's a warm welcome for everyone, straight or gay.
La Cage offers a seductive menu, European in style with the accent on local
Scottish produce, in comfortable, not to say sumptuous surroundings. The theme
is classical, you could say, with more than a touch of the Romanesque. Gilded
mirrors and classical urns and reliefs form a pleasing backdrop to the charming
intimate tables and comfortable cane seats.
The Chef has prepared a mouthwatering menu to tempt the most jaded of palates.
Tantalising starters include Filo Basket of Lobster and Scallops, flavoured
with light lobster and herb fumet, finished with cognac, or Oban Mussels,
flavoured with young garlic and finished with cream, but Warm Salad of Smoked
Duck with crisp seasonal leaves and a light soya and ginger dressing, or
Terrine of Wild Mushrooms and Chicken are equally enticing.
While Scottish seafood, lamb and venison form the backbone of the menu,
vegetarians need not be concerned as there are several savoury dishes just for
them, and puddings are deliciously wicked. Prices are agreeably reasonable too,
music is camp with variations, and a meal at La Cage can be rounded off - by
those with stamina - with a late-night session at next door's Madame
Gillespie's Night Club.
Cheapside Street is quiet and off the beaten track but surprisingly close to
the city centre and Glasgow's major hotels.
La Cage is offering a tasty Christmas menu which will cater for all tastes, not
least those who like to eat simple, straightforward, carefully cooked food
without pretensions. The Christmas menu aims to be easy on your pocket and
offers excellent value for money. La Cage's friendly staff look forward to
seeing you from 6pm until 11pm (last orders) every day of the week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>U-turn on railway sell-off signalled</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011947</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government is understood to be reconsidering its ban on allowing British
Rail to bid for some of the later rail franchises, including ScotRail and the
West Coast Main Line.
The about-turn is designed to salvage its struggling rail privatisation
programme but would highlight the fact there is little genuine outside interest
being shown in the rail franchises, most of which look set to be the subject of
management buy-outs anyway.
Contracts for the first three are due to be signed next week.
They are Great Western Railway, operating out of Paddington, South West Trains
(Waterloo), and London, Tilbury, and Southend (Fenchurch St). At least two will
go to management buy-outs, although Perth-based bus operator Stagecoach may
have undercut South West management by proposing reduced service levels.
These tenders could all have to be renegotiated, however, if the Save Our
Railways pressure group is successful with an application for a judicial review
to be held in the High Court today.
British Rail management has been annoyed at being prevented from bidding for
the franchises so far put out to tender, which include a second tranche headed
by InterCity East Coast.
Its management is mounting a strong bid, as is London and Continental Railways,
a consortium including Richard Branson's Virgin Group. This consortium is also
bidding to build and operate the Channel Tunnel rail link and is keen to bid
for the West Coast Main Line franchise when that is eventually put out to
tender.
Virgin has visions of linking up the West Coast Main Line and the Cross Channel
Rail Link.
Meanwhile, if Save Our Railways is successful at the High Court hearing, the
franchising process would be set back to square one, which must involve weeks
if not months of delay.
</TEXT>
