<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<FLAG>business digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975011948</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW-based Weir Group has landed an order worth #5m to supply water
injection pumps to the Norwegian Draugen field in the Norwegian part of the
North Sea for A/S Norkse Shell. The order is the largest placed with Weir from
the Norwegian sector.
Weir supplies about #100m in oil and gas production supplies throughout the
world each year. The new equipment, which will be manufacturered mainly at Weir
Pumps' facility in Glasgow, is part of a Norske Shell upgrade programme and
will increase oil flow capacity at the site by 45%.
To sell or
not to sell
THE shareholders of Littlewoods, Britain's largest family-owned business meet
today to discuss whether to sell the retail and football pools empire that has
been in the Moores family for three generations. Founder John Moores died two
years ago.
Boardroom battles, competition from the National Lottery and the recession have
depressed earnings and the firm has warned that this year's profits will be
``some way below'' last year's levels. The business has received two bids, one
from a former chief executive Barry Dale and more recently a joint one from
frozen food retailer Iceland and mail order group N Brown. The bids value the
company at around #1200m.
Boots agrees
Croda sale
BOOTS, the pharmacist and retailer, has agreed to buy the European cosmetics
and toiletries business of speciality chemicals firm Croda International for an
undisclosed sum. The acquired operations had net assets at the end of 1994 of
#5.7m.
Scot secures
retail post
SCOT Eddie Thompson has been elected to the management committee and council of
the British Retail Consortium.
Mr Thompson, executive chairman of the Dundee-based Morning Noon &amp; Night
convenience stores chain, will look after the interests of Scotland's 3000
independent food retailers as the Scottish Grocers' Federation's representative.
US order for
Rolls-Royce
ROLLS-Royce has won a #162m order to supply engines for US-built Gulfstream
corporate jets. The total number of Rolls engines ordered for Gulfstream
aircraft now comes to 2300.
</TEXT>
