<HEADLINE>There was not much to set the nerves tingling Exiles' win but rugby loses out at Richmond</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011949</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Exiles got their championship defence rolling with a win but, as a showcase
for the future of the game, this metropolitan chiller left almost everything to
be desired.
Richmond last night had less atmosphere than the moon and it was almost as
cold. Snow flurries provided a seasonal setting but there the Christmas spirit
ended.
At a time when the Scottish Rugby Union is determined to advance the cause of
district rugby, it is difficult not to feel sympathy for the players, whose
international futures are on the line, when they are expected to raise the pace
and tempo of their game when that other major element of top-flight rugby - a
vociferous and aggressive crowd - are conspicuous by their absence.
The Scottish coach David Johnston and selector Colin Fisher, plus A team
manager Douglas Morgan, were in attendance but it would be harsh on players to
base any kind of meaningful judgement on such a desultory display.
Until virtually the last minute of the game, it was devoid of tries and mostly
even of the threat of tries.
The six penalty goals, four from the Exiles' fly-half Stuart Laing and a couple
from his Edinburgh counterpart Ally Donaldson, represented the only points on
the board until Exiles winger Graham Smith had a try in the seventy-eighth
minute.
One player, though, who will feel especially comfortable with his performance
last night is the young Edinburgh Academicals' lock Scott Murray. The
19-year-old - who has already been labelled the best lineout jumer, bar none,
in Scotland by Edinburgh coach Ian Barnes - performed like a jack-in-the-box at
the lineout.
He is so marvellously spring-heeled that his style puts one in mind of the All
Black Ian Jones. At 6ft 6ins, he was conceding a couple of inches to the
Cardiff lock Keith Stewart but, as many a lineout man has discovered before,
size isn't everything.
Edinburgh suffered from a lack of guile and purpose at stand-off, Ally
Donaldson having a decidedly off night, being caught on numerous occasions
behind the gain line and behind his forwards.
There was little action to speak of until the twenty-ninth minute when Stuart
Laing kicked Exiles into the lead with a penalty goal.
Three minutes later Donaldson equalised for Edinburgh with a penalty of his own
but two minutes after that Exiles were back in front with Laing's second
successful penalty attempt.
It sounds fast and furious. It wasn't. Laing's third penalty goal came just on
half time and Exiles went into the second half 9-3 ahead.
After the interval, Laing, Craig, and Aaron James - a New Zealander of Scottish
descent of whom the Exiles expect much in the future - took play deep into
Edinburgh territory but a huge hit by Scott Hastings put paid to that.
Inevitably, though, the penalty was conceded and Laing speared the ball home.
Donaldson failed with a penalty effort of his own before Graham Dall drove
lineout ball and the Exiles were caught offside. With 14 minutes remaining,
Donaldson kicked the penalty goal and the match was still anybody's for the
taking.
Laing hit the post with yet another penalty attempt and Graham Smith was almost
over for a try from the rebound but he was dispossessed and Hastings cleared
the danger.
Two minutes from the end saw the only try of the game. It came from Smith after
Donaldson had muddled and guddled at a ball on his own 22 when it chiefly
required to be put convincingly to touch.
SRU director of rugby Jim Telfer is determined that districts are the way ahead
for the Scottish game. He has a point, but on the evidence of last night, when
admittedly the elements were not playing ball, it is difficult to advance much
of a case beyond saying that if you put 30 of the country's better players on
the park at one time then they might be exposed to a generally higher standard.
Scottish Exiles - G Fraser (London Scottish); M Dods (Northampton), A James
(Wasps), R Eriksson (London Scottish), G Smith (Orrell); S Laing (Instonians);
D Patterson (West Hartlepool); D Hilton (Bath), M Scott (Orrell), P Burnell
(London Scottish) A Nesbit (London Scottish), K Stewart (Cardiff), D Blyth
(Waterloo) E Peters (Bath), S Holmes (London Scottish). Replacements - M Craig
(Leicester) for Eriksson (10m); G Thompson for Dods (60)
Edinburgh - S Lang (Heriot's FP); D Macrae (Boroughmuir), S Hastings
(Watsonians), D Wyllie (Stewart's-Melville), C Glasgow (Heriot's FP); A
Donaldson (Currie), G Burns (Stewart's-Melville); R McNulty
(Stewart's-Melville); G McKelvey (Watsonians), S Paul (Heriot's FP), D Burns
(Boroughmuir), S Murray (Edinburgh Academicals), D Clark (Stewart's-Melville),
S Reid (Boroughmuir), G Dall (Heriot's FP).
Referee - C Henderson (Kelso)
SCORERS: Scottish Exiles - Laing, 4p; Smith, 1t. Edinburgh - Donaldson 2p.
</TEXT>
