<HEADLINE>BREWING Bass on line to create jobs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011950</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BASS is fuelled up to create 4000 jobs throughout Britain in its retail
operations, chairman Sir Ian Prosser said yesterday. Several hundred will be in
Scotland although the precise numbers are not yet available.
Sir Ian was speaking after Britain's second-largest brewer had unveiled
full-year results ahead of market expectations with pre-tax profits rising
11.3% to #599m.
He refused to comment on the rumoured acquisition of Ladbroke which has been
based upon the strength of the balance sheet with gearing just 23% .
The best outcome came from Bass Taverns which raised profits by a sixth to
#180m.
While beer volumes in the full year fell slightly, the recovery seen in the
summer pushed increasing amounts through the larger houses.
Food sales also expanded substantially even if there was a deal of price
promotion which ate into margins.
The hot summer benefited brewing profits by about #5m. Volume was ahead by 0.9%.
Bass has about a 23% market share compared with the 30% of Scottish Courage.
Margins in the off-trade fell but were compensated for by higher throughput in
the supermarket sector.
Britvic soft drinks saw sales rise almost a fifth but margins were under
pressure thanks to the pressures from supermarket own-label products which
vitiated the benefits of the near 10% volume growth.
The overall improvement in beer and pub trading was seen in the south of
England much more so than further north - as already indicated earlier this
week by Scottish &amp; Newastle.
However, Bass is probably taking most pleasure from the performance of the
Holiday Inns division where operating profits improved 9.3% on a 52 week basis
to #64m.
Leisure saw Gala bingo hit by the scratchcard phenomenon while Coral Racing was
helped by the spread of the ``blue'' or upgraded shops which have a higher
turnover although Coral appears to be less generous to the punter than its main
competitors.
The dividend total has been raised 7.6% to 22.7p with a 15.6p final.
Bass shares rose 26p to 695p for a 4.1% yield.
</TEXT>
