<HEADLINE>COMMERCIAL Berisford back in black</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011951</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHAREHOLDERS of Berisford are being rewarded with a dramatically increased
dividend payout after the group moved back into the black.
The acquisition of kitchens and joinery group Magnet and Welbilt of the US,
which makes a variety of commercial cooking equipment, helped the group back
into profit in the year to September 30 with pre-tax earnings of #26.9m against
a #3.2m loss in the previous 12 months.
Chairman John Sclater expressed his confidence that the group would enjoy
further strong progress in the current year. Investors will see their payout
jump from 0.5p per share to 3p on earnings per share of 14p against a previous
loss of 2.1p.
Mr Sclater was reserved in his praise for Magnet, which he said had done
creditably in a difficult market.
Magnet's sales amounted to #185m, a 6% increase.
Cost reductions had played a major part in the division's performance, said Mr
Sclater, who emphasised its trading position next year depended on the housing
market.
The group boosted its cash pile by #57.1m to #111.3m and Mr Sclater emphasised
that while its immediate task was to develop existing businesses, its cash
resources meant it could hunt for further acquisitions.
</TEXT>
