<DOCNO>GH951207-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Let's put politicians on transfer market</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Brian Meek</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975011953</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MY good friend Struan Stevenson, whom I hope to see installed as the next MP
for Dumfries, took me to lunch the other day and we listened to the words of Mr
Poul Schluter, a former Prime Minister of Denmark and currently a
vice-president of the European Parliament. He spoke, made jokes, and answered
questions in English which, as Mickey Hirst observed, should be a lesson to us
all.
The ex-Premier reminded his audience that the Danes had two referendums before
agreeing to join the Union. ``We did not get it right the first time!'' He was
grateful for the help of Sir Edward Heath during the run-up to the second
ballot.
Mr Schluter obviously had another of our Prime Ministers, Sir Winston
Churchill, as one of his heroes and he came up with a story that I had not
heard before. At a ball given by the King and Queen in Buckingham Palace,
Ernest Bevin, then the Foreign Secretary, was seen to be taking the floor.
``Look, Mr Churchill,'' instructed a companion of Winnie's, ``Mr Bevin is
dancing.''
``No,'' came the growl in reply, ``it is just him doing the Labour movement.''
I don't know any jokes about Danish leaders.
Mr Schluter did not have unstinting praise for the European institutions. ``I
do not believe they work as well as they should - nevertheless, with 15 nations
and 11 languages it is perhaps a miracle that the Union works at all. Yet it is
comforting to reflect that three of the member states - Greece, Portugal, and
Spain - were until comparatively recently military dictatorships and now have
democratic constitutions and that another 10-15 former communist-controlled
countries are lining up to join.''
He had, however, a warning for all of us in Europe. ``We must not allow others
to exploit our inventions. The EU, for understandable reasons, has invested
much of its wealth into agriculture; the rest of the world, and in particular
the Far East, has gone for new technology.
``I do not think it is insignificant that Swissair has sited its ticket-issuing
office in India. We must learn to create new industries in Europe, we must
modernise and reconstruct or we will be the losers.''
The Danish statesman was not slow to criticise some of the actions of his
European colleagues. ``I think it is quite ridiculous, for instance, that every
member state spends money on urging people to stop smoking when, at the same
time, the EU pays out one billion Ecus every year to the tobacco industry.''
Yes, he agreed, it was ludicrous that there should be Parliaments in both
Brussels and Strasbourg.
The problem was, he confessed, that long before his country, or indeed ours,
had become members a treaty had been signed with the French guaranteeing them
an Assembly. Perhaps majority voting might end this farce?
The evil Ecu having been raised, this being a largely Tory audience, the way
was clear for someone to ask about a common currency. Mr Schluter did not
flinch: ``I favour it, but every country must have the right to make up its own
mind.
``You know the currency does not have to look the same throughout the Union. If
you want to keep the Queen's head on the notes, and we might want to as well,
why should there be any difficulty?
``But I will tell you this: America would never have become the industrial
giant that it has with 15 different currencies.
``Having said that I am not campaigning for a federal Europe. Most people find
the European Parliament far less interesting than their own national
legislature and that is how it should be.
``In 10 or 15 years' time the Union will have enlarged but it will still be
made up of independent nations, free to pursue their own policies. I just hope
we are all ready for the challenge of the next decade.
``My country is small but being in the EU gives us influence. It has been my
experience that if you can mount good arguments you always have a chance of
winning.''
He was a very civilised chap, just the dish to set before the sceptics who are
so afraid of losing their wee bit of sovereignty. Indeed, as I came away I said
to another friend that it might be no bad thing if politicians were
transferable, rather like football players.
President Clinton, it seemed to me, performed with much more elan in Belfast
and Dublin than he ever has in middle America. Mrs Thatcher was practically a
saint in the States and John Major is probably a huge hit in Bangladesh.
Could they not all be sent, even for a short spell, where someone actually
wants them?
What is it you need in Mother Russia? Someone to tackle organised crime, rid
the country of the Mafia? Got the very chap for you - tough on crime, tough on
the causes of crime. Requires a different kind of school for his kid but
otherwise easily satisfied as long as he has everything his own way.
Psst - want a penny off income tax in Thailand? We have this Chancellor
chappie, likes a wet and the odd puff, but can he cook the books . . .
Strikes? You are having a lot of public sector strikes in France? Yeah, we used
to have them so we will send you the grand Mr Heseltine who can scatter a
picket line at 20 paces. And he will sell your trains to caring capitalists.
Now - what am I bid for Dennis Skinner? Good for a laugh, does a turn at
question time each week, always wears the same clothes. Tell you what, you can
have him in a free transfer, he does not quite fit in with New Labour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>RETAILING Kingfisher sees sales leap</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011954</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KINGFISHER, whose trading formats include B&amp;Q, Woolworths and Comet, increased
its sales by 4.8% in the 13 weeks to October 28. All its principal businesses
are said to have contributed to the rise.
The prolonged hot summer hit sales in Woolworths but business recovered in
September and October. B&amp;Q grew its sales in what remains a difficult DIY
sector and its market share rose. The Warehouse formats, with their more
extensive product ranges, continued to out-perform the B&amp;Q Supercentres.
Market share and sales also improved in the loss-making Comet electricals
business. The introduction of multi-media PCs into 95 stores by the end of
October boosted sales. The performance of Darty, its French electricals
business, was basically static.
Superdrug's strategic move away from household and food to health and beauty is
paying off in terms of increased sales.
Despite the good news Kingfisher shares fell 7p to 508p.
</TEXT>
