<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Margaret Vaughan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975011957</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF YOU feel a sense of deep foreboding next time you hand your family snaps in
to Boots you will not be alone. The announcement that no action is to be taken
against television newsreader Julia Somerville and her partner Jeremy Dixon
over photographs of her young daughter in the bath should be an end to a
disgraceful episode.
So where does this deep sense of residual unease come from?
It's not from the actions of the staff member who developed the pictures and
didn't share Mr Dixon's artistic pretensions. One man's art is, after all,
another man's dirty picture. And isn't vigilance in child protection urged upon
all of us? Hard as we may try, we cannot have it both ways.
It was heavy-handed if not necessarily wrong, when the store called in the
police, that they should arrive mob-handed in a crowded store to pounce when Mr
Dixon, all unsuspecting, arrived to pick up his film.
Nor was it entirely wrong that the force should call on the massed experience
of officers in the child pornography and paedophilia unit as well as offices
from an expert child protection team to scrutinise the photos in fine detail.
If they had chosen to ignore it, because he was a professional, smartly-dressed
man instead of some mythic slobbering perv in a dirty mac, that surely would be
more worrying.
That the lab assistant who clyped was induced by a fat cheque to sell his
exclusive story to the Sun says more about the ethics of those who paid him to
blab than it does about the greed of a lowly-paid worker. So, sadly, it's not
that.
What about the couple's eight-hour interrogation at a police station? Seems
tough, but it was a delicate investigation was it not?
And then the story was leaked. Ms Somerville blames Scotland Yard for leaking
details of her arrest which she says caused her great distress and public
humiliation. It's no surprise that someone sneaked. Happens all the time,
police stations being to secrets what leaky sieves are to a pot of peas.
But then the story, in all it's lip-smacking, salacious detail, was splashed
across the pages of every newspaper. Does disquiet stem from the usual tatty
problem of such stories of sexual scandal, the old chestnut of prurience
masquerading as puritanism? A distaste for the kind of exposure, with an
element of cruelty, that delights in seeing a celebrity twist in the wind,
while simultaneously, on the comment pages, clucking piously over the appalling
ordeal of poor Julia Somerville? Perhaps it's partly that.
BUT surely the most deplorable aspect of this whole sad, sordid story is in
danger of being missed. In case we forget, the real victim of this grotesque
tale is a seven-year-old child.
Her trust was betrayed. By the man who took the photographs, however
innocently. By the newspapers who identified her, whose flabby excuse will be
``oh well everyone else used Julia Somerville's name so why should we miss
out?''
If the Press Complaints Commission had any balls, if its current chairman
stopped playing footsie with the royal family and worrying about the finer
feelings of Rupert Murdoch long enough, he would act on an abject failure to
protect the interests of a child whose privacy has been invaded in the most
deplorable way. It is she who must live with the consequences. The humiliation,
shame, and ridicule will be her distressing legacy.
In this case, Julia Somerville and her partner were entirely innocent. The
damage was done not by the investigation of the case but by the manner in which
it was reported. The English Attorney-General continues to cluck over such
reporting but does not act to stop it. He must bear some responsibility.
There is one more feature of this sordid episode that causes unease and it's
this: we continue to hold a strangely ambivalent view of the sexual abuse of
children, giving off confused and conflicting signals.
Just as tragic as taking children away from innocent families, on the
half-baked beliefs of those who specialise in cranky theories on bottoms, is a
failure to protect children from parents who are committing serious abuse.
We refuse to believe figures on the sexual abuse of children. We know there is
massive cruelty in the world but this . . . no it cannot be true.
And we continue to lambast the authorities who are seen to fail when they don't
take action (think Cromwell Street) and who are vilified when, in however
hamfisted a manner, they do (think Orkney).
Lastly there is this: somehow the intimacy between children and parents is so
unlike any other kind of intimacy that maybe it's hard for us to comprehend
those who confuse what that intimacy is about. It's time we started trying
harder.
</TEXT>
