<HEADLINE>Spending tops resolutions</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011958</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TELEVISION presenter Jeremy Clarkson is one of of three million people in
Britain expected to start 1996 by making a financial New Year's resolution.
The Top Gear presenter is resolving ``never to open a bank statement'', and
``smoke more'' while ``to back my horse every time it runs'' is the resolve of
BBC football commentator John Motson.
Some 33% of adults are resolved to cut down on their spending generally in the
coming year.
In contrast, 6% said they would try to spend more, while 35% will aim for a
specific item like a car or a holiday in the year ahead, according to survey
findings published recently by IFA Promotion, which promotes professional
independent financial advice.
Just 800,000 of the three million people expected to make financial New Year's
resolutions will stick to them, it predicts.
Other popular financial resolutions include paying off credit card bills,
mentioned by one in 10 people, and sorting out a pension cited by 8%.
Psychologist Dr David Lewis thinks the majority of those announcing New Year's
resolutions make those that are to do with breaking bad habits such as smoking,
nail biting or overeating.
About 12% make bold resolutions intended to shake up their lives, according to
Dr Lewis.
</TEXT>
