<HEADLINE>Stagecoach in train for record subsidy after rail buy-out</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011959</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TRANSPORT
Stagecoach in train for record
subsidy after rail buy-out
PERTH-based bus giant Stagecoach Holdings, which looks set to become the first
private sector company to take over British Rail passenger services, is set to
receive an even greater subsidy than the public sector to run them.
Meanwhile, as if to underline that it is still very much in expansion mode,
Stagecoach yesterday announced the #12.6m acquisition of bus company Cambus
Holdings.which serves the Berkshire and Cambridge and Milton Keynes areas.
Franchising director Roger Salmon is understood to have awarded the South West
Trains franchise, one of the first three to be privatised, to Stagecoach.
It has been claimed that the Perth-based company, which is looking to link bus
and train timetables, as it expands on to the railway lines, will be given a
greater annual subsidy than the #70m which Mr Salmon currently pays to British
Rail.
A spokesman for the Office of Passenger Rail Franchising yesterday pointed out
that it was the bidders, rather than the franchising director, which named
their subsidy.
Bidders state the amount of Government funding they require on the basis of the
minimum service requirements specified by Mr Salmon.
Labour transport spokesman Brian Wilson last night urged the Office of Fair
Trading to investigate the implications of a successful Stagecoach bid before
any contract was signed.
He claimed Stagecoach would have a private monopoly in trains and buses over
large parts of the south of England.
Mr Wilson added that the likelihood of Stagecoach receiving a greater subsidy
exposed the ``ludicrous nature'' of the whole rail privatisation exercise.
Stagecoach executive chairman Brian Souter indicated last week that he
considered the south of England franchises the most attractive.
South West Trains, which operates the regional and commuter network out of
London's Waterloo, is the biggest of the 25 franchises being privatised.
However, with Mr Salmon not expected to announce the result of the South West
Trains auction until next week, Mr Souter would only say yesterday: ``We have
signed confidentiality undertakings and we are not at liberty to discuss the
matter.''
He indicated that the Stagecoach bid had been successful by stating his belief
that a newspaper report, claiming his company had won had come from the team
which made the ``failed management buy-out''.
A victory by Stagecoach would invalidate a previous claim by shipping company
Sea Containers, which last month pulled out of the race for the seven-year
passenger rail franchises, that only management buy-out teams were likely to
win them.
Stagecoach's proposals apparently required the least subsidy and were therefore
cheaper than the joint bid by South West Trains' management and French water
group Compagnie Generale des Eaux.
However, Mr Salmon's decision to set the ``minimum passenger requirements''
below the current level of service is currently being challenged by pressure
group Save the Railways in the High Court. A victory for Save the Railways
could still prompt a re-think.
It is not yet clear whether the Department of Trade and Industry would refer
the takeover to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
The referral decision, when it is taken, will set a precedent for the entire
rail privatisation process.
Stagecoach and Network SouthCentral are gunning for the InterCity East Coast
service between London and Edinburgh and Midland Mainline, which runs trains
between Sheffield and London.
Stagecoach intends to bid for ScotRail, when it is eventually privatised,
although it does not consider it the most attractive train operating company.
Meanwhile, Stagecoach could once again fall foul of the UK competition
authorities as a result of its agreed 350p per share cash bid for Cambus.
Shares in Stagecoach yesterday recorded a new closing high for the year of
288p, after adding 4p.
</TEXT>
