<HEADLINE>Earnings surge for expanding Wiseman</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011960</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FACT FILE
Interim              1995-96        1994-95
Turnover     #58.9m      #49.4m
Pre-tax profit     #3.92m     #2.95m
EPS                4.47p       3.24p
Dividend         1.0p        0.9p
ALAN WISEMAN is a happy man these days as business continues to increase for
Robert Wiseman Dairies. The purchases of the CWS and Hamiltons have raised its
market share to almost 44% and, more important for the longer term, the
Manchester development has been a success.
First-half profits jumped a third to #3.92m on turnover 19% greater at #58.9m.
That figure was struck after a #700,000 provision, largely for around 100
redundancies, against the reorganisation of the CWS operations which cost #6.6m
to acquire. That deal has helped boost Scottish milk volumes to one million
litres a day. The CWS previously sourced its Argyllshire and Dumfrieshire
supplies partly from Scottish Pride.
The Hamilton purchase, which cost #10m, half of which was debt, came just after
the interim period. Its reorganisation costs will be similar to those of the
CWS, although Wiseman is considering whether to use its modern dairy facilities
to produce UHT milk as a diversification from the fresh product.
Doorstep deliveries in Scotland are now down to about 15% but Mr Wiseman
believes they have stabilised.
Already #10m has been spent on the Manchester plant. That has helped Wiseman to
begin supplying liquid milk to 190 Iceland stores in the North of England in
addition to the 60 or so in Scotland which are serviced from local depots.
That will account for 20 million litres of milk annually out of Manchester's
initial production level of 85 million litres. This will double to 170 million
litres by late 1997. The additional capacity will cost just #2m. And there is
the potential to double even that volume through extended shift working.
Already the plant, which is well ahead of schedule, supplies Tesco, Safeway and
Morrison as well as Iceland locally, and negotiations are under way with J
Sainsbury and Asda.
Plans are also afoot to establish depots in Birmingham, Leeds and Liverpool to
supply supermarkets in those areas.
Significantly, supermarket retail prices rose almost universally last weekend
by 2p for a four-pint container, pointing to an easing in margin pressure.
More acquisitions are certain - Wiseman has just 15% of the north British
market - comprising the area from Scotland down to Manchester - and 6% of the
UK overall.
Profits for the full-year should increase from #7m to about #10.2m. That would
leave the shares at 138p, compared with the 130p of the #14m rights issue,
trading at just under 15 times likely earnings. This seems cheap given the
medium-term potential.
The interim dividend has been raised 11% to 1p with a 3.2p total in sight for a
2.9% yield.
</TEXT>
