<HEADLINE>Edinburgh awarded heritage accolade</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011961</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH was yesterday awarded World Heritage status by Unesco at its meeting
in Berlin.
Historic Scotland's submission to the judges said the capital represented the
cultural traditions of Scotland.
It had nurtured the growth of Scottish civilisation, its church, law, and legal
system.
The submission continued: ``The juxtaposition of Old and New Edinburgh offers
an outstanding example which epitomises significant stages in human history -
the Renaissance city on the rock versus the rationalist city on the plateau.''
Lord Provost Norman Irons said last night: ``This re-affirms Edinburgh's
position among the leading attractions of world cities.
``I am certain that the tourism industry as well as the city council will be
able to utilise this status to advantage, to highlight the scenic beauty of our
city.''
Councillor Eric Milligan, convener of Lothian region and the new unitary City
of Edinburgh Council, said he was delighted by the recognition.
``It is further confirmation of the city's premier standing in the
international arena and reflects the city's determination to both preserve its
unique and historic environment while developing as a vibrant place to live,
visit, and work.''
A spokesman for Historic Scotland said the recognition resulted from the
submission of a nomination by the Secretary of State for Scotland.
Historic Scotland would discuss ways of continuing and developing the many
positive initiatives taken to conserve the character of Edinburgh as a
distinctive and vital World Heritage Site.
He added that while no new planning controls were imposed by the recognition,
it gave the city a seal of international approval which should help it attract
more visitors.
The spokesman added: ``An important feature in World Heritage sites is the
incentive to protect and enhance them.
``Edinburgh Old and New Towns have been successful in a bid to become a World
Heritage Site largely because these historic areas are protected by
conservation areas which extend well beyond the boundary of the area designated.
``This `buffer zone' is vital to the effective conservation of the setting of
the historic core.''
Perspective 13
</TEXT>
