<HEADLINE>Discovery may bring Aids cure nearer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011962</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCIENTISTS have identified substances in the human immune system which appear
to block the advance of the Aids virus.
Their discovery may explain why some people with HIV do not progress to
full-blown Aids and it could open the door to new forms of treatment.
The substances are a group of polypeptides secreted by CD8-T cells, a family of
white blood cells known for their ability to home in on HIV and other pathogens.
Nine years ago, an American researcher, Dr Jay Levy, reported that certain CD8
cells also appeared to inhibit replication of HIV and he and other scientists
have been trying since then to identify the suppressor factors involved.
Now a team led by Dr Robert Gallo - co-discoverer of the Aids virus itself -
and Dr Paulo Lusso think they have found the answer.
In a report in the journal, Science, next week they will describe how they
identified the polypeptides, or chemokines, which they have labelled RANTES,
MIP1-alpha, and MIP1-beta.
No difference was detected when the chemokines were tested individually but the
scientists were able to establish that RANTES, MIP1-alpha, and MIP1-beta acting
in combination had a suppressor effect on the virus.
Dr Gallo and Dr Lusso are soon to launch toxicology studies with the ultimate
goal of beginning human clinical trials at a new Institute of Human Virology at
Maryland University, of which Dr Gallo is director, and at the San Raffaele
Institute in Milan where Dr Lusso now works.
Controversy is likely to dog the discovery, however. Dr Levy, whose work was
treated sceptically for years, says he has already tried the three candidate
substances and ruled them out but Dr Lusso says that technological progress
enabled him and his colleagues to show up things which Dr Levy couldn't in the
past.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
