<HEADLINE>`Professional witnesses' urged over anti-social neighbours</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011963</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE use of ``professional witnesses'' to give evidence in cases involving
anti-social behaviour by neighbours was advocated yesterday by Scottish Office
officials.
They were giving evidence to the Commons Select Committee on Scottish Affairs
against the background of figures which show that domestic noise complaints
rose from 269 in 1980 to 1939 in 1992-93, the last year for which figures are
available.
The Scottish Office is examining ways of dealing with neighbour disputes,
including the possible introduction of probationary tenancies, new noise
nuisance measures, the development of mediation schemes and the operation of
eviction arrangements.
The possibility of using professional witnesses - housing management teams or
inquiry agents - was raised by Mr Bill Walker, Tory MP for Tayside North, who
referred to peer pressure and intimidation in neighbour-dispute cases, which
meant one person was reluctant to give evidence against another for fear of
victimisation.
Mr Peter Beaton, director of the Scottish Courts Administration, said the basic
sanction against someone who intimidated a witness was a criminal sanction, but
he accepted this was an area in which authorities had to co-ordinate their
activities to protect witnesses.
Pressed on the matter of professional witnesses, Mr John Ewing, a senior civil
servant from the Housing Division of the Scottish Office, said: ``It is an area
worth all authorities exploring more fully.''
The committee was told that consideration still was being given to how
probationary tenancies would work. The Government appears to be moving towards
a situation where such tenancies only would apply to tenants with a previous
history of anti-social behaviour.
A suggestion from Tory MP Terry Dicks (Hayes and Harlington) that all the bad
tenants should be placed in one location - an idea that has been tried before -
was rejected by the officials. Mr David Belfall, from the Scottish Office
Housing Division, said: ``We have had experience in Scotland of some areas
attracting a very unwelcome reputation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sales fall after `mad cow' warning</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011964</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BEEF sales dropped by almost 5% last month compared to November last year, the
Meat and Livestock Commission said yesterday.
The drop coincided with a World in Action TV programme which claimed that 600
BSE-infected cows were being eaten each week in the UK. The commission is
blaming public fears over BSE - ``mad cow disease'' - for part of the November
slide, which comes after a few months of marginal growth in the beef market.
No figures are yet available for the week since neuropathologist Sir Bernard
Tomlinson added his voice to fears over beef. In the four weeks up to November
20, sales of all beef products - including the offal implicated by some
scientists in the human form of ``mad cow disease'', CJD - were down by 4.8%.
October's figure was 0.15% up on 1994 and September sales were 0.1% up on the
year before. August sales were down 14% but the commission attributes that to
the unusually hot weather which put people off the idea of a roast joint.
The commission has launched a poster and leaflet campaign to reassure butchers'
customers and has contacted schools and councils. A commission spokesman said:
``The scare over BSE must have some bearing on November's figures. Whether it
is entirely to blame or whether it is a natural blip, as people save their
pennies for Christmas, we don't know. It's probably a bit of both.
``The commission accepts the findings of those people who are actually engaged
in research into BSE and CJD, and that does not include Sir Bernard Tomlinson.
We are led to believe by those people involved in the research that beef is
safe.''
</TEXT>
