<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Glut of the cards costs brave Rangers Gascoigne puts himself in the European cold</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>James Traynor, chief sports writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011965</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Borussia Dortmund   2
Rangers   2
ON a bitingly cold and inhospitable night when to stand still for longer than
five minutes meant the blood might have frozen solid, Rangers, as they had done
throughout the Champions' League series, ran about a lot. Again, however, the
endeavour of the Scottish champions was not enough.
Also, on a night when three of their players - Paul Gascoigne, John Brown and
Alan McLaren - had been relieved of anxiety over a police inquiry into their
behaviour during a premier-division match against Aberdeen last month, the
Ibrox club's disciplinary record was blackened.
Gascoigne was ordered off late in the match in the Westfalen Stadium,
apparently because he could not bite his tongue. He seemed to run alongside the
referee, Manuel Diaz Vega, after the Spaniard had refused to give a decision in
Rangers' favour, and it was perhaps inevitable that the match official would
round on the player, who had been booked in the first half for a foul on
Andreas Moller.
The midfielder, whose fragile temperament must be a concern for Rangers'
manager Walter Smith, is likely to face at least a one-game suspension when
Rangers next play in European competition. Smith would only say: ``The player
will have to look at himself because his dissent is happening too many times.''
Rangers' disciplinary record in this competition has been dismal. Gascoigne
becomes Rangers' fifth player to be suspended, and follows Gordon Durie and
Gordan Petric, who both collected two cautions, and McLaren and Alex Cleland.
These two were given bans after having been ordered off in Champions' League
matches, and Rangers also finished Group C with players each on one caution.
On top of that, it must be remembered that David Robertson, booked twice
against Famagusta in the preliminary rounds, also missed the opening match
against Steaua Bucharest.
En route to Dortmund, Smith had expressed a degree of anxiety that a number of
his players were on the threshold of suspension, but he never expected to see
Gascoigne being dismissed. The manager was satisfied with the team's
performance, and confirmed Gascoigne's red card was for dissent.
``It was disappointing to have that happen,'' he said, before stressing that he
was unwilling to discuss publicly what action ``if any'' will be taken against
the English internationalist.
Looking back on the team's six matches in Group C which yielded only three
points, the manager said: ``It was a very difficult tournament for us and we
could have done better had it not been for some injuries.''
Smith had been concerned beforehand about the condition of the pitch which was
rock hard and treacherous and he pointed out: ``I think UEFA will have to take
a look at the Champions' League.
``If they are going to have a competition of this magnitude at this time of the
year, they will have to look for better conditions.''
The evening had started in promising fashion for Rangers when Brian Laudrup
gave them an early lead, but the Germans, seven of whom were clad in black
tights to fend off the cold, responded in typical fashion scoring through
Andreas Moller and Karl Heinz Riedle before Durie equalised six minutes from
time.
That goal helped send the Rangers fans - they were approximately 3000 in number
- away with a smile although they, too, can only be concerned about Gascoigne
and the manner in which Rangers have struggled to impose themselves at this
level.
It was a Gascoigne pass which split a rather static and square Dortmund
defensive line and set up the opening goal in 10 minutes.
Miller read Gascoigne's intentions well and was able to take possession deep
inside the opposition's territory before drawing the German keeper, Stefan
Klos, from his line. The young Rangers player then squared the ball to Laudrup,
who arrived in the centre of Dortmund's box and knocked the ball into the empty
net.
Six minutes later, Dortmund had equalised. Richard Gough rose and headed out a
pass played from deep, but the ball fell to Andreas Moller who kept his balance
well and hit a powerful, low shot which beat Andy Goram.
Gascoigne went in heavily against Moller and the Rangers player was given his
second caution of this Champions' League series. Much worse was to follow for
him in the second half as he saw red for that dissent.
Miller also was booked in the first 45 minutes after he had tripped Carsten
Wolters.
While the risk of playing Karl Heinz Riedle - back after a six months' absence
- appeared obvious, the striker's composure was exemplary only two minutes into
the second half when he put his side in front. Heiko Herrlich delivered the
ball from the left into Rangers' box where Gary Bollan had to re-adjust his
stance, but lost his footing in the process, allowing the ball to carry all the
way to Riedle. His low shot was powerful and true.
A couple of minutes after Gascoigne had been sent off, Rangers made a change,
taking off Cleland and sending on Ian Durrant, but a goal behind, a man down,
and time running away from them, the Ibrox side appeared forlorn.
Dortmund were fully aware that all they had to do was keep possession and they
did not seem perturbed in any way when McCoist took over from Miller eight
minutes from time. The home side also made a second change when the South
American Ruben Sosa was sent on in place of Martin Kree.
Despite their problems, Rangers managed to leave their fans in good spirits
after Durie scored the equaliser six minutes from time. Laudrup's cross from
the right was mis-hit by McCall, but the ball fell to Durie, and he made a
thoroughly professional job of beating Klos.
BORUSSIA DORTMUND - Klos, Reinhardt, Kree, Freund, Franck, Berger, Wolters,
Zorc, Riedle, Moller, Herrlich. Substitutes - de Beer, Kutowski, Sosa,
Tretschok, Arnold.
RANGERS - Goram, Clelland, Robertson, Gough, McLaren, Bollan, Miller,
Gascoigne, Durie, McCall, Laudrup. Substitutes - Durrant, McCoist, Salenko,
McGinty, Scott.
Referee - M Diaz Vega (Spain).
Legia Warsaw (Poland) v Panathinaikos (Greece).
Nantes (France) v Spartak Moscow (Russia).
Real Madrid (Spain) v Juventus (Italy).
Borussia Dortmund (Germany) v Ajax (Holland).
First legs to be played on March 6, second leg on March 20.
</TEXT>
