<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bid to ban boxing fails by one vote</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011966</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MOVE to ban professional boxing was blocked by just one vote in the Lords
last night.
A backbench Bill aimed at outlawing the sport was effectively wrecked as peers
voted by 39 to 38 for an amendment postponing it for six months.
However, minutes before the result was announced, Labour's Lord Taylor of
Gryfe, the Boxing Bill's promoter, told the House: ``I will return to this
subject time and time again.''
Lord Taylor, who has tried unsuccessfully twice before to win support for
similar backbench legislation, said: ``I abhor violence and I will pursue that
principle as long as I am in this House.''
Earlier, he said his latest attempt to ban boxing had been prompted by the
death in October of Scottish bantamweight James Murray, two days after a
contest.
However, Tory the Earl of Shrewsbury, proposing the ``wrecking'' amendment,
defended boxing and said: ``I do not believe it is for Parliament to legislate
against sport, for this particular sport or for sport in general. Adaptation
and not banning is the answer.''
Lord Taylor emphasised that he was not trying to ban amateur boxing, only the
professional sport.
He spoke of the catalogue of recent boxing tragedies. ``The recent history in
the ring is not a very edifying experience: Michael Watson is now paralysed and
in a wheelchair, Gerald McClellan is permanently paralysed, Bradley Stone died
just some 18 months ago, James Murray died only a few weeks ago.
``So there should be some concern about that kind of experience and that kind
of record.''
However Lord Shrewsbury said of boxing: ``Of course, it is a contact sport,
which by its very nature carries very serious risks to participants - but so do
all contact sports.''
He said that boxing was not the most high-risk sport and boxers had a
completely free choice as to whether they took it up or not.
National Heritage Minister Lord Inglewood said the Government agreed that
boxers' safety must be paramount: ``But we don't believe the professional sport
should be banned and cannot support this Bill.''
He said there were more deaths and injuries in other sports. Boxing was
voluntary, tightly regulated and popular.
``We believe individuals should have the freedom voluntarily to participate in
the sport of their choice, as long as they're fully aware of the risks'' he
said.
Opposition Front Bencher Lord Donoughue, emphasising that he was voicing his
own opinion, said: ``This is a puritanical measure. It picks out one sport, and
not the most dangerous, and seeks to eliminate individual freedom to choose to
play it.''
Labour former Sports Minister Lord Howell opposed the Bill, saying: ``The
overriding question is not whether we should ban boxing. It is whether we
should prevent the exercise of free will on behalf of citizens who, knowing all
the dangers, nevertheless wish to participate in this sport.''
Lord Airedale (Lib. Dem.) said: ``After the tragedy in Glasgow, every spectator
needs to say to himself: if I and my fellow spectators didn't enjoy this
entertainment of watching two young men trying to bash each other into
insensibility, that young man who is now dead would still be alive today.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
