<HEADLINE>Firmly slapping down claims of bullying</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stuart Trotter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011967</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Speaker, Miss Betty Boothroyd, yesterday moved to increase her already
formidable authority over MPs by hinting at the fate that might befall serious
offenders.
``As a former Whip myself, I can tell this House that when I used to keep
Members out of a division lobby it was with a single nelson and when I needed
them to go into the division lobby it was a double nelson,'' she fondly
recalled.
Tory MPs were charitably speaking up for potential Labour rebels who had wanted
to vote with the Liberal Democrats and the Nationalists against the 1p income
tax cut in the Budget the previous night. The spirit of Christmas arriving
early perhaps.
These, unnamed, potential rebels had been deterred by Labour whips ``standing
shoulder to shoulder'' at the doors to the division lobbies, claimed Sir Irvine
Patnick (Sheffield Hallam - Con.) sympathetically. As a Government Whip at the
time of the Maastricht Treaty Bill, he must be something of a connoisseur of
intimidation.
Apparently, the principles of some would-be rebels blanched as they approached
the lobby only to see the pleasant Mr Nick Brown (Newcastle-upon-Tyne East),
Labour's deputy Chief Whip, and the amiable Mr Eric Clarke (Midlothian), the
Scottish Whip, standing there.
The Sketch admits to a degree of dereliction of duty on that occasion, chatting
to one or two colleagues in the Press Gallery and not keeping the Chamber doors
to the ``no'' lobby under constant observation.
Nonetheless, anything like a single nelson or an arm lock could surely hardly
have escaped the attention of the media, always on the lookout, as its members
are, for deviations from the normal run of things.
An even more eagle-eyed observer was present and Miss Boothroyd said she had
observed nothing out of order. Mr Robert Hughes (Harrow West - Con.) had an
ingenious answer to that. The intimidators had operated out of the Speaker's
``eyeline'' which is why she had not noticed the ``assaulting, insulting and
menacing,'' which he, having a different ``eyeline'' at his disposal, had seen
happening.
The Speaker remained adamant that she had noted nothing amiss. Nor, she added,
had any MP complained to her about being prevented from voting. As MPs raised
with her matters like the air quality in the Commons and the inadequate means
of attracting taxi drivers to Members wanting to leave the precincts, she felt
sure a serious matter like being prevented from voting would have been brought
to her attention.
This could, of course, underestimate the intimidatory effect of Smiler Nick and
Hard Eric on the weaker brethren and sistern of the PLP, especially with the
ultimate threat of being dragged before Big Donald for the treatment.
All this was more entertaining though not, indeed, as important as Trade and
Industry questions in which almost the only bright moment came when Mr Dennis
Canavan (Falkirk West - Lab.) took up the President of the Board of Trade, Mr
Ian Lang, over his ``unemployment is a state of mind'' remark - a distortion,
said President Lang.
Mr Canavan rammed home his point in the vernacular. With his Galloway and Upper
Nithsdale majority at a modest 2468, did the Minister not have a sense that
``his own jaiket is on a very shoogly nail'', an attack which could only be
properly appreciated, or indeed comprehended, in the Scottish Grand Committee
or a Scottish parliament.
As for intimidation, Mr Dennis Skinner (Bolsover - Lab.), one of the gallant 10
who made it past the custodians of Labour unity, showed the right stuff of
which real rebels are made. ``I spent two minutes with a Whip before I went
in,'' he confessed to the Speaker, ``and I nearly got him to go into the lobby
with me.''
</TEXT>
