<HEADLINE>Scots are  correct to defy Government guidelines on beef products, says association Caterers back schools on BSE</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011968</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCHOOLS across Britain were advised last night by a leading caterers' trade
group to defy Government guidelines and steer away from beef products until the
controversy over ``mad cow disease'' was resolved.
As Agriculture Minister Douglas Hogg continued to insist British beef was
``wholly safe'' and said parents should be encouraging children to eat it, two
top private schools in Scotland defended their decision to take beef products
off their menus.
The row comes as new figures reveal that beef sales in Scotland have fallen by
about 3% over a year.
The controversy has also involved the BBC, which said it had ``apologised
unreservedly'' to the makers of Bovril after mistakenly using the brand name on
a BBC helpline, said to be advising people to avoid beef products.
A BBC spokesman said one operator had mistakenly mentioned Bovril when he
intended to use the more generic term stock cubes as the kind of beef products
some scientists believe may carry some risks.
In the light of the controversy over bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), or
``mad cow disease'', Mary Erskine School and Fettes College, both in Edinburgh,
have said beef offal products would be taken off their school menus.
The move has been backed by the Local Authority Caterers' Association, which
said school caterers should consider using more chicken, turkey, and pork until
the controversy was resolved.
The move came as a political row erupted over the Government's handling of the
latest BSE scare.
Labour Shadow Agriculture Minister Gavin Strang accused the Government of doing
`` too little, too late''.
Mr Strang said: ``You cannot blame people for erring on the side of caution,
because the Government have been slow to act to combat the alarm on this
issue.''
Mr Hogg, who visited London's Smithfield meat market yesterday in an attempt to
boost the beef industry, maintained the scare was unfounded.
He said he was furious at the BBC helpline on BSE and said he was ``absolutely
certain'' British beef was safe.
Meanwhile, the Edinburgh schools explained why they had taken beef products off
their menus.
Deputy head of Mary Erskine School, Ms Norma Rolls said the beef products would
be off their menu until Christmas. ``We have taken that decision to give us
time to review the situation,'' she said.
Mr Cameron Thaw, bursar at Fettes, said it had ``adopted the new menus in the
light of perceived problems''.
A policy has been drawn up by the college that whole beef would continue to be
served in the refectory but ``pies, patties, sausages, and the like, made from
beef'' would not be served for the time being.
Alternative dishes for those who were nervous about eating whole beef would
always be available, said the bursar.
He described the school's approach as both cautious and responsible. The policy
will be reviewed once the scare is over, or further guidelines are issued from
official sources, he stated.
``We have not excluded beef because we think it is an important part of the
nutritious diet for pupils at the college, which operates a cafeteria system,''
said Mr Thaw.
A spokeswoman for the Scottish Council of Independent Schools, an advisory
body, said each school would decide its own policy and what was in the best
interests of their pupils.
``I can't make global pronouncements but I can say we have not had any parents
in touch with us about the issue. We also have had no contact from the Scottish
Office.
``We would give advice to schools but any decision on pupils' nutrition would
be taken internally.''
Last night, a Scottish Office spokesman said there were no guidelines on what
should be on menus at state-run schools. ``That is a matter for local
authorities to decide for themselves,'' said a spokesman.
The spokesman re-iterated the Government view, that there was no evidence of a
link between BSE disease in animals being transferred into humans.
Scottish Office figures show that the number of cases of BSE in animals in
Scotland has been falling since its peak in 1993. In that year, 2208 cases of
mad cow disease were identified.
The following year, that figure had fallen to 1326 and, up until November 17 of
this year, 514 cases had been identified.
The Scottish Office said the outbreak of BSE started from the use in animal
feed of ruminant protein derived from sheep affected by scrapie. The spokesman
said strict controls of the movement of animals and other new measures had
helped keep the disease under control.
Meanwhile, the brain expert whose warnings on BSE triggered the latest scare,
said he would be outlining his concerns to the Government in the next few days.
Neuropathologist Professor Sir Bernard Tomlinson said he would be writing to
the chairman of the committee which advises the Department of Health on BSE.
</TEXT>
