<HEADLINE>Celtic in move to keep Collins</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011969</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE chances of John Collins continuing his career at Parkhead next season
increased yesterday with the news that Celtic manager Tommy Burns has
recommended a package deal to the board to be offered to the player before his
contract ends next summer.
Scottish internationalist Collins at one time during the season suggested that
the club was nudging him towards the exit door, but the differences between the
parties seem to have eroded.
Collins has been in tremendous form and his consistency of performance has
delighted the management. ``There has never been any question that we want to
see John stay with Celtic,'' said assistant manager Billy Stark, ``and we will
be delighted if this recommendation means he will sign a new contract here.''
Stark also took time to express his astonishment at reports which claimed
Celtic had bid #1m for Wolverhampton Wanderers striker Steve Bull. ``We once
made an inquiry about him, just as we have done with a number of players, but
Graham Taylor, who was the Wolves manager at the time, indicated that the lad
was very much a home-loving boy and would not leave Wolves. We never got near
the stage of considering a bid.''
In more positive mode, Stark was able to confirm that midfield man Phil
O'Donnell, who last played in October against Paris St Germain, is moving into
contention for a place in the side to meet Hibs at Easter Road on Saturday.
``He has had three games in the reserves now and is running freely,'' said
Stark, ``and it would be lucky for us if he could come back at the time Peter
Grant goes out on suspension.''
Meanwhile, Celtic have been given the go-ahead to open the temporary stand,
capacity 3000, recently erected.
The Strathclyde Safety for Sports Grounds committee have granted a certificate
for the temporary structure which will be open for the first time on Tuesday at
Paul McStay's testimonial against Manchester United.
It will increase the capacity of the re-developed ground to just more than
37,000.
q WILLIE Furphy is a spy in the Highlands for Albion Rovers. The Division 3
club will meet Deveronvale on Saturday in the opening round of the Tennents
Scottish Cup.
Furphy is an important player with Ross County, having spent a spell in the
Highland League. But he also trains with Albion Rovers each week.
Cliftonhill manager Jimmy Crease said: ``Willie knows the Highland League and,
as he is still with Ross County and up north regularly, he hears what is
happening. I have been quizzing him and have picked up information.''
</TEXT>
