<HEADLINE>Grampian officer is scapegoat, dealer tells High Court</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011970</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CONVICTED drugs dealer claimed yesterday that a Grampian Police officer
facing charges of corruption was a scapegoat and other officers should be
sitting beside him in the dock.
Ronald Cormack - a prisoner serving 15 years for drug offences - was giving
evidence at the High Court in Aberdeen where Police Constable Neil Cooper
denies corruption charges.
Under cross examination by Mr Kevin Drummond QC, for Mr Cooper, Cormack was
asked if he did not like the police. He replied: ``I have nothing against the
police in general but there are some police officers who are bigger criminals
than those walking the streets.
``I feel sorry for Neil. He is being made a scapegoat.
``There should be others beside him.''
Asked to name them, Cormack said: ``Hamish Moir should be sitting there facing
serious charges.''
Cormack earlier told the court that when he stopped a financial agreement with
Mr Cooper, he continued to receive information about police activities through
his friend Mr Bill Smith, said in court to be a police informant, who had
obtained it from two other Grampian Police officers, Mr Hamish Moir and Mr
Colin Clark.
He also claimed he received information through ``pillow talk'' which a friend
had with an ``undercover'' policewoman.
He insisted, however, that Mr Cooper had been a source of information for which
he had paid.
Earlier, Cormack said he made incriminating tape recordings of conversations he
had with Mr Cooper ``as an insurance policy.''
However, Cormack said the tapes, along with 1000 rounds of ammunition and part
of a gun he used in an assault, had disappeared when he was arrested.
Mr Cooper is accused of three corruption charges involving Cormack, including
accepting #6000 and other payments from him for details of police intelligence
and surveillance operations.
Mr Cooper has lodged a special defence to the charge of accepting money
claiming the offences were committed by police officer Mr James Grimmer, of
Kinmundy Avenue, Skene.
Cormack said he had recorded meetings and telephone conversations between
himself and Mr Cooper who, he alleged, had supplied information about
surveillance operations on Cormack and the names of police informants.
Asked why he had tape recorded the conversations, he replied: ``It was
insurance. I didn't trust Neil Cooper. Just in case - insurance against being
set up.''
Asked if he was suggesting that the Scottish Crime Squad had been involved in
the disappearance of the tapes he said: ``It could easy be. Officers from the
Scottish Crime Squad lied in this box at my trial.''
``They (the tapes) didn't exist,'' Mr Drummond suggested. ``They do exist but
where they are I don't know,'' Cormack said.
Cormack said he ended his association with Mr Cooper early in 1994 but
continued to receive information from other police officers through Mr Smith.
He denied ever having told his business partner Ian McLaren that the policeman
he was paying for information was a Sergeant called Grimmer.
``Did you tell him the sergeant had a gambling problem and a wife who liked
spending money,'' Mr Drummond asked him.
``I cannot recall that,'' Cormack replied.
He said he had given his wife a ``bug'' which he had detected in his garage
premises and she was to give it to his lawyer to put in the bank as part of his
defence if he was every arrested.
He said he was convinced the device had been planted illegally by the police
and was sure there were others in the premises.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
