<HEADLINE>Crawley answers the England call</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011971</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN Crawley will fill the England No.3 spot for today's match against Boland.
He replaces Mark Ramprakash and now looks certain to keep that place when the
Test series resumes in Durban next week.
Crawley started with an innings of 85 against a South African Invitation XI at
Soweto, then made 108 against Border in East London before taking 90 off Orange
Free State.
Good form against provincial sides is no guarantee of Test success, however.
Ramprakash began the tour well - then made nine, four, and nought when Allan
Donald and co provided the opposition.
Mike Atherton will sit out the four-day game against Boland. Devon Malcolm,
Angus Fraser, and Dominic Cork are also rested. The England team is:
Stewart (capt), Smith, Crawley, Thorpe, Hick, Russell (wkt), Watkinson, Gough,
Illingworth, Illot, Martin.
q BRIAN Lara claims that his dispute with the West Indies management could
strengthen the team. Lara says that the dispute ``is a very small matter, but I
hope my stand can bring everything out in the open.''
He withdrew from the World Series Cup tour after he was fined for being absent
without permission for three days during a summer tour of England. His
withdrawal from the tour shocked fans worldwide and prompted debate about a
lack of discipline on the West Indies team.
Lara said: ``My issue is small and hopefully next Friday when the West Indies
board meet they could address the real facts and what's facing West Indies
cricket,'' he said. There is precedent for governments intervening in cricket
controversies. Trinidad's prime minister, Basdeo Panday, has said that ``if it
becomes necessary, government could become involved in resolving the matter.''
</TEXT>
