<HEADLINE>SNP schemes aim to give winter warmth to elderly</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011972</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish National Party yesterday claimed to be leading the way in the
fight against fuel poverty, with measures worth #1.7m being implemented this
winter by the councils it currently controls.
In West Lothian District, for example, 19,000 pensioners will receive a #30
payment equal to about three weeks' fuel costs.
Speaking in Aberdeen, SNP vice-convener for local government Councillor Maureen
Watt claimed that every winter thousands of vulnerable people died as a direct
result of fuel poverty in Scotland.
In a country rich in energy, each of these deaths was entirely preventable, she
said.
Because of this the SNP had schemes in Grampian region, Tayside and West
Lothian district which directly combated the problem of fuel poverty and energy
plenty.
``I challenge all parties in local government to follow our lead so that the
most vulnerable in Scotland need no longer suffer the misery and danger of a
long cold winter with insufficient fuel'' Councillor Watt said.
Councillor Watt said that in West Lothian the SNP was making payments of #30 to
each pensioner in the district. It had introduced the scheme with #10 payments
three years ago and through careful budget management was now able to increase
the sum to #30 at a cost of #600,000.
Tayside Region's SNP leader Councillor Ewan Dow said that over #1m was being
spent over two years in combating fuel poverty in the area. This year's
comprehensive package would contain a number of measures including free checks
to ensure all benefits were being claimed and the waiving of charges for
meals-on-wheels and lunch clubs over the winter months.
Last year, he said 6000 benefit checks had been carried out and more than
#50,000 worth of free meals had been provided.
Councillor Joyce Stewart, Grampian's social work convener, said this year's
#325,000 package would include benefit checks and voluntary organisations as
well as local authorities would be able to waive lunch club and
meals-on-wheels' charges. Applications would also be invited to a fuel fund
worth #30,000.
</TEXT>
