<HEADLINE>Ferguson back in action after court reprieve</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE McKAIN and IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011973</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH international striker Duncan Ferguson will return to English
premiership action on Monday while he waits for a date to be arranged for a
further court hearing which will argue the merits of the 12-match ban imposed
on him by the SFA.
Ferguson, who was transferred to Everton by Rangers for #4.3m a year ago, had
his suspension put on hold by Lord Prosser at the Court of Session in Edinburgh
after argument for a judicial review was made by the player.
The striker was released recently from Barlinnie Prison after having served 44
days of a three-months sentence following an assault on Raith Rovers defender
John McStay in a match at Ibrox in April, 1994.
The reprieve means that Ferguson will play in a reserve match specially
arranged against Newcastle United today, and if he comes through unscathed, he
is likely to play against West Ham United on Monday.
Everton had insisted that the player had been punished twice for the same
offence, but the judge said he was not impressed by that argument. However, he
did agree to a full hearing as he felt there was a question of interpretation
at stake, and the matter should be investigated further. That is not likely to
take place until well into next year.
Ferguson's lawyer, Leonard Wallace, argued that the SFA rules stated that the
committee could impose ``additional'' punishment on a player who had misbehaved
during play, but Ferguson had not been cautioned or sent off during the game
and no report about it had been submitted to the SFA.
Philip Brodie QC, representing the SFA, said his interpretation of the use of
the word ``additional'' meant ``other'' and if Mr Wallace's understanding of it
was correct, then any on-the-field offences missed by the referee or the
linesmen could not be dealt with by the committee.
After having been presented with two hours of argument by lawyers representing
Ferguson and the SFA, Lord Prosser made it clear that he was sceptical about a
submission that the player had been ``tried'' twice for the same offence.
The judge suggested that this was the most dubious of Mr Wallace's arguments.
He said that half of the people in the country had written contracts providing
that a person found guilty of a criminal offence would be sacked.
He also gave the example of a doctor who raped a patient being tried by the
courts and subjected to professional disciplinary procedure. But he felt that
Mr Wallace had presented a stateable argument on the interpretation of the
disciplinary rules under which the player was suspended.
Ferguson is ultimately seeking a judicial review of the ban.
Meanwhile, the news of the suspension being lifted - he still has seven games
to serve - was greeted with predictable enthusiasm on Merseyside.
Everton captain Dave Watson said that it had given everybody at the club a
lift. He added that Ferguson had been in the thick of a practice match when
news from the court reached the club. ``He was having a hard time in training
when he got the call to go up stairs. He said he was just delighted to get out
of training. But seriously, we are delighted at the news.
``The lads are pleased for him because he has worked very hard since coming out
of jail. This seems to be his bit of a break and I'm sure he'll grab it. ``When
you train all week and there's nothing at the end, it does get you down a bit.
He's got something to look forward to now. The reserve game tomorrow will
probably get 20,000 fans, that's how influential Duncan is on Merseyside.
``If he comes through that match, then there's a chance for Monday. He has a
big influence here. He's a character on and off the field. He gets people
around him playing and apart from that he's an outstanding player himself.''
Ferguson sat out one match for Rangers before the ban was put on hold pending
the court hearing, and then joined Everton after two months on loan at Goodison.
He played in only the first two matches of this season before needing a hernia
operation. The club's last four games, against QPR, Sheffield Wednesday,
Liverpool and Tottenham, have counted towards the suspension.
</TEXT>
