<HEADLINE>The cost of success is a worry for Forest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011974</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOTTINGHAM Forest may have to risk plunging deeper into debt to preserve their
proud status as Britain's lone remaining standard-bearers in Europe this season.
Manager Frank Clark wants to buy reinforcements for his squad, realising that
even the ring of defensive steel which has helped Forest to progress to the
UEFA Cup quarter-finals is unlikely to repel the sides now looming on the
horizon.
Forest's accounts book reveals a secured bank overdraft of #6.5m, and although
they sold Stan Collymore to Liverpool for #8.5m, they almost wiped that out by
buying Kevin Campbell, Andrea Silenzi, and Chris Bart-Williams.
Success in Europe - at the expense of three moderate victims in Malmo, Auxerre,
and Lyon - is pumping some cash back into coffers, and live television coverage
of both third-round legs against Lyon is expected to help generate around #1.2m.
However, the top players Clark would want are valued at astronomical figures.
``I'm always looking to improve the side and I would be interested in any good
players who become available,'' said Clark. ``But you will have to ask the
chairman about finances. I don't know what, if any, percentage of the money we
have made from the UEFA Cup will be available for me to spend.
``The bank manager may like to see the club reduce the overdraft a bit first.''
Bryan Roy will be back from his recent knee operation in time for the UEFA Cup
quarter-finals in March, expecting to rediscover more of his true form which
was diluted this season by the gradual deterioration of a torn cartilage.
Having come so far in Europe in such determined style, Clark's team will
undoubtedly need to step up a gear now - and the big doubt is whether they have
the personnel to do so.
However, one man who should be a big asset to Forest in their quest for greater
glory on the European stage is Scot Gemmill, the Scottish internationalist, and
he would like nothing better than for his club to be drawn against AC Milan in
the quarter-final stage.
Gemmill has his fingers crossed that the Italian team do not slip up in their
second-leg tie tonight at Sparta Prague, leading 2-0 from the first leg.
``I would love AC Milan to get through because it would be a dream to play in
the San Siro in March,'' said Gemmill. ``There are so many great teams left in
the competition, but it would be a bit special to play against Baresi and Co.''
</TEXT>
