<HEADLINE>Funding boost for Scotland</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011975</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By MURRAY RITCHIE
European Editor
Brussels
LABOUR Euro-MP for Lothians David Martin said last night he believed the
European Commission was about to announce the scrapping of a review threatening
continued EU aid to large areas of Scotland.
The money involved goes to so-called Objective 2 areas which are classified as
suffering from industrial decline.
A mid-term review was built into the agreement reached on structural funding
support for needy areas at the Edinburgh summit. There were worries that
Scotland could have lost more than #200m between next year and the end of the
century.
Mr Martin's statement came after an informal meeting of the Council of
Ministers in Madrid last week. Although such meetings do not take explicit
decisions, the Ministers apparently found no support for the principle of a
mid-term review.
Mr Martin said: ``They took the view that it would be premature to start
cutting the programme at this stage when money was just beginning to flow to
the projects.''
He described the news as ``an excellent Christmas present by the Commission''.
</TEXT>
