<DOCNO>GH951207-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hendry hits back to reach quarters</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011976</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WORLD champion Stephen Hendry came from behind to chalk up his fourteenth
successive victory in the second round of the German Open in Frankfurt
yesterday.
The Scot made a second-frame break of 126 en route to a 5-3 win over Malta's
Tony Drago and will face 24-year-old Liverpudlian Rod Lawler in tonight's
quarter-finals.
Hendry lost three of the first four frames and admitted: ``I couldn't afford to
let Tony get any further ahead. It was vital for me to win the fifth frame.''
The UK champion did so, and breaks of 79, 72, and 56 carried him through to the
last eight.
The Scot was only 51 points in front with four reds left on the table -
potentially 59 points - when Drago conceded the eighth frame and the match
after having missed an easy pink.
Hendry said later: ``I'm finding it difficult to get as psyched up for this
tournament as I was in the UK championship. However, I had to slow down the
pace to keep Tony away from the table for long periods. He became very nervous
because of it.''
Lawler, No.45 in the global rankings, caused an upset when he defeated the
world No.5, James Wattana 5-2. Lawler out-potted the Thai, who has yet to get
beyond the last 16 of a ranking tournament this season.
Wishaw's John Higgins had to hit back from 2-0 down in his 5-3 win over Mark
King, who had beaten Ronnie O'Sullivan in the first round. The Scot had runs of
88 and 30 as he reached 4-2 and after King had narrowed the gap, Higgins
cleared the colours in frame eight for victory. Second-round results:
S Hendry (Scotland) beat T Drago (Malta) 5-3; R Lawler (England) beat J Wattana
(Thailand) 5-2; J Higgins (Scotland) beat M King (England) 5-3; D Morgan
(Wales) beat N Bond (England) 5-1.
</TEXT>
