<HEADLINE>Charges at historic sites defended</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011977</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE level of entrance fees to historic sites in Scotland was defended strongly
yesterday by officials from the Scottish Office Development Department.
Attendances at Historic Scotland sites in 1994-95 fell by 110,000 to 2.3m
visitors, but there was a 53% increase in real terms in income from admission
charges.
Pressed on the matter at a session of the Commons Public Accounts Committee
yesterday, Mr Graeme Munro, director and chief executive of Historic Scotland,
said there was an annual review which took account of inflation.
A family of four, for example, would pay #14 for admission to Edinburgh Castle,
and there were special arrangements such as free days for school parties. He
claimed that the charges were at proper commercial rates and were ``very
competitive.''
The committee was told that there are now 6100 scheduled monuments in Scotland,
an increase of 22% since 1991. The broad estimate of perhaps 10,000-12,000
monuments not as yet assessed for scheduling remains unchanged.
</TEXT>
