<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ice rink had no gas-detection system</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011978</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A HIGHLAND ice rink had no ammonia detection system installed when potentially
lethal fumes escaped into the main arena two weeks ago.
More than 200 people, mostly children, were evacuated from Inverness Ice Rink
and a nine-year-old asthmatic boy, John MacLean, of Conon Bridge, almost died.
His heart stopped several times in the incident during an ice hockey tournament
between teams from Inverness and Glasgow.
About 30 people were hospitalised.
The rink reopened for business within hours.
It emerged yesterday that, unlike most other rinks in Scotland, Inverness Ice
Rink had no detection system, which would have set off alarms and prevented the
distressing side-effects of a major ammonia escape, such as burning eyes and
breathing difficulties.
Rink management and owners, Taylor Clark Leisure Ltd, had refused to confirm or
deny whether a detection system was fitted to the refrigeration plant room
where the leak began.
Yesterday, the firm again refused to comment.
The lack of detection equipment was confirmed yesterday by Inverness District
Council's environmental health department who took over the investigation from
the Health and Safety Executive.
However, a spokesman said senior management had agreed to instal the detectors
which would be linked to a mechanical extract ventilation system.
The company also would call in an ammonia expert to give staff and the
emergency services a presentation on the safe use, handling, and emergency
procedures associated with ammonia.
The spokesman added: ``Inquiries are continuing with the full co-operation of
the company and we are keeping our options open on further action. No report
has gone to the procurator fiscal.
``There is no specific legal requirement for an alarm system to be installed in
ice rinks. It all comes down to risk assessment.''
</TEXT>
