<HEADLINE>Major says Europe must recognise dangers over monetary union Premier warns of currency `chaos'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011979</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN MAJOR yesterday issued a blunt warning of ``chaos and difficulty'' across
Europe if mistakes were made over moves towards a single currency.
Many questions about European monetary union remained unanswered, said the
Prime Minister, in Florence for a one-day summit with his Italian counterpart
Lamberto Dini.
``It is not a question of slowing it down or speeding it up, if and when it
proceeds it has got to be right.
``If it isn't right, there will be chaos and difficulty right across Europe,''
he told journalists at a news briefing after the talks.
The Prime Minister said Europe had to be certain what the implications were in
this ``novel procedure'' of single currency.
He said the question was to make sure Europe knew what the implications were of
proceeding if only a minority of member states went ahead.
``The working assumption would be that less than half of the European Union
would meet the Maastricht criteria and be able to proceed by January 1, 1999.''
Europe should examine these issues and ``see what they mean.''
The timing and decisions could affect enlargement of the EU, he said.
Mr Major said he was sceptical at the suggestion of a new form of Exchange Rate
Mechanism outside the single currency, proposed by the Germans.
Italy takes over the EU presidency when the inter-governmental conference on
the Union's political and economic future gets under way next year.
The Italians were angered at the EU summit in September when Germany's finance
minister Theo Waigel said Italy would fail to meet the criteria for the
take-off of European monetary union planned in 1999.
Meanwhile, Tory infighting over Europe resurfaced yesterday with a sharp attack
on former leadership challenger John Redwood by ex-Foreign Minister Tristan
Garel-Jones.
Mr Garel-Jones criticised those urging Mr Major to rule out any prospect of a
single Euro-currency for at least the next six years - likening them to having
a #10 each-way bet on the Grand National and being invited to tear up the slip
for a #20 bet to win.
``I think I would assume that my interlocutor was either a visitor from outer
space who had never been to a racecourse in his life, or that he was a bent
jockey,'' Mr Garel-Jones wrote in the London Evening Standard.
The MP's friends made clear this was a swipe at Mr Redwood, nicknamed ``the
Vulcan'' by his critics.
Sweeping reform of Europe's system for fixing farm support prices was demanded
in the Commons yesterday by Euro-sceptic Tory Tony Marlow.
In a short debate, Mr Marlow (Northampton North) protested that the Common
Agricultural Policy (CAP) discriminated against UK farmers.
The former whipless Conservative demanded free trade in agriculture and the
repatriation of powers to Britain.
Another Tory Euro-sceptic, Mr Christopher Gill (Ludlow), said the CAP was wide
open to fraud, and added: ``I cannot for the life of me understand why a
Conservative Government can be such a willing accomplice to a Soviet-style
central plan.''
q.Mr Major said yesterday that he is to press the EU for a crackdown on the
``pollution'' caused by the illegal drugs trade from South America to Europe.
``What I would like the EU to do is to examine effective help for small
Caribbean states to cut off the shipment of drugs from Latin America to
northern Europe,'' he said.
</TEXT>
