<HEADLINE>Royal couple step out separately</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011981</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Princess of Wales opened the new English National Ballet School in London
yesterday as the Prince of Wales tried his hand at bingo calling before
visiting a new housing estate in Cheshire.
The princess was at ease despite the political tensions surrounding her bid to
become an unofficial ambassador for Britain.
A former ballet dancer herself, she is expected to be put through her paces by
Prime Minister John Major and palace officials before any decision on her
future role is revealed.
The new ENB school in Chelsea, established with #87,000 of lottery cash as part
of a #250,000 funding package, has 31 students, aged 16 to 20, on a two-year
full-time course with fees of #13,000.
Meanwhile, Prince Charles also seemed in his element as he called bingo numbers
on a visit to Chester.
Around 600 bingo regulars packed the Top Rank Club in the town where the prince
was calling the numbers for a special game.
He watched as one of his Prince's Trust officials received a cheque for #75,000
raised by Top Rank at its clubs throughout the country.
When he took the microphone, he said, to laughter from his mainly female
audience: ``I've a ghastly feeling that what you would much rather do is get on
with this game of bingo rather than having me telling you things.''
``Four and nine, forty nine,'' the prince began haltingly, but was soon into
his stride, calling out the numbers with growing confidence.
A couple of gaffes - neglecting to shout ``On its own'' when numbers eight and
nine came up, and ``All the fives'' for 55 - were good humouredly received by
the crowd.
House was called by Mrs Rose Jones, 64, from Chester. Her prize is a trip to
London and a tour of Buckingham Palace.
Earlier, the prince visited Runcorn to see Hallwood Park, the award-winning
Merseyside Improved Houses rented-housing scheme which replaced the infamous
``Legoland'' plastic houses of the town's Southgate Estate.
q A MAN was detained by police yesterday after they spotted him waiting for the
Princess of Wales to leave the English National Ballet School.
It is understood he had been noticed at other public appearances by the
princess and that police were concerned that he could be a stalker.
</TEXT>
