<HEADLINE>Private investors `would switch funds overseas if Labour wins'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011982</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR's concerted attempt to woo the City appears to have failed to convince
private investors, according to a new survey which shows that a majority plan
to divert funds into overseas equities in the event of a Labour election
victory.
The study carried out among 2500 private investors throughout the UK by
Cantrade Investment Management, part of the Union Bank of Switzerland Group,
shows that 70% expect a Labour election victory but that few (15%) trust New
Labour.
At present, about 78% have at least half their portfolio made up from UK
equities, however should Labour come to power they have indicated there would
be a dramatic shift from UK to overseas equities.
Only 12% predict a Conservative win, with 18% suggesting there could be a hung
Parliament.
Only 15% trust New Labour - 47% do not and 28% are undecided.
60% see politics at a fundamental influence on the stock market.
81% would change their investment policy should Labour win the election, with
56% increasing their overseas investmnts and 23% taking out more index-linked
gilts.
57% have yet to adjust their portfolio strategy to reflect the expectation of a
Labour election victory.
Mr Robert Brown, Cantrade deputy managing director, said that although private
investors clearly expected to see a Labour Government after the next election,
more than half had yet to adjust their investment policy accordingly, ``so the
stock market may not be discounting a Labour Government as much as the City
likes to think.''
</TEXT>
