<HEADLINE>Pittodrie game is called off by police with loud-hailers Irvine comeback is halted as northern lights go out</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975011983</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Aberdeen 1, Kilmarnock 1
match abandoned
THE lights went out in a gloomy clash between Aberdeen and Kilmarnock last
night and ended the briefest of comebacks by local hero and multiple sclerosis
victim Brian Irvine.
With just 57 minutes played Pittodrie stadium was plunged into darkness.
Although emergency lighting came on there was no PA system in 75% of the ground
to enlighten the 8500 fans who had braved freezing weather to see the match.
Only the fans in the Richard Donald Stand were kept informed by a public
address system.
After 20 minutes police walked round the pitch announcing by loud-hailer that
the game had been abandoned. Spectators who retain their tickets will be
admitted to the rearranged game.
Aberdeen secretary Ian Taggart said the entire Pittodrie area had been blacked
out by a power failure.
``The referee Jim McGilvray gave us 15 minutes but said if it was going to be
significantly more than that he would have to abandon the game.
``It was very cold, the players had cooled off, and it would not have been fair
to them to put them back out.
``If spectators keep their ticket stubs they will be admitted to the rearranged
game and we will be contacting the Scottish League immediately to see when that
might be.''
He said it was the first abandonment because of a power failure for 14 years.
Aberdeen manager Roy Aitken said they were disappointed because, after losing
an early goal, they had equalised and were playing well when the power failure
struck.
He said, however, that Brian Irvine would be happy to get back into action
albeit for only two minutes and revealed it was a hamstring injury to John
Inglis which prompted the substitution.
His 120 seconds of first team football this season marked a milestone for
Irvine, who was diagnosed as suffering from MS in the close season.
However, he has overcome his initial mild attack and his reserve performances
won him a place on the bench last night and then, to a standing ovation, his
return to the first team.
Aberdeen fans were also assessing the club's new striker, Dean Windass, who had
played from the start but had little opportunity to make a major impact.
One of the most disappointed spectators will have been Spurs' manager Gerry
Francis, who had flown up from London with the object of his interest thought
to be teenager Stephen Glass.
Aberdeen won two corners in the first 90 seconds as they pushed forward against
Kilmarnock, who quickly revealed that attacking was not top of their priorities.
In seven minutes, Paul Bernard started a great move with Shearer back-heeling
his pass to Dodds, but as Shearer collected the return ball a linesman's flag
went up for offside.
In 15 minutes, Shearer did well to snatch a shot from a Grant flick into the
box but the ball went straight into Lekovic's arms.
An Inglis shot from a Glass pass in 22 minutes went just over the bar, and
Michael Watt awaited Kilmarnock's first effort at the Merkland Road goal.
Four minutes later he was stunned when an Ally Mitchell shot slid under him to
give Kilmarnock the lead.
In the visitors' first serious move forward, Gary Holt sent in a cross from the
left and Paul Wright almost got his head to it in the middle of the Aberdeen
defence, which was in disarray.
The ball slipped through to Mitchell on the right and his 12-yard shot easily
beat the keeper.
Two minutes later Kilmarnock burst through the Aberdeen defence again and Watt
took two attempts to save another Mitchell shot.
In 33 minutes Dodds passed to Bernard just outside the box and it took a great
save from Lekovic to deny him the equaliser, but as the first half drew to a
close slipshod play by Aberdeen let Kilmarnock make break after break.
In 50 minutes Whitworth became the first player to be booked after a foul on
Dodds. Just 60 seconds later Shearer equalised with a tremendous near-post
header from a Glass corner on the right.
In 53 minutes Lekovic failed to hold a Jess cross but the danger was cleared as
Aberdeen stepped up the pressure.
Irvine was just settling down to his midfield role when the lights went out.
ABERDEEN - Watt, Grant, Glass, Bernard, Inglis, Smith, Miller, Shearer,
Windass, Dodds, Jess. Substitutes - Hetherston, Stillie, Irvine.
KILMARNOCK - Lekovic, MacPherson, Black, Reilly, Whitworth, Anderson, Mitchell,
Connor, Wright, Brown, Holt. Substitutes - Hendry, Maskrey, Meldrum.
Referee - J McGilvray, Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
