<HEADLINE>Porto fail as Rovers hit four</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011984</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHAMPIONS' LEAGUE
ROUND-UP
FORMER England manager Bobby Robson was a disappointed man last night when his
Porto side, who needed to defeat Aalborg to have any chance of catching Nantes
and reach the quarter-final stage, were held to a 2-2 draw in Portugual.
Porto went a goal down after 10 minutes when Erik Bo Andersen scored, the home
side equalised in 62 minutes. However, the home side's fans were still
celebrating when Jens Christian Madsen scored again for the Danes. But Porto
did not stop going forward and their efforts were rewarded after 75 minutes
when Emerson scored again. But is was not to be for Robson's side.
In France, Nantes drew 0-0 with section winners Panathinaikos, and are through.
Blackburn hit the goal trail in no uncertain fashion at Ewood Park when a hat
trick from Mike Newell and a penalty from Alan Shearer put the English
champions on easy street against Rosenborg in a Group B match, with Steffen
Iversen scoring for the visitors.
However, there was a down side for Rovers when defender Paul Warhurst was sent
off in 51 minutes for a second bookable offence.
He tested the keeper with a drive but seconds later Warhurst took the long walk
to the dressing room following a challenge on Hoftun.
In the same section, Spartak Moscow, already through to the next round, beat
Legia Warsaw 1-0, but with the happenings at Blackburn in mind, the Poles are
safe.
Steaua Bucharest's Ion Vladoiu was sent off after 64 minutes against Juventus
in the same section as Rangers. The match in Romania ended 0-0.
Strikes from Marc Overmars and Ronald de Boer in the opening 22 minutes sent
Group D winners Ajax on their way to success against Ferencvaros in Holland.
Then just after the hour mark, Finnish internationalist Jari Litmanen put the
match well beyond the Hungarians' reach when he netted a double early in the
second half.
Real Madrid will qualify as runners-up from Group D.
