<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Raul is main man for Madrid</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011985</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHAMPIONS' LEAGUE
ROUND-UP
REAL Madrid, Legia Warsaw, and Nantes completed the quarter-final line-up in
the European Cup last night as Ajax, the holders, underlined their status as
favourites.
The Dutch side beat Ferencvaros 4-0, with two goals from Finnish striker Jari
Litmanen, extending Ajax' record unbeaten European Cup run to 17 games.
The Group D winners now play Borussia Dortmund, while Real, 2-0 away winners
against Grasshopper Zurich, must face the 1985 champions, Juventus.
Raul Gonzalez, the 18-year-old striker who found the net twice in Real's latest
Spanish league match, set his side on their way and added another to make sure.
Polish champions Legia Warsaw, runners-up in Group B, play Panathinaikos, who
drew 2-2 with Bobby Robson's Porto last night, and Nantes take on Spartak
Moscow, whose 1-0 away win over Legia left them as the only team in the
Champions' League with a 100% record.
In England, Blackburn Rovers manager Ray Harford praised his players'
commitment after their 4-1 success against Rosenborg.
Rovers, who have disap-pointed in Europe, kept their best play for the last
match in this season's tournament, with Alan Shearer scoring with a penalty
before Mike Newell netted his first hat trick for the club.
The only disappointment for the home side was the sending off of Paul Warhurst.
``We were tentative at the start but I was delighted with our attitude and
application, especially when down to 10-men,'' said Harford.
``Goals change thinking and I was pleased with our third. We must have played
about 27 consecutive passes there.''
Meanwhile, Bordeaux went down 2-1 to Real Betis in their UEFA Cup third round
second leg clash in Spain - but reached the quarter-finals.
</TEXT>
