<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sampras eases to victory in Munich</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011986</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN world No.1 Pete Sampras earned himself $762,500 for a day's work when
he cruised to a 6-1, 7-6 first-round victory over compatriot Patrick McEnroe at
the Grand Slam Cup in Munich yesterday.
After guiding the United States to their Davis Cup triumph last weekend, he can
increase his earnings in the world's richest tennis event to $2.12m by winning
the cup, which brings together the best performers from the four grand slam
events.
The Wimbledon champion won the first set with ease and although his form
slipped slightly in the second, he took the tiebreak 7-1.
Sampras earned $500,000 just for turning up in Munich following his victories
at Wimbledon and the US Open. The losers in the the next round, where Sampras
will play Croat Goran Ivanisevic, are guaranteed $262,500.
American Todd Martin booked his place in the quarter-finals with a 7-6, 6-4
victory over Spain's former French Open champion Sergi Bruguera.
q LYNDSAY Reilly faces the biggest test of her young life next week when the
talented teenager from Currie, Midlothian, jets to Florida to attempt to
qualify for the world junior championships.
The current under-16 and under-18 Scottish hardcourt champion will be playing
on an alien clay surface, but she has won several tournaments in North America
since starting a one-year scholarship several months ago.
She said: ``It's the biggest tournament of its kind in the world and I'm really
excited about it.''
q BRITAIN'S Clare Wood was knocked out in the second round of the Challenger
event in Paris yesterday, beaten 6-3, 4-6, 6-3 by American qualifier Angela
Lettiere.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Row over `political' decision to hold school ballot inquiry</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011987</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT officials are to investigate claims of misinformation and
intimidation over an opt-out ballot at a school in Mr Tony Blair's constituency.
The decision brought a clash at Westminster, with Education Secretary Gillian
Shephard calling on the Labour leader to condemn the alleged behaviour of party
supporters in Hurworth, County Durham.
Shadow Education Secretary David Blunkett hit back, accusing her of instigating
the inquiry for party-political reasons.
The row took a new twist last night when the head who made the complaints,
writing personally to Mr Blair and the Prime Minister, condemned Mrs Shephard's
intervention.
Mr Eamonn Farrar, head of Hurworth School, said he still wanted Government
action to ensure fair opt-out ballots in the future. However, after a
bitterly-fought local campaign, he said he did not want his school to be a
political football.
``The governors never asked for an investigation and we don't want one. We want
a line drawing under this now,'' he said.
Parents at Hurworth School voted two-to-one in a ballot counted earlier this
week not to apply to remove the school from the control of Durham County
Council. However, Mr Hurworth says he believes the ballot was swung by a
campaign of intimidation and misinformation by local Labour activists.
A spokeswoman for the Labour leader said last night: ``Tony Blair has no
evidence to stand up claims of intimidation. But if there were such things
going on, he entirely dissociates himself from them and anybody with any
evidence should present it to the inquiry.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000140</DOCNO>
