<HEADLINE>Strikers win support from Labour MPs in Europe</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From MURRAY RITCHIE European Editor in Brussels</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011988</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR in Europe yesterday gave its formal support to the French strikers in a
show of solidarity which could also embarrass Mr Tony Blair.
Veteran left-winger Alex Falconer, Euro-MP for Mid-Scotland and Fife, won
unanimous backing from the European Parliamentary Labour Party for a resolution
backing the industrial action which threatens the future of prime minister
Alain Juppe, and has provoked the worst street disorder for 30 years.
At the same time, the EPLP was split on how to vote in next week's debate in
the European Parliament on whether to approve a customs union with Turkey.
Mr Blair will be unhappy at his party in Europe being so divided on the issue
because, last week, he reportedly promised President Bill Clinton, who supports
the idea, that British Labour - with 62 Euro-MPs - would ease the controversial
trade deal with Turkey through the Strasbourg assembly.
However, Europe's 217-strong socialist group met in Brussels last night and
decided to approve the Turkish deal when the Strasbourg assembly votes on it
next week, but also demanded monitoring arrangements for human rights progress
and continuing democratic reforms.
The proposed agreement has passed all its hurdles in the EU except next week's
European Parliament vote.
Many European socialists are unhappy at the EU approving a deal which will earn
the Turks millions in new trade, while the Ankara government stands accused of
human rights abuses, especially against the Kurds.
Last night, one Euro-MP said of European Labour's reluctance to back the
leader: ``Tony Blair will be fuming about this. It seems we are always accused
of causing him trouble.''
Labour's Pauline Green, the London Euro-MP who leads the European socialists,
was at the meeting which endorsed backing for the French strikers, but there
was no word of whether she joined in the voting.
Mr Falconer made headlines earlier this year when he infuriated Mr Blair by
winning the EPLP's majority backing for keeping Clause 4.
His efforts earned him a scornful denunciation by the leader, who attacked the
EPLP after 32 of its members put their names to a newspaper advertisement
backing the retention of the clause - seen by some as an article of socialist
faith - which has since been jettisoned by New Labour.
Mr Blair attacked the EPLP for its ``infantile incompetence'' which, he said,
had blunted a party policy launch in Europe.
Mr Falconer's resolution backing the French strikers was adopted without
debate, according to Labour officials. It said that ``this EPLP, mindful of the
failure of Thatcherism, supports the French workers in their campaign to defend
their welfare state''.
Earlier, Mr Falconer had written to the French unions expressing his support in
their campaign to prevent welfare spending cuts.
He said: ``During the Maastricht debate, many of us warned that the convergence
criteria would lead to massive spending cuts, which would be unacceptable to
the people of Europe.
``Why should the rest of Europe put up with the disaster of the Thatcher
experiment, which has so patently failed us in Britain? The French, Germans,
and other people of Europe have only to look across the Channel to see the
chaos that the past 16 years of this nonsense has produced.
``In Britain, we have seen recently a growing mood of militancy. In view of the
anti-union laws in this country, it is important that workers combine
unofficially to resist the attack on our welfare state.
``Governments cannot tell workers to invest in private pension and insurance
schemes, when the same workers are being faced with wage cuts. It does not make
economic sense. I support the French people in their struggle and would
encourage all sections of the British working class to do likewise.''
Mr Falconer, 55, a former foundry worker, was a trade union shop steward at
Rosyth naval dockyard before entering the European Parliament. He is known to
be deeply unhappy with the rightwards drift of the Labour Party. There has been
speculation that he will announce his retirement before the next
Euro-elections, which are three-and-a-half years away.
q The parliament's European People's Party, which includes British
Conservatives, voted last night to approve the EU-Turkey deal. But the group
expressed dissatisfaction with Turkey's progress on human rights and said it
must be monitored.
