<HEADLINE>Scots Tories challenged on fuel VAT vote</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BENEDICT BROGAN Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975011989</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S Tory MPs yesterday were challenged by Labour to explain why they
chose not to back a Finance Bill amendment that would have opened the way for a
reduction in the level of VAT on fuel from 8% to 5%.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson has written to each one demanding a
justification for an action he claims betrays Scottish households facing a
winter of home-heating bills.
In Tuesday night's votes on last week's Budget, the Government defeated an
amendment that would have forced a cut in the current rate of VAT on fuel,
which the Government failed to raise to 17.5% last year.
This proved that Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth and the Government could
not be trusted on tax, Mr Robertson said. ``Only Labour stopped him voting VAT
on fuel up to 17.5% last year. On Tuesday night, he refused again to support
those Scottish households who rely on heating in the winter most,'' he said.
``Michael Forsyth is a world expert in hated taxes: first the poll tax and now
VAT on fuel. Labour's top priority is to reduce VAT on fuel from 8% to 5%. This
would save the average Scottish family #22 a year.''
In a letter sent to Scottish Tories including Foreign Secretary Malcolm
Rifkind, Mr Robertson said the Scottish people would want to know why they
voted against reducing VAT on fuel, but backed the abolition of inheritance and
capital gains tax. ``Is it not time that you explained these perverse
priorities?'' he said.
Meanwhile, Liberal Democrat MP Ray Michie criticised Scottish Tory MPs for
backing a Government Budget measure on hydrocarbon oils that will increase the
price of petrol by 3.5p per litre.
She said: ``The Tory Party claims to represent the interests of Scotland's
rural areas and yet they were quite happy to vote for a hike in petrol prices
which will have a disproportional impact upon the rural economy of Scotland.
``The Government's policy is aimed at topping up Treasury funds rather than
preserving the environment. Obviously, the Labour Party is still the party of
the cities and is not prepared to stand up for Britain's remote areas.''
</TEXT>
