<HEADLINE>Moving the deficit to Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975012006</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR editorial said, ``Scots in recent years have persisted in giving the
majority of their votes to any party but the one that sits in authority over
them'' (December 1).
Translated into plain English that means, ``All parties are minority parties in
Scotland''.
They have been since 1955, not by the machinations of Westminster but by the
will of the Scottish electorate in exercising their democratic right to vote
for the parties of their individual choice.
Only in the devolution-inflamed imagination of the Scottish media do Scotland's
voters wheel and turn in unison like flocks of electoral starlings, forming
coalitions against this or for that.
In the real world there is no political consensus in Scotland for any one
party, or against any one party. If Labour were in office today, that would
constitute a ``democratic deficit'' for the 61% of Scottish voters who voted
against Labour in the last General Election.
This minority party situation is not one that would be likely to be changed by
the setting up of a devolved Scottish parliament.
Notwithstanding a decorative frill of additional representation, the most
likely outcome would be the permanent ``democratic deficit'' of Labour in
office in Scotland on the basis of a minority vote, currently 39% of the total
- the transference of a ``democratic deficit'' to Edinburgh, possibly in
perpetuity.
Thanks to Michael Forsyth the devolution argument has lifted to a higher
intellectual level than in recent years. Let us try to keep it there by not
returning to the hyperbolical rubbish of the 1980s.
James Scott,
5 Turnberry Road, Glasgow.
</TEXT>
