<HEADLINE>Music   Sir Alexander Gibson Memorial Concert, Glasgow Royal Concert Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Tumelty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975012010</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WELL, I wasn't going to do any political point-scoring following this
celebration - by the Royal Scottish National Orchestra and Scottish Opera - of
the life of Sir Alexander Gibson. But Dame Janet Baker, in her address to the
packed house at the Royal Concert Hall, started it, and I'm quite happy to pick
up the flag where she set it down.
All the areas of life important to Sir Alex were represented in that great
crowd last night, said Dame Janet: ``His family and friends, his colleagues,
the orchestra he was so closely associated with for many years, the opera
company he founded, and the Scottish audience he served for so many years.
``What hope have the arts in these dark and difficult times?'', she asked,
pointing - as a rallying call - to Sir Alex's commitments to ``excellence and
to Scottish musicians and singers, to whom his loyalty was unswerving''.
He was, she said, ``a marvellous influence on my own career, and on music
internationally''. And Dame Janet referred to ``the treasures he laid at the
feet of his audiences everywhere''.
Two of those treasures - the RSNO which he nurtured and Scottish Opera which he
founded - were onstage, with their current chief conductors, and in their
prime. Both of them - imminently Scottish Opera - are now endangered species,
and the very evidence of what they produced stands as a testimony to their
magnificence and a dire warning of what Scotland will lose should they go to
the wall or be diminished in any way. (And I hope that the dignitaries and
significant movers in the glitzy audience take note of the fact.)
What a display the companies turned on. First on was the explosive Russian,
Alexander Lazarev, who set the pace and the tempo for the night with a
blistering account of Sibelius's Finlandia with the RSNO. I recall, some years
ago, Sir Alex shaking his head in wonder at another Russian who did something
similar; he'd have done the same at Lazarev's scorching account, with the band
playing at white heat.
Then, without a single crunch of gears, the RSNO slipped into Viennese mode for
a momentous account of the first movement of Beethoven's Fourth Piano Concerto
- weighty, controlled, and confident - with chief conductor Walter Weller and
the incomparable pianist John Lill. This great pianist produced for the
occasion an immaculate blend of concentration, poetry, and intellect; solid as
a rock, with Weller reading him like a book.
Weller then let the band off the leash in a stunning performance of Elgar's In
the South Overture, packed with brilliant solos from within the orchestra, and
shining as heroically and epically as one of Richard Strauss's great tone poems.
And then, in the second half, Scottish Opera, its orchestra, chorus, and music
director Richard Armstrong took the stage with extracts from Berlioz's The
Trojans (with soloists Jeffrey Lawton and Anne-Marie Owens) and - rousingly -
Wagner's Mastersingers.
Let's be succinct. Richard Armstrong has fashioned a very fine orchestra here:
extremely well-balanced, with a compact wind section, softly burnished brass,
and - from the strings - a remarkable clarity of ensemble. Their playing, light
and mellow, was heartwarming. And I'm sorry once again to stick it up the noses
of the accountants and politicians (like hell I am) but we really should not
lose this opera orchestra. It's the only one we've got; bloody well pay for it
or lose part of your cultural fabric. The heritage of Sir Alex Gibson deserves
nothing less.
This review appeared in some editions yesterday.
</TEXT>
