<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Theatre   The Jungle Book, Young Vic, London</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Carole Woddis</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975012017</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LAST year's Christmas entertainment by the Young Vic's artistic director, Tim
Supple, produced one of the treats of the season - Grimm's Fairy Tales in a
story-telling version that, paradoxically, became a celebration of total
theatre.
A knockout for young and old alike, it must have seemed a hard act to follow.
But Supple's festive fare for this year runs it very close - a dramatisation of
Rudyard Kipling's Jungle Book that, if tending to be busy where the former
relied on subtle pacing, once again uses its slender resources with terrific
imagination and great satisfaction.
Using every aspect of the Young Vic's in-the-round space, Supple makes
Kipling's tale of young Mowgli and his adoption by the Seeonee Wolf Pack a
gripping adventure tale that, last night at least, kept two-year-olds on the
edge of their seats way beyond their bedtime.
Supple's version interestingly also lets us see the environmentalist and
conservationist in Kipling. ``We be of one blood,'' says Ronny Jhutti's young
``manling'' man-cub (as his adopted family call him) rehearsing the mantra of
jungle law. That Kipling felt huge sympathy with all living creatures from
whom, as humans, we could learn a good deal comes over with unusual clarity and
force.
Most of all though this, like the Grimm Tales, reinforces the art of theatrical
story-telling. Melly Still's red sawdust ring and arching bridge, and Adrian
Lee's wonderful Indian-based music is all the actors need to create their world
while as mother and father wolf, bear, tiger, the howling Bandar-log monkeys,
Kaa the python and the rest, they inhabit their animalistic selves with a
beauty and economy Peter Brook would surely applaud.
</TEXT>
