<HEADLINE>Return to Russia with love</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LESLEY DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975012029</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LESLEY DUNCAN talks to a remarkable octogenarian about a new book in which she
relates the experiences of going back to the troubled land of her birth
TO HAVE a new book published within days of one's ninetieth birthday is an
unusual distinction. It's one that can be claimed by Eugenie Fraser, whose
sequel to her best-selling The House by the Dvina appears next week.
That first book described Mrs Fraser's idyllic childhood in Archangel, in
northern Russia, before the First World War and the Bolshevik Revolution
destroyed traditional Russian civilisation and values - as well as millions of
the country's citizens.
The material was intended originally for Mrs Fraser's sons. She was encouraged
to publish it after her description of her Russian great-grandfather's
unorthodox acquisition of wife and mother-in-law (he bought them) caught the
fancy of her lecturer in an extramural class at Edinburgh University.
Mrs Fraser, the daughter of a Russian father and a mother from Broughty Ferry,
was fortunate to escape back to Britain as a young teenager with her mother and
brother in 1920. But her ailing father was left behind, as well as an extended
family of Tolstoyan dimensions, including the admirable babushka, her Russian
grandmother.
Mrs Fraser's new book, The Dvina Remains, tells the story of her returns to
Russia, in pre and post-glasnost days. It also - through the letters of her
namesake cousin, Evgenie - fills in the often painful family history of those
dark decades of communism.
In the cultured but cosy ambience of her Morningside flat in Edinburgh, and
with kilted husband Ronald in solicitous attendance, Eugenie Fraser defies
time. A bright-eyed, slender woman, she's at once imposing and approachable,
with a mind and memory of undiminished brightness. A slight deafness is her
only concession to age.
She's a little worried about the unorthodox format of her new book, with her
own reminiscences sandwiching a central section of her cousin's letters. She
shouldn't be. The inherent interest of the material transcends any
organisational gaucheness.
The opening chapter deals with her first visit, in 1972, to her native country
after 52 years, many of them spent in India. It was not a happy experience. She
was, as any sentient outsider would be, critical of what she saw - from the
veneration accorded the stuffed Lenin in his Red Square mausoleum to the
devastation and suffering endured by St Petersburg under 70 years of communism.
And at a personal level she met rebuffs from Russians and fellow travellers, no
doubt because as a native-born Russian and fluent speaker of the language she
was a potentially dangerous person to know in these still paranoid times.
Particularly sad was her abortive effort to meet some of her relations in St
Petersburg (still Leningrad then). A woman cousin took to the country to avoid
her. But from this non-event sprang a poignant correspondence with the woman's
brother Evgenie - a noble, gaunt-looking man in the family album that Mrs
Fraser produces.
``I only knew him as a child,'' Mrs Fraser recalls. ``He was like a little
brother to me.'' That early rapport was revived more than 50 years later in his
eloquent letters. Mrs Fraser takes them from a plastic bag - a huge sheaf of
airmail envelopes, all carefully annotated on the front with the theme of their
contents. She has translated them freely.
The letters touch on harrowing matters, including the execution and suicide of
two male relations - tainted in Stalinist eyes with having served with White
Russian forces in the civil war - and the exile of others to Siberia. (Several
family members also died of starvation in wartime Leningrad.)
The letters also offer more humdrum insights into the privations of ordinary
Russians under communism. There are moments of tragicomedy - as when a
razor-sharpener is sent as a present from Scotland and provides a short-lived
business for Mrs Fraser's blind father and young Evgenie.
Sadly, Eugenie and Evgenie never met as adults. Evgenie was dead before Eugenie
returned again to the land and place of her birth in 1990. This new visit was
prompted indirectly by the success of her first book, which as well as being
translated into Swedish, Dutch, and Finnish has a transatlantic edition. An
American woman with the splendid handle of Mrs Charles Bragg II presented a
copy to the Archangel library. Invitations to its author ensued.
Glasnost had made its mark and this time, and on a subsequent visit to
Archangel in 1992, Mrs Fraser was feted. She was also the subject of television
programmes.
Was she glad to have returned to Russia? ``Very glad; overwhelmed,'' she
replies. There is a qualification, though. She had hoped that some schoolfriend
might get in touch, especially after the television broadcasts, but ``I never
met a single soul my own age - I was too old for them!''
q The Dvina Remains by Eugenie Fraser is published next Thursday by Mainstream
at #12.99.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Enter young talent</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Keith Bruce</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975012036</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Keith Bruce talks to budding writers about to take their work centre-stage
IF THERE is to be any addressing the complaints of Scottish playwrights David
Greig, Stephen Greenhorn, Iain Heggie et al that their vocation is not taken
sufficiently seriously, then there is only one place to start.
The Scottish Young Playwrights' festival has been running as an offshoot of
Scottish Youth Theatre for almost as long as SYT itself. Now biennial as part
of the company's established cycle of activity, the invitation to budding
writers for the stage was this year promoted through the pages of The Herald.
Of some 40 completed applications, a shortlist of four was selected. Aged from
16 to 21, they are all male, but you can forget any thoughts of sexism. The
judging panel, including playwright Lara Jane Bunting, herself a graduate of
the scheme, were all female.
So too are the two writers - Vivian Adams and Susan McClymont - who are working
with the winners this week in an intensive process of bringing their scripts
towards the stage. Based at the Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama, the
writers are working with directors Robin Wilson and Andrew Dawson and 20
students from the drama school's second year. Although the focus of the work is
firmly on the script, it will result in rehearsed readings of 20 minutes from
each of the pieces at the Old Athenaeum a week today as part of SYT's winter
festival.
The quartet could hardly be more varied. Douglas Maxwell is from Girvan, 21 and
a Stirling University graduate who wrote a stage adaptation of Hogg's
Confessions of a Justified Sinner as his part of his honours English degree,
and formed the student musical society, staging Grease and West Side Story. He
applied on a coupon from The Herald.
Suggest to him that this project lacks the cynicism often encountered in the
professional stage, and he feels compelled to inject it. He claims to be
resisting the temptation to get a job, being reluctant to adopt the
Government-approved label of ``graduate job-seeker''.
``All the new playwrights and philosophers are out there wearing badges that
say: `My name is Bob, how can I help you'.''
Gavin Sayers, 18 and from Dundee, is hunched in drainpipe black jeans and long
black hair. He read about the competition in The Big Issue. He is pretty clear
about being unemployed, and less than impressed, in his meek way, with the film
and televsion companies who have returned his writing without any indication of
why it has been rejected. His ambitions run to independent film production and
Orwell, Steinbeck, and Pinter are among those he admires.
``It's uplifting to be taken seriously as a writer,'' he confesses, shyly.
James McNulty is 19 and from Kilmarnock and eager to consign to the past his
time with the Palace Youth Theatre, although they staged his Caveat Emptor. An
admirer of Chris Hannan, Iain Banks, Samuel Beckett, and James Joyce, he is now
at Glasgow University reading theatre studies and philosophy.
His next work, Tricolour, will feature at the Bedlam's Febfest in Edinburgh,
and it and the SYT piece, The Sunmaid, are set for future performance at the
Cottier Theatre.
``This is so useful because it is the opportunity to work and speak with
professionals. After the first read through I was asked a lot of questions and
that helped me get things straight in my own head. This time it is the emphasis
that has shifted rather than the script that has changed, but it will make a
huge difference to what I do in the future.''
Bram Gieben is a 16-year-old polymath for James Gillespie's school, who has
come to writing from acting classes with SYT, has done a spot of directing at
school, and plans to go the RSAMD unless someone wants to sponsor him to go
film school in New York. (Just send the cheque to The Herald and I'll forward
it.) Although he is too young to be permitted to see any of his films, he
claims Tarantino as an influence, alongside Canadian Brian Drader, whose work
he heard at a rehearsed reading at the Traverse.
His piece, Billy Joe, is a short David Lynch-esque tale of a Scots family
Robertson in an 80s housing scheme. A tale of mortality, urban violence, and
abortion, he maintains, based on the Bobby Gentry hit Ode to Billy Joe, which
he should be too young to know.
That piece and Maxwell's The Chameleon's Play are paired for one group of 10
actors working with McClymont and Dawson, while Wilson and Adams work with The
Sunmaid and Sayers's The Trouble With Mr Charlie. The latter is about a chap
whose imaginary childhood friend returns to him and leads him to confront the
terrors of his past, while Maxwell's is a theatrical farce that involves the
killing of Oscar Wilde and acknowledges the influence of Dario Fo, Joe Orton,
and Dad's Army.
McClymont says that the process which the young writers are going through in a
mere 10 days is similar to the reality of bringing new work to the stage with a
professional theatre company.
``I'm dead jealous because the actors really like these plays,'' she added.
Adams says they are putting the process of years into a nutshell, but if
Scotland wants a reputation for its playwrighting it will have to take young
writers seriously.
``What is important is that what is learned is theatrical. To talk of structure
and objectives is not imposing a formula - it has to be opening doors and
giving the writers the tools to get across their next idea even more strongly.''
Just as interesting will be the question of which of these four diverse talents
will produce the piece about the four young writers who are thrown together and
feted at a young age, having their talent nurtured by enthusiastic
professionals towards that all-important first night. On the other hand,
perhaps not.
n Scottish Young Playwrights, 7.30pm Thursday December 14, Old Athenaeum,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951207-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951207-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>951207</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Amazing new theory of self-determination</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>diary</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975012169</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
At this season of impending media overload it is traditional for the August
Economist newspaper, taking a break from its usual demands that the Govemment
should slash spending here or squeeze budgets there to produce a magazine
previewing the year ahead - a kind of Old Moore's Alamanack with long words and
bar charts.
Interestingly, in recent times the paper has made repeated efforts to predict
that next year, for certain sure, something  sensational will happen vis-a-vis
Scotland  and the constitutional issue. Each year, like most  in the punditry
profession, it is entirely mistaken. Shame.
With that in mind, perhaps, the Economist's  god-like commentators have been
more canny this time round. Outlining the various positions of the party - no,
we don't propose to go through all that again - it tries a novel approach.
The real battle in 1996, it states, " will be for the English hearts and minds.
In the run-up to the next election, can the Tories persuade enough Englishmen
that Scottish devolution means Scottish independence (and that would be a bad
thing)?"
Now why didn't Michael Forsyth think of that? Our prediction for 1996 is that
this amazing new theory of self-determination might just qualify for nomination
as the West Leicestershire Question.
With one voice
Lord but that Christmas spirit is catching. Or as the Scots Independent, "the
only true voice of Scotland", puts it in its latest patriotic issue: "The Board
and Editor of the Scots Independent wish all of their readers, regardless of
political persuasion, the Compliments of the Season." And God bless Tony Blair?
Hard to swallow
The evil cunning that goes into the drugs trade sometimes passes all belief.
Take, for example, the case of hapless Paul MacPherson convicted at Inverness
Sheriff Court last week for possession of 1773 of amphetamines with intent to
supply.
In his defence, MacPherson's agent told the court that his client was "quite
green" and not "dealing in the strict sense".  The drugs he explained were
offered on a sale or return basis.
Relieved of 25
Still in the courts, a Stranraer man has been fined 25 at the local sheriff
court.  His offence? Urinating in the street. Tush, so to speak.
Worse than that, the villain committed the offence "in a way likely  to cause
annoyance".  We wait information on the polite way.
Money laundering
Ignoring the fairly obvious fact  that, what with British Europhobes, French
strikes, Italian deficits, and so forth, monetary union may never come to pass,
the Benelux countries have settled on their choice of a name for a future
European currency.
With startling wit and oodles of imagination, Belgium, the Netherlands, and
Luxembourg suggest "Euro" as the name for the dosh of the future when European
leaders make a decision on December 15-16.  The Benelux choice arises,
apparently, because the Germans oppose "Ecu", believing it has "negative
connotations" after the recent monetary instability of recent years.
What the diary wants to know is why anyone thinks "Euro" has a positive image.
Robbed of childhood
In California, meanwhile, one Mrs Billie Jean Matay is suing Disneyland after
she, her daughter and three grandchildren were robbed at gunpoint in the car
park.
Understandably, perhaps, Mrs Matay believes security at the park was lax. But
what really infuriated her, according to the lawsuit she filed this week, was
that while being questioned about the incident by guards her grandchildren were
allowed  to see Disney characters disrobe and "traumatised" by "the reality
that the Disney characters were, in fact, make-believe".
Unlike , we hasten to add, the California legal system.
Still in the Land of the Free, we heard tell of the two firemen and six
volunteers suspended from the bridge in Seat Pleasant, Michegan, after being
involved in a brawl.  The heroes were fighting over who should carry the big
hose into a burning house.
With good cause
Keen to demonstrate that the running of the National Lottery is something more
than just a licence to print millions, Camelot,  the organisers , have taken to
handling out little leaflets  explaining what a wonderful job "you" (that's me
and you) do for good causes every time "you" buy a ticket.
In a rather clever marketing wheeze , the leaflets distributed in Scotland
mention only the Scottish causes - thus side stepping  the rather well-founded
claim that London has done better than most places from the gaming tax - and
might just leave the unwary with the impression that all the dosh is going to
projects in Pollockshields, Plockton and Kirkcaldy.
Equally, the thing somehow entirely overlooks any mention of the profits made
by the organisers themselves.  But as Camelot would doubtless put it, it's all
in good cause.
Mis-herd
There may be older jokes, but we can't think of one.  Teacher  to class "What
do you call a group of angels?"
Little girl at the back: "A herd , miss!"
Teacher: "Whatever gave you that idea?"
Small girl: "It's the carol we're learning, miss!"
Teacher:"What carol?"
Small girl: "Hark! The herd of angel sing."
Worth its weight
Finally, for the Christmas gift that would best express your deepest feelings
for the woman you love, we direct your attention to a sale of dolls, teddy
bears, textiles, trains tinplate toys and so  forth to be held at Phillips the
auctioneers in Edinburgh on Friday.
There, we hear, a "stocky little lady known by collectors as ' the little
wrestler' because of her chubby figure and shapely legs with moulded boots...
is looking for a new home". Just 800-1000 for the stocky lady in your life.
